<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ToughPrincipal     03-29 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tough Principal,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Votes To Deny Principal's Salary Increase</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Elease cq in 3rd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school board voted Tuesday night to
withhold a salary increase in the 1988-89 school year for Joe
Clark, the tough-guy principal at inner-city Eastside High School.
   After meeting in executive session for an hour, the board voted
6-1 to deny Clark an increase on the grounds that he expelled
students from the high school without due process, was
insubordinate in refusing to readmit the students when directed to
do so and failed to maintain proper records and proper reporting
procedures.
   Board member Elease Evans said she voted against the resolution
because she thought the evidence was insufficent.
   Clark was not present, but his attorney, Vickie Donaldson, met
with the board for about 30 minutes and emerged, saying she had
``spoken her peace.'' She did not elaborate.
   Reached at home after the meeting, Clark said he would direct
his attorney to work to reverse the board's decision.
   But he also said the dispute ``was all worth it, because the
entire nation knows what buffoons exist on boards of education. If
it means that I lose an increment (raise) to make sure the nation
is aware of the deficiencies pertinent to ... education, then I
think it only fitting and proper that I accept that outlandish
punishment.''
   The board is still negotiating salary levels for next year so it
is not clear how much money Clark would stand to lose.
   Clark gained fame and plaudits from the Reagan administration
and most of his school's students and parents for his no-nonsense
approach, which included roaming the halls with a baseball bat and
a bullhorn.
   Earlier, the board had considered more severe action against
Clark, such as suspending him.
</TEXT>
