<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--HaitiansIntercepted     03-29 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Haitians Intercepted,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Intercepts Haitians Crowded On Motorboat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-registered motorboat carrying 246 Haitians
was turned back by the U.S. Coast Guard about 450 miles southeast
of Miami, a little more than halfway to the United States, officers
said.
   ``This is the first time in a long time I can think of that
we've picked up a U.S. registered boat,'' Lt. Cmdr. Jim Simpson
said. Officials were still checking records late Monday to
determine ownership.
   A Coast Guard Falcon jet spotted the Miss Kay, a U.S. boat from
Houma, La., on Saturday morning, said Petty Officer Luis Diaz in
Miami.
   A cutter was dispatched to the boat and took the Haitians aboard
for interviews by Immigration and Naturalization Service agents who
were flown in Monday, Simpson said.
   Anyone with a legal claim to enter the United States will be
allowed to do so, but the Coast Guard generally turns back 98
percent of the passengers, he said.
</TEXT>
