<2ND_LINE>AM-Motorcade Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0605,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Dies From Injury Suffered During Presidential Caravan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with funeral; PICKS UP 4th graf
pvs, `Chihuahua Judicial ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican presidential candidate
Manuel Clouthier shifted his campaign schedule and attended the
funeral of a 15-year-old girl fatally injured by a stone thrown at
a Clouthier motorcade.
   About 500 people attended the funeral Mass for Maria Teresa
Ramirez Aguilar, who died Sunday of injuries suffered a week
earlier.
   At the funeral mass, Bishop Manuel Talamas Camandari called for
``civic activism that goes beyond vain ambition'' and ``a better
Mexico in which we all can contribute equally.'' Worshipers
applauded after Talamas' mass.
   Priests are forbidden under the Mexican constitution to espouse
their political views publicly. Clergymen have led several revolts
in Mexican history.
   About 300 people jammed the Sagrada Familia Catholic Church and
about 200 others stood outside, some straining to listen to the
Mass.
   Miss Ramirez, a student at Burges High School in El Paso, Texas,
was hit by a rock as she sat in the back of a pickup truck in a
motorcade trailing Clouthier, candidate for the opposition National
Action Party, from the airport to downtown Juarez.
   Chihuahua Judicial Police arrested five people and were looking
for others. Police alternately described the subjects of their
search as ``cholos,'' or young toughs, or as members of the
militant leftist Popular Defense Committee.
   Committee spokesman Juan Beltran Nunez said Sunday the party
shouldn't be blamed.
   The arrested suspects admitted throwing stones in the area, Jose
Garcia Gutierrez, an attorney with the public prosecutor's office,
told the El Paso Times. A judge will decide whether the suspects
will be tried in the girl's death, Garcia said.
</TEXT>
