<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua-Divisions Bjt   03-29 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Divisions, Bjt,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Say Renegade Contras Continue Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Contra fighters oppose the
cease-fire accord signed by their leaders and the government, and
reports reaching the capital say renegade rebels are staging
attacks in violation of a fragile truce.
   The division between Contra leaders and the fighters was evident
Monday at talks to work out the mechanics of a formal 60-day
cease-fire to begin Friday.
   After Monday's session in Sapoa, Diogenes Hernandez Membreno, a
rebel military commander, told reporters:
   ``I want to tell the Nicaraguan people and the world that the
combatants are not going to put down their arms until Nicaragua is
a democracy.''
   Both the leftist Sandinistas and the rebels declared an informal
truce on March 21, the start of three days of talks that ended with
a document designed to end the more than six-year war. Monday's
meeting was to discuss the location of zones where the Contra
fighters will gather during the official cease-fire.
   The cease-fire agreement does not say whether the Contras must
lay down their weapons. That issue seemingly would be one of the
topics to be resolved during the technical meeting that was to end
today in Sapoa, the same southern border post 90 miles south of
Managua where last week's meeting was held.
   On Monday, a source who has been reliable in the past told The
Associated Press that an evangelical pastor, Enrique Morales, said
there was fighting Friday in the village of Juste in central
Chontales province when rebels engaged Sandinista troops. Two
soldiers reportedly were kidnapped.
   The same source said Radio 15 de Septiembre, the clandestine
rebel station broadcast from Honduras to Nicaragua, reported that
Contras knocked down electric posts Friday in southern Zelaya
province.
   The radio also said there was fighting Saturday in Paiwas, in
the easternmost part of the central province of Matagalpa.
   The Defense Ministry said it did not have any official reports
of combat. But an officer, who spoke on condition he not be further
identified, said: ``It's possible, we know there are some Contras
not in agreement.''
   Witness for Peace, the American-based organization that
documents Contra abuses, said on Monday night it had heard of no
truce violations.
   On Sunday, Interior Minister Tomas Borge said pressure from the
some sectors of the United States and dissident groups within the
Contra ranks were attempting to obstruct the cease-fire agreements.
   A violation of the truce during last week's cease-fire talks was
written off by both sides as a result of poor communications.
   In Sapoa, Maj. Gen. Joaquin Cuadra, deputy defense minister and
army chief of staff, said on Monday there had been ``violations of
the truce of a minor character but we understand that they are due
to the communications problem.''
   A rebel commander attending the Sapoa talks, Walter Calderon,
said it was difficult for both sides to explain the cease-fire
agreement to their troops.
   The Contra fighters reportedly were caught off guard by the pact
signed by rebel leaders who live in Miami. Most of the combatants,
supplied with U.S. goods ranging from uniforms to weaponry, live
the rough life of guerrillas roaming in the northern mountains and
down through the central plains.
   During the past year they garnered some degree of public support
in the hinterlands, where peasants sold food to the rebels and
passed on Sandinista troop information. The war was described by
military experts as stalemated.
   The Contras' military ability grew enormously in 1987 with
air-dropped U.S. supplies that were part of the $100 million
package approved by the U.S. Congress in June 1986. The funding ran
out Feb. 29 and no agreement has been reached on additional aid.
   The loss of American support was said to be one of the main
reasons the rebels agreed to the cease-fire. The Contras agreed in
the pact to accept only non-lethal aid from a neutral organization,
such as the Red Cross. But the Contras also obtained promises from
the Sandinistas for democratic liberties.
   For the Sandinistas, the agreement offers a chance to rebuild a
shattered economy and calm widespread discontent over chronic
shortages and mandatory military conscription.
   The pact calls for the 10,000 or so Contras to move into special
zones during the first 15 days of April. The cease-fire is to last
until June 1. Conversations to work out final details were to be
held during that time, the first to be April 6 in Managua.
   The Sandinistas also agreed to gradually release 3,300 political
prisoners. The first 100 were freed Sunday.
</TEXT>
