<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HemingwayContest 2ndLd-Writethru a0785 03-29 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hemingway Contest, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0785,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ersatz Hemingway Contest Winner `Not The Last, No Never The Last'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to ADD background on winner; PICKS up
3rd graf pvs, `The hairs ...'; INSERTS two grafs after 11th graf
pvs, `Carlson, who ...' with more background, quotes from newspaper
editor.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``It was now morning, and he was in the
bathroom shaving, shaving for the first time that day, but not the
last; no, never the last.''
   With those words, Gordon ``Satch'' Carlson, an English teacher
and newspaper columnist from Anchorage, Alaska, won the 11th
International Imitation Hemingway Competition on Monday at _ where
else? _ Harry's Bar & American Grill.
   ``The hairs kept coming,'' his entry continued, ``tiny hairs and
black and there was nothing for it, nothing for it at all but
shaving.''
   Carlson's winning parody of the late novelist Ernest Hemingway's
manly prose went on and on for 350 words, discussing the hirsute
portions of a man's body, then an estranged woman, then more
shaving, drinking wine, and then drinking more wine.
   The dozen judges, fortified with their own glasses of wine,
muttered things like ``Holy cow!'' as they pored over the entries,
then argued spiritedly and after some mysterious process decided
upon the winner among the 21 finalists.
   Author Barnaby Conrad, one of the judges, said Carlson's entry
contained qualities lacking in others, namely ``a beginning, middle
and an end, the Hemingway cliche, and the pun.''
   The punny last paragraph of Carlson's piece read as follows:
``She turned, lifting her thin American lip over those thin, white,
perfect, American teeth, and that thin American sneer. `It's only a
nick, Adams,' she said.''
   Nick Adams was a character in several Hemingway stories.
   Carlson gets a round trip for two to Italy, with dinners at
another Harry's Bar in Florence.
   In a brief biography provided to judges, Carlson claimed that he
was once thrown out of reading class and that he moved to Alaska
about 20 years for ``reasons that remain obscure'' to him. He gave
his profession as ``social gadfly.''
   Carlson, who was not present for the judging, did not
immediately return a telephone message Monday.
   At the Anchorage Daily News, where Carlson writes a weekly
column on state and local issues, City Editor Pat Doughterty said:
``He can be both very funny and quite acerbic and opinionated. He
basically is a humor columnist.''
   Carlson, who Doughterty guessed was 41, also writes a column for
the national magazine Auto Week and teaches English at Bartlett
High School in Anchorage.
   He and the other 20 finalists were among 2,432 entries from all
50 states and more than a dozen foreign countries. Despite the
author's globe-hopping exploits, none of the entries bore a foreign
postmark.
   The judges were to include Jack Hemingway, son of Ernest, but he
did not attend because of illness. Other judges were newspaper
columnist Herb Caen, authors Ray Bradbury and Cyra McFadden, and
poet Lawrence Ferlinghetti.
   The entries, went the rules of the contest, had to ``sound like
Hemingway. Read like Hemingway. They know that funny is good and
very funny is very good.''
   Entrant 66 wrote: ``There were many cows but no bulls. `I
respect this place,' Nick said. `It is an honest place ... this
could be the capital of the world.'''
   In entry 366, ``The president looked at the woman he called
Nancy ... other men also called her Nancy.''
   Sticking to the political season, finalist 287 told how in
spring, a fellow named Gary ``took the young woman to the Bahamas,
avoiding reporters and living on rum and sun and the catch of the
day ... he had not taken his wife.''
   Number 1,400 dealt with ``A Farewell To Arms, Legs, Feet and
Neck,'' while 923 sought glitter in ``A Farewell to Lunch.''
   In another Nick adventure, entrant No. 1,507 portrayed the hero
gazing into ``a plate of trout amandine ... his eye lingered over a
big, two-breasted capon, all the while leaning on a wall of pasta.
Above all, thought Nick, it was `a farewell to qualms.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
