<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HousingHelp     03-29 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing Help,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Task Force Says $3 Billion In Seed Money Needed For Housing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private task force is recommending a series
of actions to provide ``fit, livable and affordable housing for all
Americans'' by the year 2000, starting with a first-year
appropriation of $3 billion.
   The report of the National Housing Task Force issued Monday
urges that half the money go to the states as matching funds, and
the remaining $1.5 million go to cities with no matching
requirement and few bureaucratic rules on how it is to be spent.
   The task force said housing for most poor Americans is
``unavailable, unaffordable or unfit.'' It said the $3 billion seed
money should stimulate state and local efforts to develop, renovate
and conserve low-income housing and to produce 150,000 to 200,000
units.
   James W. Rouse, a nationally known developer and chairman of the
26-member task force, called attention to the growing percentages
of women and children among the homeless.
   ``This isn't your typical hobo, this isn't a person who is a
drug addict, or alchoholic or lazy,'' Rouse told a news conference.
``These are people who want a place to live and in our country,
think of it, there's no place to live. I don't think this has ever
before happened in our country that people like this have nowhere
to live.''
   The report recommended that the government's rental assistance
program be increased by 200,000 units instead of the 100,000 in the
1989 federal budget. The added cost would be $380 million a year,
it said.
   Samuel R. Pierce, the secretary of Housing and Urban
Development, issued a statement saying that fresh ideas on low
income housing always were welcome. But the statement went on to
say that several of the recommendations call for significant
increases in federal spending and will require require difficult
budget decisions by the administration and Congress.
   The National Association of Realtors praised the report as ``a
step in the right direction.''
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of the subcommittee on
housing and urban affairs, said the report is ``of historic
importance'' and copies will be sent to all presidential candidates.
   Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato of New York, the subcommittee's ranking
Republican, said ``a decent place to live is no longer the problem
of the poor and homeless (but) the call comes from millions of
families, particularly young families.''
   The report said that from 1973 to 1983, 4.5 million units _ half
occupied by low-income households _ were lost to the rental market
either through demolition or structural conversion.
   ``Those who struggle with modest or minimal incomes represent a
cross section of America,'' said the report. ``They are young,
middle aged, elderly, disabled. They are single parents and intact
families. They are working.''
   The task force recommended that substantial new capital be
raised by establishing benevolent loan funds, accepting deposits at
low interest rates from ``socially motivated investors'' and
lending it at below-market rates to low-income housing developers
and home buyers.
   There must be greater emphasis on preserving and improving
existing low-income housing and renovation of thousands of units,
the report said, and it called for use of tax-exempt financing and
a commitment by the federal government to adequate rental
assistance. It also said the government should allow the Federal
Housing Administration to offer mortgages to more moderate income
people.
   While the report outlined a 12-year program, it said
homelessness is a problem that can't wait and recommended that
additional funds be made available in 1988 to states and
communities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VeepSpeculation Bjt   03-29 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Veep Speculation, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speculation Builds Over Likely Nominee Bush's Choice Of Running
Mate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Vice President George Bush's grip on the
Republican presidential nomination tightens, more and more people
are asking the No. 2 question:
   Whom will he choose as his running mate?
   Bush says it's too early to think about it.
   Former President Richard Nixon suggests White House chief of
staff Howard H. Baker Jr. Baker says he doesn't expect to be asked
because he wouldn't bring the right strength to the ticket.
   Others propose California Gov. George Deukmejian. Deukmejian
says he couldn't accept because he would leave his state in the
hands of a Democratic lieutenant governor.
   Nixon, in a forthcoming London Sunday Times political column,
says the ideal formula is to pick your principal rival, as
President Reagan did with Bush. But, he suggests, maybe the
campaign between Bush and Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole has been
too bitter for that.
   Some have another idea: not principal rival, but wife of
principal rival. How about Secretary of Transportation Elizabeth
Dole?
   And so it goes.
   Nixon argues that Baker, a Tennessean and former Senate
Republican leader, would be helpful in Southern states and in
dealing with Congress.
   In a recent television interview, Baker said, ``George Bush
needs to find someone who will bring strength to the ticket on a
regional and political basis, and I think that is not going to be
me.''
   He didn't say he would turn it down. ``If someone asked me to do
it,'' he said, ``I would have a very difficult time trying to
figure out what I was going to say.'' But, he added, ``I do not
wish that to happen.''
   Baker has mentioned former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander,
Deukmejian of California, New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean and former
Pennsylvania Gov. Richard Thornburgh as good choices for the vice
presidential slot.
   If Deukmejian left office in mid-term, Lt. Gov. Leo T. McCarthy,
a Democrat, would become governor of the nation's largest state. At
a news conference in Sacramento recently, the California governor
said, ``Even if they did ask me to accept the vice presidential
nomination, I wouldn't be able to take it.'' Later, he added,
``That doesn't mean I wouldn't like to be vice president.''
   Another possibility: Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, who ran as a
conservative alternative to Bush for the presidential nomination
but fared poorly.
   Also mentioned is Sen. Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas. She was on a
long list of potential Reagan running mates in 1980 but took
herself out of consideration because, as a freshman senator, she
said she didn't have enough experience. She has eight years more of
it now.
   If Bush should decide to choose a Midwesterner, to strengthen
the ticket in a region that could be crucial to Republican hopes,
another possibility would be Illinois Gov. James Thompson, who
endorsed the vice president and campaigned for him in the Illinois
presidential primary.
   Other names that have been mentioned include Sen. Alan Simpson
of Wyoming, Dole's deputy in the Senate leadership; Secretary of
Education William J. Bennett; Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas, an
architect of the congressional deficit-reduction mechanism; and
Colin Powell, the president's national security adviser and one of
the top-ranking blacks in the Reagan administration.
   All of this, of course, assumes that the vice president wins the
nomination. He is way ahead, and Dole said last week, ``I think
it's probably a foregone conclusion what's happening on the
Republican side.''
   Bush, asked whether he would consider Dole as a running mate,
said: ``It's too early for me to start thinking about any running
mates. That would project a certain arrogance or presumption that I
don't want to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
