<DOCNO> AP880329-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignNotebook     03-29 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Notebook,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vignettes From Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt did so poorly in Michigan's
caucuses that he knew his race was over. But he wasn't ready to
announce it yet, and one of those ugly scenes of modern politics
unfolded.
   In the death throes of his campaign, Gephardt attracted a large
press contingent. An aide to a rival muttered something about a
``death watch,'' and said to the reporters, ``Stay away from us for
a while.''
   Gephardt ended his speech and headed for a hotel room with his
wife, Jane. The crowd pursued, some walking backward in front of
him, television lights glaring, down a maze of corridors. Finally,
Gephardt reached the sanctuary of an elevator.
   One elderly man, caught up in the stampede, fell on his face
onto the concrete-hard floor. The crowd stepped around him.
   Reporters pressed Gephardt to say he would get out of the race.
   ``Did that do you a lot of good?'' senior aide Dick Moe snapped
bitterly at one reporter who has covered Gephardt throughout the
campaign.
   One television reporter, perhaps not realizing Gephardt was at
the end of his candidacy, persisted in asking the congressman how
he expected to do in Wisconsin's primary 10 days later.
   Gephardt press secretary Ali Webb was carrying a pair of red
boxing gloves, a gift from supporters presented two days earlier.
   ``Congressman, I have some boxing gloves here if you need
them,'' she said.
   ``I knew you brought those along for a reason,'' said Jane
Gephardt.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of his victory in Michigan, Jesse Jackson spent one
of those campaign days a candidate hopes for _ the crowds were
overflowing and raw emotion was evident.
   Scores stayed outside the door at a church rally in Flint, even
after the fire marshal said the building was too full.
   Always appealing to the nation's downtrodden, Jackson even
campaigned among those who are arguably the most disaffected and
certainly his most captive audience: inmates at the Wayne County
Jail.
   Only those jailed on misdemeanors were allowed to meet him.
Since the inmates weren't felons, they could vote. And while his
real audience may have been the television cameras, Jackson
reminded the inmates they could cast absentee ballots.
   The next day in Milwaukee, Jackson appeared humbled by the
dimensions of his win. He spoke of ``a lot of poetry, a lot of
history.''
   What did he think, he was asked, of calls by party elders for
Democrats to nominate the candidate who leads in delegates ``at the
end.''
   Having just scrambled the Democratic race, probably assuring no
one will win a majority through the primary season, Jackson paused
and smiled.
   ``At the end,'' he said simply.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Macedonia Missionary Baptist Church in Flint, Jackson
urged his mostly black audience to raise its expectations.
   ``Doors shut in your face _ I understand,'' he said. ``I was
born in the slum, but the slum wasn't born in me.''
   But before leaving, Jackson asked his supporters for a
contribution and referred to the expensive designer clothing some
wore.
   ``I want you to give tonight like you dress _ give Gucci-ly,''
Jackson said. ``Give like you live.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gephardt aide Joe Trippi knew the results from Michigan weren't
going to be good Saturday afternoon. But his heart sank when he
heard some shouted news.
   ``Duke's ahead by 9,'' they said.
   Stunned, he interpreted the message to mean Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, often called ``The Duke,'' was winning big.
   It was only later that the real meaning was explained. Duke
University was beating Temple in the NCAA Eastern Regional
basketball game.
   His relief was short-lived. Gephardt lost by far more.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of the Democrats met at an outdoor rally in Wausau, in
north central Wisconsin.
   Dukakis, Gephardt, Albert Gore Jr. and Paul Simon sat through
what must have seemed to them an interminable time on the stage,
listening to each other. They'd heard it all before, but seldom
under such conditions.
   The temperature was less than 20 degrees and a wind howled.
   Several reporters traveling with Gephardt found a respite,
however. They had arrived from the airport in a local supporter's
plushly appointed van, and the motorcade parked conveniently beside
the rally. From inside they could stay warm, hear the speeches _
and watch that Duke-Temple game on a color television.
   ``Wimps,'' Gephardt spokeswoman Webb said, pounding on the van's
windows from outside. They didn't budge.
</TEXT>
