<DOCNO> AP880329-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     03-29 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Picks Up Kemp Endorsement; Predicts Wisconsin Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, saying ``one of the
best things that happened to me was getting my brains kicked out in
Iowa,'' is moving to consolidate his mounting Republican support
while vowing to ``whip the Democrats.''
   With an unassailable lead for the GOP presidential nomination,
Bush on Monday picked up the endorsement of Rep. Jack Kemp. And
with the expected withdrawal of distant rival Sen. Bob Dole
looming, Bush talked of ``smooth sailing'' ahead for his campaign.
   Here for three days of campaigning in advance of the April 5
Wisconsin primary, Bush told an invitation-only rally in a high
school in nearby Cedarburg late Monday: ``I don't put too much
stock in the polls, but they do look good.''
   ``I will not project an arrogance, I will not project
overconfidence,'' he added.
   But Bush brimmed with optimism, saying Kemp's endorsement was
``good, because what we want to do is to have this party unified,
together, so we can whip the Democrats.''
   ``One of the best things that happened to me was getting my
brains kicked out in Iowa,'' Bush told his audience. ``Got beaten,
beaten fair and square and came in third.''
   ``Everybody had me dead and buried. (But) We were resurrected
right there in New Hampshire. So people say now things are going
pretty well for you, and they are.''
   Earlier Monday, Kemp joined Bush at a news conference in
Milwaukee to announce his support. ``George Bush is going to be the
nominee of the Republican party. He's earned it,'' Kemp said.
   The New York congressman dropped out of the race earlier in the
month, after poor showings in New Hampshire, South Carolina and in
Super Tuesday contests.
   Both Kemp and Bush said discussion of a possible vice
presidential bid did not come up.
   Kemp said ``my support is unequivocal'' for Bush even though he
had felt he himself was ``the best candidate for Republican
conservatives.''
   ``The voters believed otherwise,'' Kemp said.
   As to a Dole withdrawal, Bush said that was a decision for the
Senate minority leader to make on his own. ``I'm just going to keep
on campaigning,'' Bush said.
   Later, he told reporters, ``I'm not in a position to be telling
Dole what to do.''
   He said the general election contest ``will be close, it will be
tough ... I cannot act like I have this nomination in the bag.''
   However, Bush suggested a victory in Wisconsin would do just
that. And his sights were clearly set on the general election
contest beyond, repeatedly speaking of the importance of party
unity.
   Bush said he would take his case to the American people,
reflecting efforts to lay a groundwork for the general election
campaign.
   ``It's a national messsge,'' he told the rally in Cedarburg.
   ``This time, I'm going all the way to the White House,'' he
said, noting he had spoken at a campaign appearance in the town in
1980 in his then-unsuccessful presidential bid.
   As he has done before, Bush blamed Democrats in Congress for the
nation's $150 billion budget deficit, vowed to work to reduce the
tax on capital gains and echoed President Reagan's pledge to veto
all-encompassing stopgap spending legislation.
   And, also taking a cue from Reagan, Bush declared: ``I'm not
going to raise your taxes _ period.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
