<1ST_LINE>u a AM-82ndReturns 4thLd-Writethru a0774 03-29 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-82nd Returns, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0774,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whistling U.S. Paratroopers Return from Honduras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, `I am...,' to UPDATE with
soldiers returning to California</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT BRAGG, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 700 members of the Army's 82nd
Airborne Division parachuted into their home base Monday in a
flamboyant end to 12 days of exercises in Honduras, where they were
sent in a show of U.S. might.
   As family members, commanders and a military band waited, seven
huge C-141 planes flew over at 5 p.m. Moments later, the first of
the paratroopers began their descent to the base's Sicily Drop
Zone, evoking a loud cheer.
   ``I am glad you are home, Baby,'' Delores Piper told her
husband, Staff Sgt. Charles Piper, as their two young daughters
clung to their father's legs.
   Later Monday night, about 100 soldiers from the 7th Infantry
Division Light returned to California, landing at Travis Air Force
Base to greetings from an Army honor guard and a band playing
``Stars And Stripes Forever.''
   Lt. Gen. John Foss, commander of the 18th Airborne Corps at Fort
Bragg, welcomed the troops, who were dispatched to Honduras on
March 17 to counter a reported incursion of Nicaraguan forces into
that country. The 82nd is a division of the 18th Airborne Corps.
   ``Now, 12 days later, there are no Nicaraguan forces in that
country and a cease-fire exists,'' Foss said. ``We were watched by
everyone in the world, and everyone was impressed. I want you to
know I'm very proud of you.''
   Some 2,000 soldiers from the 82nd Airborne were deployed to
Honduras on March 17. There were part of a 3,200-troop force sent
by President Reagan. The rest of the American troops are expected
to return by Wednesday.
   ``The Nicaraguans ran back across the border as soon as we
came,'' Piper said. ``We did what we had to do.'' But he added it
was good to be home. ``Honduran ground is too hard to sleep on,''
he said.
   The mission ended just in time for 1st Lt. Steve Swimley, who
said he was becoming bored.
   ``We were doing the same stuff over and over,'' he said as he
hugged his wife, Mary. ``It was clear to me we'd be coming home
soon because we had accomplished our objective.''
   His buddy, 1st Lt. Jim Cooper, said he was looking forward ``to
taking a shower and drinking a few beers.''
   Earlier in the day, about 200 Hondurans demonstrated their
support for the Americans outside the Palmerola Air Base in
Honduras.
   They carried signs saying, ``Thanks for having helped us
maintain our liberty'' and ``Unity makes for democracy, thanks for
being here.''
   Nicaragua denied the reported incursion and claimed the United
States was preparing to invade or was using the deployment as a
cover for providing equipment to the Contras. U.S. officials have
said the troops are taking back all the equipment they brought with
them, including tanks and aircraft.
   In addition to the 82nd Airborne, the reinforcements include
soldiers from the 7th Light Infantry in Fort Ord, Calif.
   The U.S. troops never saw action, but Honduran President Jose
Azcona Hoyo said all along he expected them to back him up if the
Sandinistas didn't withdraw.
   By late last week, Honduran officials said the Nicaraguan troops
were back on their own side of the border.
</TEXT>
