<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Colombia-Drugs Bjt   03-29 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Drugs, Bjt,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother Linked to Drug Trade, Attorney General Reportedly Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney general of Colombia,
Alfredo Gutierrez Marquez, resigned after news media reported an
airstrip at his brother's ranch was used by drug runners, a source
at President Virgilio Barco's office said.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, told The
Associated Press late Monday that Barco accepted the resignation
earlier in the day. Neither the president's press office nor the
attorney general's office would comment.
   Radio stations RCN, Caracol and Todelar reported the resignation
Monday.
   An Intervision TV news program said on Sunday night that planes
used by drug smugglers operated off a 5,000-foot runway owned by
Libardo Gutierrez Marquez on a farm near Medellin, a city in
northwest Colombia where most of Colombia's reputed drug
traffickers live.
   The runway was next to property belonging to Pablo Escobar,
named in the United States as a top leader of the Medellin drug
cartel, and aircraft belonging to Escobar used it, Intervision said.
   The source said that Gutierrez acknowledged in resigning as
attorney general on Monday that his brother did own a farm as the
news reports said.
   Caracol had reported the attorney general resigned shortly after
a confiscated drug plane was stolen March 1 from a military air
base and landed at the runway, but the later radio reports said he
quit on Monday.
   Barco has declared war on the powerful drug traffickers, who
have killed a justice minister, an attorney general, judges, two
newspaper editors and scores of policemen and soldiers.
   The Medellin cartel smuggles most of the cocaine reaching the
United States, the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration says.
Escobar was among five men indicted on U.S. drug charges and named
as belonging to the cartel.
   The army said that when it raided a country estate owned by
Escobar last week, it found tape recordings linking drug dealers
with someone close to the attorney general's office. It did not
elaborate.
   Last year the army confiscated a twin-engine propeller aircraft,
an Aerocommander, that had been used for drug trafficking. On March
1, the plane was stolen from an air force base and landed at
Libardo Gutierrez's runway, Intervision said. It said air force
planes strafed the plane, other aircraft and hangars and that two
days later, army bulldozers destroyed the runway.
   The president says the government will not yield in the drug war.
   In the last two months, the army has attacked five homes of
suspected drug traffickers, including Escobar's home, and reported
finding arsenals of weapons and ammunition, stolen license plates
and army and police uniforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Trade     03-29 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Trade,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Voters Have Rejected ``Trade Demagogues''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The exit of Richard Gephardt from the race for
president gave President Reagan the opportunity to contend the
public has no appetite for protectionist legislation such as the
trade bill pending in Congress.
   ``I think the American people have decided that one Great
Depression is enough, and they aren't going to give the trade
demagogues a second chance,'' Reagan said Monday during a speech at
Reynolds Metals Co., in Richmond, Va.
   ``Protectionism isn't just bad economics _ it's bad politics,''
the president said.
   He pointed to the March 8 Super Tuesday presidential delegate
selection contests and said, ``Those who had predicted that
protectionism would be embraced in the South were proven wrong.''
   Gephardt, D-Mo., who had made the nation's trade woes an
important part of his campaign for the Democratic presidential
nomination, announced Monday he was ending his bid. Gephardt had
done poorly in more than two-dozen states, including the southern
Super Tuesday states.
   Reagan long has advocated a policy of free trade and fair trade.
At the same time, he has resisted protectionist legislation, even
as the merchandise trade deficit climbed to a record $171.22
billion in 1987.
   Reagan derided an international trade bill that is under
consideration by a House-Senate conference committee and threatened
to veto it unless it is drastically changed. The panel is working
out compromises in the widely varying versions of the 1,000-page
measure.
   ``They've got a trade bill before Congress that could squelch
productivity, destroy American competitiveness and make all their
doomsday myths a reality,'' Reagan said.
   He accused his critics of ``predicting economic disaster,'' and
ignoring the fact that the economy is in the 64th month of recovery
from the recession of 1981-82.
   He said the bill's mandatory retaliation provisions could
``require me and future presidents to take actions that would be in
direct violation'' of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trades
and ``seriously harm the national interest.''
   ``If enacted, they could weaken the international trading system
and could require the president to start trade wars,'' Reagan said.
   But Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas,
reacting to Reagan's remarks, told reporters, ``I don't think he
has really studied the bill and doesn't have a full knowledge.''
   Bentsen is vice chairman of the House-Senate conference
committee ironing out differences in the two versions of the trade
legislation.
   Bentsen said Reagan's remark that provisions of the bill could
lead to violations of international trade rules is ``just not
correct.''
   ``What the president is concerned about is that it makes him
accountable,'' Bentsen said. ``Most presidents don't like
accountability. This legislation requires him to do something. He
can't just do nothing.''
   Bentsen said the plant closing provisions would not cost
companies any money and merely reflect practices that most
corporations already are following. Those provisions would require
the firms to provide their employees with advance notice of
closings and large-scale layoffs.
   Reagan objects to many provisions in the trade bill, including
an amendment named for Gephardt that would require the president to
reduce ``excess and unwarranted'' surpluses run up by Japan and a
few other countries in trade with the United States. If
negotiations failed, the president would be required to use import
curbs to lower the surpluses at a 10 percent annual rate.
   The president could waive such action if he found it contrary to
the national economic interest or if the offending country were
wrestling with serious debt. But critics say the plan is a long
step toward protectionism and invites retaliation against U.S.
industries.
   ``You may have been reading lately that the trade bill is making
good progress _ that a lot of protectionist provisions have been
jettisoned,'' he said. ``And there is some truth to that. But
there's a long way to go before the legislation does more good than
harm to the U.S. economy.
   ``Only wholesale elimination of the objectionable provisions
will produce a bill I can sign.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
