<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DemocratsDebate     03-29 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats Debate,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Differs With Jackson on Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., saying his approach to
homelessness is ``more responsible'' than Jesse Jackson's, has
taken a rare if mild poke at Jackson in the race for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   The point was one of the few areas of disagreement at a forum on
urban policy in the Bronx attended Monday night by Gore, Jackson
and Sen. Paul Simon. All three called for a broad spectrum of
improved social programs.
   Jackson urged ``emergency assistance for the homeless.'' But
Gore said: ``The cost of an emergency short-term response is often
far greater than the cost of a more responsible long-term effort to
respond to this problem.''
   Gore, of Tennessee, said his approach would include community
mental health care programs and permanent housing for the homeless.
   Simon said to the audience at Fordham University: ``I ask you
who is best prepared for the presidency.''
   The other Democratic leader, Gov. Michael Dukakis of
Massachusetts, did not appear at the forum. Aides said he had a
longstanding commitment to attend two fundraisers in Washington.
   ``If it had been possible to rearrange the schedule we would
have done so,'' Dukakis said earlier.
   Dukakis, Gore and Simon, of Illinois, made separate campaign
appearances Monday in New York City, an indication of the increased
importance of the state's April 19 primary, when the selection of
255 delegates is at stake.
   Polls have indicated a lead for Dukakis in the Connecticut
primary today, a dead heat between Dukakis and Jackson in the
Wisconsin primary April 5 and a lead for Dukakis in the New York
contest two weeks later.
   At the 1{-hour Bronx forum, Jackson, Gore and Simon agreed on a
need for more spending for education and housing, a greater effort
to combat AIDS and stronger measures to fight drugs.
   Gore urged ``an all-out war on drugs,'' noting that it is Vice
President George Bush, the likely Republican presidential nominee,
who heads a federal anti-drug effort that Gore described as failed.
   Jackson criticized the administration's drug-fighting efforts
the most forcefully. He said: ``In Latin America, it's becoming
clear in this administration while the focus was on communism, it
was fascist drug lords that in fact were overthrowing governments
there and infiltrating our government and killing our people at
home.''
   He did not elaborate on the infiltration assertion.
   In a similar vein, Gore called CIA involvement with Panamanian
strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega ``a disgrace.'' Simon added:
``We talk about a war on drugs. It's been mostly public relations.
That's the grim reality.''
   On AIDS, the three criticized what they said was an
uncoordinated government response. But Gore lauded the efforts of
Surgeon General C. Everett Koop and said Koop should be considered
for renomination in a Democratic administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
