<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-29 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Bank Bolsters U.S. Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intervention by Japan's central bank helped the
dollar recover after opening lower against the yen in Tokyo
Tuesday, while stock prices rose substantially for the second
straight day.
   The dollar began trading at 123.88 yen, down 0.55 yen from
Monday's close of 124.43 yen, and then gained strength on the basis
of the Bank of Japan intervention and fiscal year-end buying by
companies, dealers said. The U.S. currency ended trading at 124.37
yen, down 0.06 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average
gained 330.38 points, or 1.29 percent, finishing the day at
25,953.09.
   Traders said most stocks were managing to maintain their gains
from Monday, when the Nikkei index rose 301.99 points.
   The Bank of Japan began buying dollars shortly after the
beginning of trading on the foreign exchange market, dealers said.
They said the scale of the central bank's intervention was not
immediately clear.
   The bank, which does not comment officially on its market
activity, bought an estimated $300 million on Monday.
   The dollar's close on Monday capped a 2.72-yen fall over three
trading days.
   Traders said some market participants weren't convinced that
central banks in Japan and the United States were committed to
maintaining the dollar's past level. Recent intervention by the
banks appears to have been aimed at slowing the dollar's fall, not
at boosting its value, they said.
   Despite the dollar's rise from its opening level in Tuesday
trading, dealers said a yen-buying mood was likely to continue
after the end of the Japanese fiscal year on March 31.
</TEXT>
