<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-29 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Steve Meyer and Craig Peden found
a big, blue rock while gem hunting, Meyer thought it was probably
worth something _ but not enough to keep him from using it as a
paperweight on his desk.
   That was before last month, when a master gem cutter told them
the baseball-size stone they found in the Smoky Mountains of North
Carolina might be a star sapphire worth millions of dollars.
   Gem cutter John Robinson of Plano, Texas, said the sapphire
could surpass the 1,154-carat, $4 million Star of America sapphire
in both size and value.
   Robinson is cutting and polishing the crystal, trying to
determine if it will display a six-ray star when exposed to light.
   ``It has a good potential for starring,'' said Robinson, who
also cut the Star of America. ``If that happens, it will be an
important gem.''
   Peden said that even if the sapphire doesn't star, ``it's
probably worth a couple of hundred thousand dollars.''
   Meyer, a 32-year-old X-ray technician, said he and Peden found
the stone about 5 feet underground just before Christmas.
   ``We'd only been out about 10 times since the end of last
summer,'' he said Monday. ``And we got lucky.''
   Peden, who operates a dental ceramics business, said he hoped to
help his parents and establish a scholarship for Seventh-Day
Adventist students. Meyer said he would open his own X-ray
laboratory.
   Meyer, who spent much of Monday talking to reporters or doing
interviews for television, said the impact of his discovery was
just beginning to sink in.
   Has he heard from any long-lost relatives?
   ``No,'' he said. ``But I'm sure I will.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE PARK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olivia Walker has sewn so much glitter
and gleam onto the robes of professional wrestlers, she says she
has to wear sunglasses when she begins putting needle to fabric.
   She has assembled the silk and sequins which have flowed over
the shoulders of such wrestling stars as Dusty Rhodes, Lex Luger,
The Killer Bees and Ric Flair.
   Flair ``loves his robes, I'll tell ya,'' said Mrs. Walker, 44,
who has been making the gaudy creations for 20 years and lives in
this suburb south of Atlanta.
   How many has she made?
   ``It's either 972 or 792,'' she said recently. ``Let's say 972.
That sounds better.''
   Asked what makes a good wrestling robe, Mrs. Walker joked, ``The
money.'' Her creations cost up to $8,000.
   She said a robe's cost depends on the weight of its decorations.
One robe for Flair required 7,200 rhinestones, all applied by hand,
and weighed 45 pounds.
</TEXT>
