<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Lays Off Top Aide To Trim Payroll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESAPEAKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With less than $2 million left before he
exceeds the federal campaign spending lid, Republican hopeful Pat
Robertson laid off his highest paid staffer and restructured the
rest of his national staff.
   Connie Snapp, the former media coordinator and one of the brains
behind the Robertson campaign, will be off the payroll as of April
1, Barbara Gattullo, Ms. Snapp's former assistant, said Monday.
   ``It's kind of the thing that happens when you reach the
spending limit,'' Ms. Gattullo said. ``There were no hard feelings,
I'm sure.''
   Ms. Snapp, a former vice president and marketing director for a
division of the New York-based advertising and public relations
agency Young and Rubicam, will continue with the campaign as a
consultant.
   R. Marc Nuttle, Robertson's former campaign manager, who along
with Ms. Snapp charted the early course of the campaign, also
becomes a consultant.
   The day-to-day management of the campaign will be done by Allan
Sutherlin who has 20 years experience in Republican politics and
has served as secretary and political director of the party in
Indiana.
   Ms. Gattullo, who will take over most of Ms. Snapp's duties,
said many of the changes were to streamline the campaign's focus
and finances. Robertson has between $1 million and $2 million
remaining before he exceeds the federal campaign spending cap for
primaries.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Residency Dispute Headed Toward Supreme Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys in the dispute over the residency
of secretary of state Evan Bayh predict the case could reach the
Indiana Supreme Court by the middle of April.
   The appeals process in residency dispute picked up speed Monday
when a Shelby County judge turned down a request to review his
ruling that Bayh does meet the five-year residency requirement to
be governor.
   Shelby Circuit Court Charles D. O'Connor overruled the State
Election Board's motion to correct errors in his March 14 ruling.
   Election board attorney Michael R. Franceschini said an appeal
will be prepared immediately along with a request that the Supreme
Court accept the case now rather than having it go first to the
Indiana Court of Appeals.
   The court action was precipitated by a request from Gov. Robert
D. Orr to have the election board rule on Bayh's residency. Orr
said he would not back down from seeking a high court ruling on the
matter despite urging from Lt. Gov John M. Mutz to drop it for
political reasons.
   ``The governor's position has not changed,'' said his
spokeswoman, Dollyne Pettingill. ``He is interested in a final
determination, one that cannot be challenged. And that must come
from the state's highest court.''
   Mutz is unopposed for the Republican nomination to succeed Orr,
who is barred from seeking a third straight term.
