<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CentralAmerica-Glance     03-29 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Central America-Glance,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central America At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of the latest developments involving Central
America:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PANAMA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Soldiers fired birdshot and beat
protesters with rubber truncheons Monday to break up march by
10,000 people demanding the ouster of strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega. A general strike entered its second week. Also Monday,
police and troops swept into a hotel in the capital, arresting
opposition leaders and journalists.
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Former Venezuelan President Carlos Andres
Perez planned a trip to Panama to ask its Roman Catholic
archbishop, Monsignor Marco Antonio McGrath, to mediate a peaceful
solution to Panama's crisis. Andres Perez spent two days meetings
with President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica and Spanish Prime Minister
Felipe Gonzalez about Panama.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NICARAGUA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   SAPOA, Nicaragua _ Rebel and government negotiators began
hammering out the details of a 60-day cease-fire outlined in the
peace accord signed last week. They are to decide in what areas the
Contra rebels can gather during the truce. The talks, which began
Monday, were scheduled to resume today.
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua _ Reports reaching the capital say Contra
fighters opposed to the cease-fire accord are staging attacks.
Fighting was reported in southern Zelaya province and the central
provinces of Chontales and Matagalpa.
   WASHINGTON _ House leaders are trying to put together a package
of non-lethal aid for the Contras, who under the truce agreement
have promised not to accept any military aid. The closed-door
talks, which also involved Contra officials and the
secretary-general of the Organization of American States, broke up
Monday after five hours with Republicans and Democrats deadlocked
over the issue. More meetings were scheduled for today.
   FORT BRAGG, N.C. _ More than 700 U.S. paratroopers on Monday
parachuted into their home base 12 days after entering Honduras the
same way, where they were sent as a show of force against a
reported Nicaraguan incursion against the Contras. Altogether 2,000
soldiers from the Army's 82nd Airborne Division were deployed to
Honduras on March 17. There were part of a 3,200-troop force sent
by President Reagan and conducted exercises during their stay. The
rest of the American troops are expected to return by Wednesday.
</TEXT>
