<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SDXJournalismAwards     03-29 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SDX Journalism Awards,0837</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miami Herald Wins Three Awards, One For Hart-Rice Story</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Miami Herald won three distinguished-service
awards from the Society of Professional Journalists, Sigma Delta
Chi, including one for the newspaper's stories on Gary Hart's
association with Donna Rice.
   The Herald also won awards for foreign correspondence and news
photography.
   Veteran journalists from throughout the country judged the 1987
entries for the awards, presented annually since 1932 by the
journalism society.
   The Herald's Tom Fiedler, Jim McGee and James Savage won the
Washington correspondence award for their series on how Hart met in
a Washington, D.C., townhouse with Miss Rice after his repeated
proclamations of marital fidelitly.
   Publicity about the relationship last year led him to drop out
of the race for the Democratic presidential nomination. He rejoined
the campaign briefly, then dropped out earlier this month after
faring poorly in several primaries.
   The Herald stories ``resulted in a major controversy in
political and journalistic circles after readers were apprised of
the differences between the public perception and the behavior of a
prominent, national political figure,'' the society said in
announcing the awards Monday.
   ``The accuracy of the Herald stories, while widely questioned at
the time of publication, has stood up under the thorough scrutiny
of critics. The stories were in the finest tradition of responsible
newspaper reporting and met the strictest standards of
journalism,'' the society said.
   The Herald's Guy Gugliotta, Jeff Leen and James Savage won the
foreign correspondence award for a series analyzing the Colombian
crime ring known as the Medellin Cartel, which allegedly controls
the trafficking of cocaine from Latin America to the United States.
   The newspaper also won the news photography award for Michel
duCille's series of black-and-white pictures showing how crack, a
form of cocaine, dominated the lives of impoverished people living
in a public housing project.
   The Dallas Times Herald won the society's public service award
for a newspaper with circulation over 100,000 for its series
explaining the effect of the government's immigration reform act.
   The Alabama Journal in Montgomery won the public service award
in the under-100,000 circulation category for its series on the
state's high infant mortality rate.
   The society will present its distinguished-service awards at a
banquet in Orlando, Fla., on May 7.
   Other awards announced Monday were:
   _Editorial cartooning, to Paul Conrad of the Los Angeles Times,
for cartoons on Lt. Col. Oliver North's testimony before Congress
on the Iran-Contra affair. Conrad, the recipient of six
distinguished-service awards, has been honored by the society more
than any other journalist.
   _TV spot news reporting, to Allen Pizzey, Paul Vittoroulis and
Georges Ioannides of CBS for a report on efforts to rescue crewmen
from a burning Cypriot tanker in the Persian Gulf.
   _Public service by a TV station in the top 50 markets, to KING
in Seattle, for a documentary exploring the impact of sex education
on teen-agers.
   _Public service by a smaller-market TV station, to WBRZ in Baton
Rouge, La., for a documentary examining how state and city
officials failed to appeal costly court judgments.
   _Television editorials, to Phil Johnson of WWL in New Orleans,
for a series lambasting the administration of a prison for young,
first-time offenders.
   _General reporting by a newspaper with circulation over 100,000,
to Jacqui Banaszynski of the St. Paul Pioneer Press for a
three-part series on a political activist with AIDS.
   _General reporting by a newspaper with circulation under
100,000, to Paul Nyden of The Charleston (West Va.) Gazette for a
series examining malpractice claims and insurance settlements in
the state.
   _Editorial writing, to Jane Healy of The Orlando (Fla.) Sentinel
for a series on how Orange County commissioners mismanged plans for
urban development.
   _Magazine public service, to The Washington Post Magazine for a
story by Walt Harrington focusing on a father's struggle to cope
with the kidnapping of his three-week-old son.
   _Magazine reporting, to Stephen Fried, senior editor of
Philadelphia magazine, for a story on how a suburban police officer
sexually molested boys over the past 25 years.
   _Radio public service, to MonitoRadio, a Christian Science
Monitor news program, for a series on the plight of children in
developing nations.
   _Radio spot news reporting, to the news staff of KNX-AM in Los
Angeles, for coverage of an earthquake and aftershocks that rocked
Southern California in October.
   _Editorials on radio, to Catharine Cahan of Chicago's WBBM-AM,
for a series calling for flexible hours in city health clinics,
based on the needs of the community.
   _Journalism research, to Randall P. Bezanson, Gilbert Cranberg
and John Soloski, for their book ``Libel Law and the Press.''
   _Print bicentennial, to John Lofton, retired editorial writer
for the St. Louis Post-Dispatch for a series examining how
provisions of the U.S. Constitution came to be.
   _Broadcast bicentennial, to Beatrice Black of WHYY-FM in
Philadelphia, for a story on First Amendment rights of individuals
protesting abortion.
</TEXT>
