<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Volcano-Colombia     03-29 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Volcano-Colombia,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Reduces Volcano Alert in Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nevado del Ruiz volcano grew calmer,
but the government insisted that people continue evacuating areas
close to the crater.
   The volcano was spouting steam on Monday, but no ash was falling
in areas around the volcano, the government's National Emergency
Committee said. Also, no tremors were being recorded.
   The volcano started spewing steam and ash on Friday, becoming
the most active since it erupted Nov. 13, 1985, when 23,000 persons
were killed.
   People within a six-mile radius of the volcano were ordered to
evacuate.
   The Bogota newspapers El Tiempo and El Espectador reported
Monday that many people in small villages were refusing to leave.
In Murillo, the largest village close to the volcano, Mayor Jesus
Maria Romero Aranzazu said only eight of the 600 residents there
had left, El Espectador reported.
   Murillo, undamaged by the 1985 eruption, is five miles from the
volcano.
</TEXT>
