<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--NearCollision     03-29 0147</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Near Collision,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jetliner, Two-Seater In Near Crash Over England</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A DC9 jetliner and a two-seat training plane flew
within 700 feet of each other over England, the Civil Aviation
Authority said.
   The incident occurred Sunday two miles south of Cambridge
Airport, the authority said Monday.
   It involved a Paramount Airways DC9, which was carrying no
passengers, and a Piper PA38 Tomahawk. The two planes were flying
at an altitude of 2,000 feet.
   The Civil Aviation Authority did not say what caused the planes
to fly so close to each other, but said the incident would be
investigated by the independent Joint Air Miss Working Group.
   The standard safe distance between two planes is 1,000 feet.
   Paramount Airways is a new regional airline based in Bristol,
England.
   The Civil Aviation Authority recently adopted a policy of
reporting all near-collisions over British air space.
</TEXT>
