<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--NaziFlags     03-29 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Nazi Flags,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Complains About Display Of Nazi Flags</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South African army's display
of Nazi flags at a military pageant has drawn criticism, a military
spokeswoman said.
   The military displayed the Nazi flags last week at The Castle, a
historic military building in Cape Town.
   A Jewish visitor complained when he saw the flags, which contain
a swastika, the military spokeswoman, Lt. Ina Fourie, said on
Monday. A number of telephone callers also objected to the display,
Ms. Fourie added.
   She said the use of the flags was ``merely symbolic in depicting
World War II. We are very sorry if we have offended or hurt
anyone.''
   She said the flags would no longer be displayed.
   South Africa supported the Allied side in World War II, but a
large segment of the white population was sympathetic to Germany.
</TEXT>
