<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Argentina-Strike     03-29 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Argentina-Strike,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teachers' Strike Enters Third Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide teachers' strike
that has prevented 7.2 million children aged 3 to 18 from starting
public school this year has entered its third week with no end in
sight, officials said.
   The walkout by 505,000 primary and secondary school teachers
belonging to CTERA, the Confederation of Educational Workers of the
Argentine Republic union, began March 14 over demands to be paid a
minimum of $115 a month.
   The government under Education Minister Jorge Sabato, while
admitting teachers' salaries are low, has offered $85, saying it
cannot pay more because of the economic crisis. Some teachers
receive only $55 a month.
   Inflation in Argentina, the developing world's third-most
indebted nation, was 189 percent in 1987 and 10.4 percent in
February.
   Private schools have been mostly untouched by the strike, which
entered its third week on Monday.
</TEXT>
