<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--LifePreserver-Drowning     03-29 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Life Preserver-Drowning,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search for Missing Fisherman Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers have found no evidence of a
fisherman who disappeared on the Sandy River last weekend after
tossing his life preserver to his son, sheriff's deputies said.
   George Earl Trenkle, 40, of Blackfoot, Idaho, was presumed
drowned after a Saturday boating accident in which he and two
others were thrown from their driftboat.
   His son, George Edward Trenkle, 18, said their driftboat hit a
log and capsized. The elder Trenkle gave up his life preserver to
save his son's life, then was carried by the current around a bend.
   The third man, Roland Parkhurst, 40, of Gresham, was wearing a
life jacket. He and the younger Trenkle were rescued by witnesses.
   A Multnomah County river patrol crew searched the bank and
surface for Trenkle's body Saturday, Sunday and Monday. Deputy Garr
Nielsen said nothing was found and that the search would continue.
</TEXT>
