<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0553EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-29 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hail, High Wind Hits Oklahoma; Storms Brew Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hail the size of golf balls pounded portions of Oklahoma early
today, where high winds and possibly tornadoes earlier inflicted
damage and killed a woman in her mobile home.
   Other storms were scattered along a cold front that extended
Monday night from the upper Great Lakes into the southern Plains.
   Thunderstorms produced hail 2} inches in diameter at Duncan,
Olka., Monday evening as well as near Comanche, Okla. Smaller hail
fell in other parts of the state, while the golf ball-sized hail
fell early today at Ada and near Tahlequah, in eastern Oklahoma.
   Meanwhile Monday night, thunderstorm winds near 60 mph were
clocked near Velma, Olka., and heavy rain drenched much of the
state. Oklahoma City received over 2} inches of rainfall over a
24-hour period.
   The high winds damaged a mobile home in Oklahoma City, killing a
woman inside and seriously injuring her husband. Elsewhere in the
city, about a half-dozen mobile homes where thrown onto their sides.
   In Mustang, Okla., police reported the roofs on City Hall and a
fast food restaurant were damaged by wind. The weather service said
a possible tornado was spotted near Mustang just before 5 p.m., and
other possible tornadoes in Oklahoma were reported at Harrah and
Midwest City.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across Kansas and
Missouri and eastern Arkansas. A flash flood watch was issued for
tonight for southwest Missouri as the rains over Oklahoma move
northeast.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms extended into parts of Illinois
and eastern Wisconsin. Rain was reported across parts of lower
Michigan into western New York state.
   Freezing drizzle was reported in sections of Michigan's Upper
Peninsula early today, while rain was scattered across the Pacific
Northwest and snow was falling over parts of the southern Colorado
Rockies.
   Skies were mostly clear across much of the Southwest on Monday
evening, but high winds continued in sections. Carlsbad, N.M.,
clocked winds to 70 mph late Monday and Phoenix reported winds
gusting to around 40 mph at Deer Valley Airport.
   Some clouds moved into parts of the Southeast late Monday, while
dense fog formed along the Florida Panhandle coast.
   The forecast for today called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern and eastern Texas across the Mississippi and lower Ohio
valleys to the Great Lakes region; snowshowers in northern
Minnesota and northwest Wisconsin, and from northwest Montana to
eastern Washington; and rainshowers in the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs were expected in the 30s or 40s from upper Michigan across
the upper Mississippi Valley and the northern and central portions
of the Great Plains and Rockies to Idaho and eastern Washington;
the 70s or 80s from the southern Atlantic states and interior
portions of the mid-Atlantic states across the Ohio, Tennessee and
lower Mississippi Valleys to central and southern Texas; and the
70s and 80s from the desert Southwest to central and Southern
California. Elsewhere, highs will be in the 50s or 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from zero at
Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 75 at Kingsville, Texas, and Key West,
Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 51 partly cloudy; Boston 35 fair; Buffalo 43
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 43 fair; Cincinnati 58 cloudy; Cleveland
51 windy; Detroit 46 partly cloudy; Miami 73 fair; New York 43
cloudy; Philadelphia 43 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 46 partly cloudy;
Portland, Maine 30 fair; Washington 45 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 23 fair; Chicago 55 rain; Dallas-Fort Worth
70 windy; Denver 21 fair; Des Moines 42 windy; Indianapolis 53
cloudy; Kansas City 38 rain; Minneapolis-St. Paul 34 partly cloudy;
Nashville 61 cloudy; New Orleans 64 cloudy; St. Louis 59 rain.
   _West: Albuquerque 33 fair; Anchorage 31 cloudy; Las Vegas 45
fair; Los Angeles 65 fair; Phoenix 58 fair; Salt Lake City 27 fair;
San Diego 60 fair; San Francisco 48 fair; Seattle 38 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 28 fair; Toronto 36 cloudy.
