<HEAD>Tornadoes, Hail Hit Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Spring thunderstorms spawned tornadoes and pounded Oklahoma with
hail and winds gusting to 75 mph that destroyed a mobile home,
killing a woman, while in Utah a snowstorm was blamed for a fatal
car-train collision.
   Frigid air followed the storm that hit Utah on Monday, and the
National Weather Service warned fruit farmers the low temperatures
could hurt crops today.
   Thunderstorms swept through central, eastern and southwestern
Oklahoma on Monday.
   A tornado touched down in southwest Oklahoma City, and
unconfirmed tornadoes were reported in nearby Mustang, Harrah and
Midwest City. Another touched down just northwest of Little Rock,
Ark.
   In Oklahoma City, high winds destroyed a mobile home in the
Sherwood Homes trailer park, said authorities, who could not
confirm reports of a tornado.
   Lillian Robinson, 69, was dead on arrival at Midwest City
Hospital, an unidentified spokesman said. Her husband, who was not
identified, was hospitalized in serious condition.
   The wind shoved some mobile homes off their foundations and
shook others, said trailer park resident Mike McFarland.
   ``It was a very loud noise,'' McFarland said.
   High winds also threw half a dozen trailers onto their sides at
a trailer company in Oklahoma City, and damaged roofs on city hall,
a fast food restaurant and a funeral home in Mustang, officials
said.
   Hail up to 4 inches in diameter was reported around the state,
the weather service said.
   To the north, thunderstorms dropped golf ball-size hail just
west of Quincy, Ill., and marble-size hail at Leavenworth, Kan.
   The Utah snowstorm caused about 50 accidents, most of them
fender benders, the state Highway Patrol reported.
   At the height of the storm, a freight train collided with a car,
killing driver Villiami S. Pauni, 39, said Salt Lake County
Sheriff's Cpl. Ron Little. The train engineer sounded his horn and
the crossing signal was working, but the car apparently slid into
the train's path, Little said.
   A snowstorm in central Colorado also left roads icy, triggering
numerous accidents. In Montana, a snow storm left up to a foot of
snow.
</TEXT>
