<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Latin     03-29 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Latin,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latin Nations Denounce Foreign Intervention in Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR HUGO CARVAJAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Latin American nations met in
emergency session at Panama's request and were asked to denounce
foreign intervention in Panama and call on the United States to end
economic measures aimed at toppling Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   A formal regional position on the crisis in Panama is to be
drawn up later at the extraordinary meeting of the 26-member Latin
American Economic System.
   The organization, based in Caracas, was founded in 1976 as an
economic forum for Latin American countries.
   The organization is expected to reject any foreign intervention
in Panama, while urging that Panamanian military and civilian
leaders abide soon with the promise of free national elections,
delegates at the meeting Monday said.
   Individual nations, including Mexico and Venezuela, already
indicated their opposition to outside interference in Panama's
affairs, without specifically mentioning the United States by name.
   Noriega, who as military chief also is Panama's strongman, was
indicted on federal drug trafficking and money-laundering charges
in the United States, and President Reagan says Noriega must go.
Noriega denies the charges. The Reagan administration also has
frozen Panamanian government funds in U.S. banks, denying this
country a supply of dollars, the official Panamanian currency.
   In an hourlong speech Monday, Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge
Abadia Arias asked the delegates for support against U.S.
``economic aggression'' which he claimed is meant to keep the
Panama Canal under U.S. control.
   ``Panama is suffering the most cruel economic strangulation seen
on our continent, within a strategy of domination with which the
U.S. hopes to replace the wars of annexation that the world thought
were long gone,'' Abadia said.
   Manuel Rodriguez Arriaga, Mexico's subsecretary of international
cooperation, rejected ``any act of foreign intervention to
influence the destiny of Panama.''
   ``We cannot permit that someone tells us from outside what is
good or bad. Today it is Panama, yesterday many others, and
tomorrow anybody,'' Rodriguez said. He called for U.S. economic
measures against Panama to cease.
   Venezuela's acting foreign minister, Horacio Arteaga, rejected
foreign intervention in Panama, but reiterated Venezuelan support
for ``revitalization of democracy in Panama.''
   ``We fervently hope that when Panama assumes full sovereignty
over the canal, its people will have consolidated their democratic
institutions,'' Arteaga said.
   He said Venezuela would like Panama's government to make good
very quickly its promise of free national elections.
   Delegates from other countries asked Panamana to call for free
elections this year rather than next, sources at the meeting said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   One delegate, also speaking on condition of not being
identified, said, ``Most Latin Americans would like Gen. Noriega to
leave, not to be toppled.'' In general, Latin American nations have
rejected the interference of the Panamanian military in the
civilian government and called their ambassadors home for
consultations. The meeting was expected to end today.
</TEXT>
