<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0644EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Austria-Kurds     03-29 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Austria-Kurds,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurds Apparently Suffering From Mustard Gas Wounds Arrive For
Treatment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six people apparently injured by mustard
gas allegedly used in Iraqi attacks on Kurdish villages arrived
here today for medical treatment. More than 30 others were to be
taken to other cities.
   Dr. Gerhard Freilinger, department head of Vienna's University
Clinic plastic surgery, said after talking with some of the
patients, their injuries appeared to be from mustard gas that may
have been mixed with a nerve gas.
   Freilinger, who since 1984 has treated about 30 victims of
alleged chemical weapons attacks in the 7{-year-old Persian Gulf
war, said the effects on the lungs of the patients indicated they
suffered from the effects of mustard gas.
   Freilinger spoke to reporters at an airport where the injured
arrived aboard an Iran Airlines ambulance plane.
   It was possible the mustard gas was ``in combination with a
light nerve gas, because they all have bad headaches, are dizzy and
(some) may have been unconscious,'' he said.
   Mustard gas is heavier than air, which would explain how it
seeped into cellars where the patients said they had been hiding
during the March 16 and 17 attacks, Freilinger said.
   Iran has said the Iraq dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on
three Kurdish towns in Iraq, killing 5,000 people and injuring
5,000. The attacks on the towns, which were captured in an Iranian
offensive, occurred March 16-17.
   Freilinger said two of the patients, a child and a severely
wounded Iranian soldier, were to be placed in the intensive care
unit at his university clinic. The four others _ three women and a
man _ were to be brought to private clinics in Vienna.
   The remaining Kurds on board the plane were to be carried on to
Geneva, Frankfurt, London and then New York.
   Freilinger said about 50 percent of about 30 patients he has
treated since 1984 survived, but added that patients only arrived
for treatment after 10 or 15 days, meaning that the damage done by
the gas could not be reversed.
   An Iranian soldier Freilinger had removed from the plane in
Vienna was originally to go on to New York. However, Freilinger
said the man's injuries were so severe, that he could not continue
the trip.
   Freilinger said poison gas penetrates everything including
clothes. ``They can't run away from it because if they do, they
breath it in even deeper,'' he said. He said mustard gas causes
changes in the lungs that can lead to suffocation. He said it could
also destroy the bone marrow and causes burns on the skin.
   Freilinger said in 1984 he had visited areas allegedly bombed
with chemical weapons and had taken a sample of the gas for
verification and testing.
   In the past Iran has sent soldiers allegedly poisoned by mustard
gas to Vienna and other European cities for treatment. In July,
Iranian civilians were brought for treatment for the first time.
   On board the plane, patients with burns on their hands, backs
and faces coughed violently or lay motionless on stretchers.
   One child of six who Iranian and Kurdish officials said had lost
her entire family in the attack, sobbed constantly and called for
her parents.
   Iran's Ambassador to Austria, Hossein Noghrehkar Shirazi was at
the airport when the plane arrived as were representatives of
several Kurdish groups.
   In downtown Vienna on Monday police arrested 60 people at a
Kurdish demonstration in front of the Iraqi Embassy against
chemical weapons attacks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
