<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0710EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Flooding     03-29 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Flooding,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Reported Killed In German Flooding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH JAUTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rhine River stopped just short of
pouring into a section of Cologne today, and two people in Bavaria
apparently died when another flooded river swept away their vehicle.
   The Rhine stabilized at 32.3 feet. At 32.5 feet, the river would
have entered Cologne's low-lying old town area. Experts predicted
the Rhine floodwaters will slowly begin to recede.
   Rescue workers searched today for a Volkswagen bus with two
people that witnesses said was swept away by the flooded Main river
in the Bavarian city of Wuerzburg, where streets along the banks of
the river were inundated.
   Police said the witnesses reported seeing the headlights of the
vehicle in the floodwaters and heard cries for help. The vehicle
had disappeared by the time rescue workers arrived in boats, police
said.
   Over the weekend and on Monday, rising waters in Bavaria forced
the evacuation of thousands of residents and farm animals. On
Monday, the Danube river burst through dikes in at least five
locations, causing the region's worst flooding in 70 years,
authorities said.
   If the death of the two people in Wuerzburg is confirmed, the
flood-related death toll would climb to five. An elderly man died
Monday after suffering a heart attack in the flooded upper Bavarian
town of Straubing, and a 61-year-old Koblenz man and 3-year-old boy
from Bamberg died over the weekend.
   In Bavaria, 3,500 residents were evacuated from homes near
Straubing, 30 miles north of Munich, late Sunday and early Monday.
   At least 2,500 cows, pigs, and other farm animals were also
taken to higher grounds as floodwaters spilled into the farms and
pastures of upper Bavaria.
   ``If the rain does not stop soon, this could get much worse,''
Hans Voggenreiter, a Straubing official, told The Associated Press
on Monday. He said residents were evacuated by rowboats, powerboats
and ``whatever was available.'' He added: ``Most were taken in by
relatives and friends. The rest are being cared for in schools and
public auditoriums.''
   Nearly 900 volunteers worked throughout the day Monday filling
sandbags and shoring up the earthen dams that line the Danube near
Straubing, Regensburg and other upper Bavarian towns.
   Floodwaters had also entered parts of the ancient city of
Regensburg, as well as sections of Passau, 80 miles to the east.
   Officials said flooding along the Neckar and Mosel rivers was
receding, but the Rhine continued to climb.
   The rising Rhine forced authorities to close parts of a major
highway between Mainz and Koblenz on Monday, and disrupted train
traffic through the valley. Travellers reported delays of several
hours for some trains, and said others were rerouted away from
riverside tracks.
   Riverside sidewalks and some streets in Bonn, the federal
capital, had disappeared beneath the Rhine's floodwaters.
   Residents of the large villas that line the Rhine at the Bonn
district of Bad Godesberg, home to many embassies and ambassadors'
residents, were using pumps to dry out their flooded cellars and
preparing sandbags.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
