<DOCNO> AP880329-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0719EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HemingwayContest     03-29 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hemingway Contest,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Columnist's Parody Wins Lighthearted Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evening came, and then the people were in
the little room apart, drinking wine and reading, drinking and
reading for hours that night. It was good wine and good reading.
   It was not exactly Ernest Hemingway, but a spirited review of
loving parodies of the famed novelist's crisp, masculine style.
   One of the literary lampoons, chosen from 21 finalists by a
dozen well-lubricated judges, won the Eleventh International
Imitation Hemingway Competition on Monday.
   ``It was now morning, and he was in the bathroom shaving,
shaving for the first time that day, but not the last; no, never
the last,'' begins the winning entry, which ends with a groanworthy
pun.
   The parody by Gordon ``Satch'' Carlson of Anchorage, Alaska, met
the key rule of the lighthearted contest: to sound like Hemingway
and read like Hemingway. To ``know that funny is good and very
funny is very good.''
   Carlson, a high school English teacher, newspaper and magazine
columnist and self-described ``social gadfly,'' said in a telephone
interview that he had no trouble imitating Hemingway's distinctive
style.
   ``Actually, I've been accused of writing Hemingway parodies when
I'm not trying,'' he said.
   Carlson's work continued: ``The hairs kept coming, tiny hairs
and black and there was nothing for it, nothing for it at all but
shaving ....''
   The 350-word parody went on and on, discussing the hirsute
portions of a man's body. It then described an estranged woman,
then more shaving, drinking wine, and then drinking more wine.
   The climax came when the man cut himself.
   ``She turned, lifting her thin American lip over those thin,
white, perfect, American teeth, and that thin American sneer. `It's
only a nick, Adams,' she said.' ''
   Nick Adams was a character in several of Hemingway's short
stories.
   Carlson maintains that Hemingway's short stories, rather than
his novels, are key to the writer's work. He said most of the lines
for his parody came from his favorite Hemingway story, ``The Short
Happy Life of Francis Macomber.''
   Carlson, who was vacationing in Seattle when he learned he won,
gets a round trip for two to Italy, with dinners at Harry's Bar in
Florence.
   The other 20 finalists, each straining the language to produce
literary lookalikes of Hemingway's terse, manly style, were among
2,432 entries from all 50 states and more than a dozen foreign
countries.
   The judges included authors Ray Bradbury, Barnaby Conrad and
Cyra McFadden and poet Lawrence Ferlinghetti. It was the first time
the contest was held outside Los Angeles.
   One would-be Hemingway wrote, ``The president looked at the
woman he called Nancy ... other men also called her Nancy.''
   Sticking to the political season, another contestant told how in
the spring, a fellow named Gary ``took the young woman to the
Bahamas, avoiding reporters and living on rum and sun and the catch
of the day ... he had not taken his wife.''
   Another competitor was taken with a large fellow named Jose, ``a
fellow who could laugh in such a large way when the bird sat on his
cigar, (a) cigar the size of a monkey's arm.''
   One entry dealt with ``A Farewell To Arms, Legs, Feet and
Neck,'' while another sought glitter in ``A Farewell to Lunch.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
