<HEAD>Emmy-winning TV Writer Albert Schwartz Dead at 77</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emmy award-winning writer Albert Schwartz,
who created scripts for such TV and radio shows as ``The Bob Hope
Show,'' ``Here's Lucy,'' and ``Gilligan's Island,'' died of
complications from emphysema. He was 77.
   Schwartz, who died Saturday, was part of the original writing
team for ``The Bob Hope Show,'' when it went on radio in 1938.
   His first TV credits came in 1955 for ``The Milton Berle Show''
and ``December Bride.''
   He later wrote for ``Gilligan's Island'' and three television
movies based on the series. He also wrote for ``Petticoat
Junction,'' ``Chico and the Man,'' ``Good Times'' and ``The Brady
Bunch.''
   Schwartz, nominated twice for Emmys, shared the award in 1961
for his work on several episodes of ``The Red Skelton Show.''
   He is survived by his wife, Mimi, two sons, two daughters, six
grandchildren and two brothers.
</TEXT>
