<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Rebels     03-29 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Businessman Fatally Shot; State of Alert For Rebel
Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a Japanese nightclub
owner today, and the military said it captured two top communist
rebel leaders during an early morning raid on a hideout in suburban
Manila.
   The military, meanwhile, was on alert to guard against attacks
by communist guerrillas marking their army's 19th anniversary.
   Police said Akihiro Sato, was shot near Manila airport. He was
taken to a nearby hospital where he died of bullet wounds in the
neck and shoulder.
   Police Pvt. 1st Class Bert Hipolito said investigators had no
idea who Sato's killers were. A Japanese friend of the victim who
declined to be identified told reporters at the hospital that Sato,
48, was a native of Tsuchiura City in Japan's Ibaraki Prefecture,
where he owned a nightclub.
   The source said Sato frequently visited Manila on business trips
and was to have returned to Japan today. He arrived March 20 and
was reported to have a Filipino wife. The Japanese Embassy said it
was trying to obtain more information and could make no further
comment.
   Armed forces chief Gen. Renato de Villa told a news conference
today that authorities captured Rafael Baylosis, secretary-general
of the Communist Party of the Philippines, and Benjamin de Vera,
central committee member in charge of operations on Mindanao, the
country's second largest island.
   ``This is certainly a big loss to the Communist Party of the
Philippines because these are very high-ranking personalities who
have been subject of many manhunts and many operations in the
past,'' de Villa said.
   Brig. Gen. Alexander Aguirre, overall commander of security
forces in the capital, said the two were arrested during a raid on
a hideout at the Manila suburb of San Juan early today.
   Armed forces spokesman Col. Oscar Florendo said the military was
on alert today in anticipation of possible rebel attacks. The alert
covered five regions, including Manila, northern, southern and
central Luzon and parts of the central Philippine Visayas islands.
   President Corazon Aquino told reporters she ordered Executive
Secretary Catalino Macaraig to summon the mayors of 13 towns and
four cities that comprise the Philippine capital to a meeting to
plan safety measures.
   No major rebel attacks were reported today, but reports of
attacks in the countryside often take days to reach Manila.
   The 24,000-strong New People's Army, part of the outlawed
Communist Party of the Philippines, traditionally observes its
founding anniversary by attacking government installations and
executing ``enemies of the people.''
</TEXT>
