<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Threatens To Use Chemical Weapons Against Iran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6-7th grafs pvs ``Iran claims....'' to clarify, give
names of towns reported attacked. Picks up 8th graf pvs ``Kurdistan
is ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>^By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq today said its warplanes attacked
two supertankers off Iran in the Persian Gulf and threatened to use
chemical weapons against major Iranian cities.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted a
military spokesman as saying Iraqi warplanes hit two ``very large
maritime targets,'' or supertankers, off the Iran coast during the
night.
   There was no immediate confirmation of the report, which
provided no other details. News of Iraqi raids in Iranian tankers
are difficult to verify because of an Iranian news blackout on such
incidents.
   Nuri Nayef, director of the Cairo office of the Iraqi News
Agency, today said an ``authorized Iraqi spokesman'' told him
``Iraq might choose a number of large Iranian cities to be the
targets of chemical weapons as a deterrent and punitive measure.''
   Nayef, who spoke to reporters in Cairo, said the unidentified
spokesman said Iran deployed chemical weapons in Iraq's
northeastern Kurdistan region and that Iraq may respond to stop the
Iranians from doing so again.
   Iran claims Iraq dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on three
towns in Kurdistan, killing 5,000 Kurds and injuring 5,000. The
attacks on the town of Halabja and the nearby villages of Khormal
and Dojaila reportedly began March 16 and continued over the next
few days.
   Western reporters have seen victims of chemical weapons at
hospitals in Halabja, which they visited with Iranian guides, and
in Tehran. Survivors told them chemical bombs were dropped by
Iraqi, not Iranian, planes.
   Kurdistan is where the majority of Iraq's 3.5 million Kurds
live. Most of them have been fighting the Baghdad government for
autonomy in the mountainous region. They are backed by Iran.
   Baghdad has neither confirmed nor denied the use of the outlawed
weapons. But a statement by Iraq's ruling Revolutionary Command
Council on Saturday said Iraq has the right to defend itself ``with
all available weapons.''
   On Monday, the official Islamic Republic News Agency, also
monitored in Nicosia, said Iran's Revolutionary Guards had killed
or wounded 300 Iraqis in the latest battle of an Iranian thrust
into the Kurdistan region.
   The news agency quoted Revolutionary Guards Minister Mohsen
Rafiq-Doust as saying the Iranians have overrun 540 square miles of
the region.
   The Iranians also have pushed 15 miles into the Darbandikhan
region, east of Iraq's Kirkuk oilfields, communiques said.
   Iran claims to have killed or wounded nearly 13,500 Iraqis,
captured more than 5,000 and destroyed 225 tanks and armored
vehicles since March 16.
   Iraq has admitted losing territory in Kurdistan.
   But if the Iranian claim is confirmed, it would mark Iraq's
biggest military setback since the Iranians battled to within six
miles of the southern city of Basra early last year and occupied
wetlands east of it.
   Iran also claimed its air force fighters downed two Iraqi
warplanes in the Kurdistan battle zone Monday. Iraq admitted losing
only one aircraft.
   In another development, rebels fighting Iran's government with
backing from Iraq said Monday their National Liberation Army
launched a major offensive on a 15-mile front in Iran's
southwestern Khuzestan province near the town of Shush.
   Iran acknowledged the attack, but said more than 1,000 Iraqi
soldiers and NLA ``counter-revolutionaries'' were killed and the
advanced was foiled.
</TEXT>
