<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Mediation,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Call On Roman Catholic Archbishop To Mediate Panamanian Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former president of Venezuela will
fly to Panama to ask the Roman Catholic archbishop to try to
mediate an end to the crisis over the strongman-rule of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica and Spanish Prime Minister
Felipe Gonzalez told a news conference Monday they would ask
Panamanian Monsignor Marco Antonio McGrath to seek a peaceful
solution to Panama's devastating political and economic situation.
   They said former Venezuelan President Carlos Andres Perez will
go to Panama to present the request to McGrath. No schedule was
given.
   Arias, Gonzalez and Perez met Sunday and Monday in the resort of
Guanamara, 220 miles north of San Jose.
   Gonzalez is on a four-day visit to Costa Rica. He said Noriega
has not sought asylum in Spain, but if he does it will be granted
with the assurance he would not be extradicted to the United States
where he is under a federal indictment in Flordia on charges of
drug trafficking.
   The Spanish leader told the news conference an ``immediate
solution is necessary to end the anguish and the pain of the
Panamanian people and we believe that if Archbishop McGrath agrees
to mediate, it would be a very important point.''
   He said he and Arias ``are reasonably optimistic that there will
be a rapid solution in Panama.''
   Arias said he wanted McGrath ``to serve as mediator ... not only
between the Civic Crusade and President Manuel Solis Palma but also
with all the political parties to find a solution to the crisis in
Panama.''
   The National Civic Crusade is a coalition of about 200 business,
professional, student and union groups. It has been trying since
June to force Noriega to step down as commander of the
15,000-member Defense Forces that includes the armed forces and
police. Arias also said Noriega should resign from the post, which
the general has used to dominate the government.
   Noriega picked Solis Palma as the new chief execuive on Feb. 26,
the day after President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire Noriega
and instead was ousted from office. Delvalle is living in hiding in
Panama and is still recognized by the United States as the
country's legal president.
   Arias won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize as author of a peace plan
signed last August by the presidents of the five Central American
countries, Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Costa
Rica, designed to end regional conflicts.
</TEXT>
