<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0810EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Diet-Aging     03-29 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diet-Aging,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low-Calorie Diet Shown to Prolong Rats' Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists seeking to explain the longer
lifespan of rats fed low-calorie diets are not recommending that
people follow such a strict regimen, but merely that they eat
sensibly.
   ``I think the studies support the wisdom of what is commonly
referred to as a prudent diet,'' said Dr. Richard Weindruch of the
National Institute on Aging. ``Don't overload yourself with
calories.''
   Scientists from a range of disciplines gathered Monday at the
University of Notre Dame to analyze a study in which about 200 rats
fed 30 percent fewer calories than a similar-sized group lived an
average of 20 percent longer. The conference continues through
today.
   While the link between a restricted diet and longer life is
long-established, the researchers are trying to find out why diet
tends to slow down the aging process.
   An immunologist suggested suggested lower food intake kept the
animals' immune systems strong. Other results were less conclusive,
but Weindruch cautioned against issuing hasty advice.
   ``The studies at present do not justify a recommendation to the
general public of severe caloric restriction, or even moderate
caloric restriction, because there are so many difficulties in
translation between the animal model and the human situation,'' he
said.
   Immunology researcher Dr. Yoon Kim of Chicago speculated that
the restricted diet may have exposed the rats to fewer antigens _
or disease-causing agents in the food _ to which the immune system
reacts by producing antibodies.
   ``In a restricted diet, the tendency is not to use up'' the
immune system's ability to fight disease, said Kim. ``Life, and
healthy life, is due to restriction of diet, maintaining the
potential of the defense system, not using it unnecessarily.''
   Thirty-two researchers in the United States and Canada were sent
tissue samples for analysis from the 400 rats raised at Notre
Dame's Lobund Laboratory in a study supported by the Chicago-based,
non-profit Retirement Research Foundation.
   The study involved 400 rats, half of which were fed 12 grams of
food per day, or about 70 percent of normal, with fat limited to 5
percent.
   Animals on restricted diet lived an average of 38 months, an
increase of nearly 20 percent above the control group, scientists
said.
   The rats on restricted diets were healthier in their old age and
developed fewer cancers of the prostate and liver. The rats also
suffered less disease of the heart and brain and had
better-functioning immune systems, scientists said.
   Dr. Gilbert Boissonneault, a clinical nutritionist from the
University of Kentucky, said he found no difference in body fat
content between the two groups of rats.
   Dr. Gibbons Cornwell III, a professor of medicine at Dartmouth
College, found extensive weakening of heart muscle in all rats, but
less in the diet-restricted animals.
   Additional studies will look at the glandular system and
gastrointestinal tract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
