<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissileTests     03-29 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missile Tests,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Successfully Tests Two Cruise Missiles Over Florida, Alabama
Coasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EGLIN AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two unarmed Tomahawk cruise
missiles flew 800 miles over rural Florida and Alabama in a
simulated ship-to-land attack, then parachuted down to a test
range, a Navy spokesman said.
   The missiles, 18 feet long and 21 inches around, were fired from
Navy destroyers in the Gulf of Mexico, according to Bob Holsapple,
a spokesman for the Cruise Missile Project in Washington.
   ``These were the eighth and ninth successful tests over the
Florida and Alabama test range,'' he said Monday. ``The flight
route took the missiles over sparsely and non-populated areas
only.''
   The exact course of the missiles and the identity of the ships
they were fired from was classified, he said.
   The missiles, fired at 10 a.m. CST Sunday and 3 p.m. CST Monday,
traveled at 500 mph at altitudes varying from 500 to 6,000 feet. It
took one hour and 45 minutes to complete the tests, Holsapple said.
   Seconds after being launched from the destroyers, the missiles
dropped their solid-fuel rocket boosters and switched to their
cruise missile engine.
   They flew ``a fully-guided test flight over approximately 800
miles over portions of Florida and Alabama and then terminated at
the Eglin Air Force Base test range,'' he said.
   The Tomahawks were guided to Florida's west coast by their
on-board navigation system. Once over land, their guidance system
adjusted course using an on-board computerized ``terrain contour
matching system,'' Holsapple said.
   The Tomahawk cruise missile, which is designed to fly close to
the ground to avoid radar detection, is deployed on destroyers,
cruisers, battleships and attack submarines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
