<DOCNO> AP880329-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0837EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArgentineGeneral     03-29 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentine General,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Prisoner Faces `Lord of Death and Life'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horacio Martinez-Baca was a labor union
lawyer in Argentina when the military took control there 12 years
ago. Six days after the coup, Martinez-Baca was arrested and began
a four-year nightmare of imprisonment and torture.
   ``They laid me down on a table. They tied my arms and legs. They
put electric shocks on my genitals and my gums, and they asked who
were my friends,'' Martinez-Baca testified Monday.
   A few feet away in the hushed courtroom sat Carlos Suarez Mason,
64, a former general who oversaw the military prisons in which
Martinez-Baca was held.
   ``The prisoners used to call him the lord of death and life,''
Martinez-Baca said.
   The former prisoner, testifying in a $10 million lawsuit against
Suarez Mason, said the 90-minute torture session occurred about a
month after he was arrested in March 1976 and was repeated several
times before his release in April 1980.
   There were also beatings, freezing showers, death threats, and
``probably the worst torture,'' solitary confinement in an
unheated, windowless cell for days at a time, he said.
   Suarez Mason, former commander of the First Army Corps in Buenos
Aires, was arrested in January 1987 at his home in Foster City,
just south of San Francisco, more than three years after fleeing
Argentina.
   He faces extradition on charges of 43 murders and 23
kidnappings, allegedly committed by soldiers under his command from
1976 to 1979 during a military campaign against suspected leftists.
   The civil suit by Martinez-Baca is one of three by Argentinians
now living in the United States who say they were imprisoned and
tortured, or their relatives were killed, by Suarez Mason's forces.
   U.S. courts have allowed suits against foreigners in their
jurisdiction for certain types of human rights violations,
including torture, prolonged detention and summary execution.
   U.S. District Judge Samuel Conti declared a default March 15
after the former general failed to respond to the suit or answer
pre-trial questions, claiming he had spent his last $100,000 on
lawyers in the extradition case. The judge ruled that the trial
would be limited to the amount in damages Suarez Mason must pay.
   At Monday's session, San Francisco attorney Ray Archuleta
appeared and said he was representing Suarez Mason, who declared he
was now willing to answer questions. But Conti said Suarez Mason
had no right to take part in a hearing after a default and ordered
Archuleta to the back of the courtroom.
   Martinez-Baca, a former local government official in Mendoza,
Argentina, said his nearly blind father, a former state governor,
was arrested along with his mother and brother on the day the
military took power. Six days later, two plainclothes police
arrested him in his apartment.
   He said he was never told why he was beng held.
   One of the most frightening events of his imprisonment was being
flown from one military prison to another. He had heard about other
prisoners thrown out of helicopters alive, Martinez-Baca said.
Another time, when he was led away for interrogation and torture,
his jailers told him to say his last words and acted as if he would
be killed, he said.
   The military finally allowed him to leave the country in 1980
just as Argentina's Supreme Court was about to order his release,
Martinez-Baca said. He arrived at the home of a sponsoring
Presbyterian minister in Berkeley speaking no English, separated
from his family and about 70 pounds lighter than when he was
imprisoned, he said.
   Though he still fears retaliation from the Argentine military,
he said, he filed the suit as ``a deterrent for people who think
they are the master of life and death.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
