<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     03-29 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs ,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Sikh Militants Kill 17 in Punjab</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sikh militants sprayed a
wedding party with rifle fire, killing 10 people, and fatally shot
seven other people elsewhere in the northern Punjab state, police
said today.
   Among the victims of the suspected guerrillas were the bride and
bridegroom and four children aged 1 to 5 who were with the wedding
party, authorities said.
   Five Sikhs were slain in attacks in Gurdaspur and Kapurthala
districts, according to police in Chandigarh, the Punjab capital.
Two Hindus were also shot dead in Jalandhar in the attacks late
Monday and today, they said.
   Four men armed with AK-47 assault rifles opened fire at random
Monday night on the Sikh wedding party of about 20 people in the
village of Johramadan, 18 miles south of Amritsar, police said.
   The attackers escaped, leaving behind a note that claimed the
victims were police informers. It was signed ``Khalistan Liberation
Force,'' according to Police Superintendent Izhar Alam.
   Khalistan is the name Sikh militants use for the independent
nation they demand be created in Punjab.
   The latest deaths raised to more than 560 the number of people
killed in attacks in Punjab blamed on Sikh militants since the
beginning of the year.
   The Sikhs, whose religion combines Hinduism and Islam, make up
about 2 percent of India's population. They are a majority,
however, in the rich farming state of Punjab. The militants say
they need a separate nation to protect their faith from domination
by Hindus, who are more than 80 percent of India's people.
</TEXT>
