<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SelvageExecution     03-29 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Selvage Execution,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Execution Back on Schedule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The execution of a man condemned for
murdering a sheriff's deputy can go forward Wednesday, an appellate
court said, but lawyers for the man said they will appeal to the
Supreme Court.
   John Henry Selvage, 37, is scheduled to be executed before dawn.
The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals late Monday vacated the stay
for Selvage that was granted Friday by U.S. District Judge Norman
Black of Houston.
   Selvage was convicted of capital murder in the death July 30,
1979, of Harris County Sheriff's Deputy Albert Garza.
   Black had granted the reprieve while the appellate court
reconsiders the appeal of another death row inmate from Harris
County, Leon Rutherford King. King is questioning the selection of
jurors during his trial.
   David Cunningham, Selvage's attorney, said he would appeal to
the Surpreme Court today. He said the appeal will be based on
several issues, including instructions to jurors on mitigating
circumstances, a matter the court is considering in the case of
Texas death row inmate Donald Gene Franklin.
   Garza was trying to prevent a robbery at a jewelry store in
Houston but had not drawn his weapon at the time he was shot.
   Selvage has been granted at least four postponements or stays
for scheduled executions.
</TEXT>
