<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceProbe     03-29 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Probe,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cops Will Be Deputized As Federal Marshals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. attorney said city police officers can
be trusted to help investigate charges of corruption on their own
force.
   Affidavits released in federal court here last week revealed
that FBI informants have accused several New Orleans police
officers working in the French Quarter of crimes including drug
dealing, accepting bribes and burglary.
   Some officers will be deputized as federal marshals as part of
an effort to investigate the charges, U.S. Attorney John Volz said
at a news conference Monday.
   Police Superintendent Warren Woodfork wouldn't say who among his
investigators would be deputized. But both he and Volz said they
were confident the deputy marshals would investigate their own
department thoroughly.
   ``We have no reason at all to have any lack of trust in the
superintendent or in anyone he designates,'' said Volz.
   The affidavits unsealed last week were filed by the FBI over two
years to support requests for permission to place wiretaps on
businesses and residences of reputed organized crime figures
believed to be involved in drug smuggling.
   In those affidavits, two unidentified FBI informants are said to
have accused officers of crimes. One officer is accused of selling
cocaine. Another is accused of burglarizing a warehouse.
   An informant also said officers who worked off-duty guard
details for businesses sometimes made questionable arrests at the
behests of their off-duty bosses.
</TEXT>
