<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Continues In Stepanakert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: NEW thruout with newspaper report of strike in Stepanakert,
details of Sumgait deaths and Gerasimov comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of a disputed region in the republic of
Azerbaijan shut down their main city for a second day today to
protest the government's refusal to transfer the region to
neighboring Armenia, a newspaper said.
   ``My report today will be short,'' P. Gutiontov, a correspondent
for the government newspaper Izvestia wrote from Stepanakert.
``City enterprises are at standstill, people are home.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov also told a
regular news briefing that some workers in Stepanakert stayed home
from their jobs.
   ``Certain enterprises are not functioning or are partially not
functioning,'' he said.
   Stepanakert is the biggest city in Nagorno-Karabakh, a region in
Azerbaijan which Armenians want annexed to Armenia. Activists said
a general strike began last Wednesday in the mostly Armenian area.
   In a separate report, the afternoon newspaper Izvestia provided
the first breakdown of casualties in Sumgait, an Azerbaijani city
where ethnic rioting broke out Feb. 28. It confirmed the official
death toll of 32, and said 26 of them were Armenians while six were
Azeris.
   Activists have claimed the death toll was much higher.
   Gerasimov said residents of Yerevan, the Armenian capital, went
to work as usual. He reiterated that the government would not be
forced into appeasing Armenian demands to annex Nagorno-Karabakh.
   ``We cannot solve the problem by mechanically transferring this
region as some Armenian officials want,'' he said. ``The more you
study this problem the more you will see the whole thing is not as
simple as that, as merely saying Nagorno-Karabakh must be part of
Armenia.''
   Also today, a Moscow dissident said police on Monday evening
broke up a demonstration by more than 50 people who demanded
freedom for a jailed Armenian activist and carried signs saying,
``We don't believe in perestroika.''
   The dissident, Tamara Grigoryants, said she received her
information about the protest in a telephone conversation with
members of a committee promoting Armenian self-determination in
Yerevan.
   Police did not interfere with an earlier demonstration Monday in
Yerevan by more than 100 people, but dispersed the second group,
she said.
   She said her telephone call was interrupted and she could not
find out other details, including whether there were any arrests.
   Both groups demanded freedom for jailed nationalist leader
Paryur Arikyan, she said.
   Arikyan was arrested in Yerevan after being detained by police
in Moscow, where he had provided information to foreign journalists
about events in Armenia. Dissident sources say they have learned he
has been charged under a law prohibiting spreading false
information about the Soviet Union.
   The signs against perestroika were a challenge to Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his broad effort to restructure Soviet
society. The Soviet government last week declared Armenian
agitation for annexation of Nagorno-Karabakh intolerable but
released a plan to improve economic and social conditions in the
region.
   Gorbachev has appealed for patience and said that the
policy-making Communist Party Central Committee will discuss the
dispute in an upcoming meeting on relations between the Soviet
Union's more than 100 nationalities.
   Officials have pledged a cultural and economic development plan
for Nagorno-Karabakh, apparently instead of meeting the Armenian
demand to annex the territorty.
   The newspaper Sovietskaya Kultura said today the plan would cost
up to $640 million.
   ``These millions, which are so necessary now for restructuring,
the country is giving to Karabakh,'' it said in a front-page
article tracing the unrest to poor social and economic conditions.
   Sovietskaya Kultura backed the Soviet leadership's plan to
improve conditions, even though Armenian activists have said
specifically that improvement of education, cultural facilities and
economic conditions will not solve the problem.
   The newspaper said there is almost a complete absence of
schoolbooks in the Armenian language, no teaching of Armenian
history and that residents of Nagorno-Karabakh could not receive
Armenian television.
   It said each resident of the area would have a separate
apartment or home by the year 2,000 and that the government would
build two reservoirs to improve the water supply to Stepanakert.
</TEXT>
