<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Fighting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0554,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills At Least Four Soviets In Kabul</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The bomb ...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
Soviets denying report of Soviet deaths. PICKS up 5th graf `Earlier
Sunday ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb planted in a jeep killed at
least four Soviets in Kabul, and an Afghan Politburo member
narrowly escaped assassination when a bomb blew up a bridge,
Western diplomatic sources said today.
   The Politburo member was wounded and two of his bodyguards died,
the diplomats said.
   The violence in the Afghan capital coincided with reports of
clashes in northern and eastern Afghanistan between Soviet-backed
government forces and anti-communist Moslem guerrillas, the
diplomats said. They spoke on condition of anonymity.
   In Moscow, a Soviet spokesman denied that Soviets had been
killed in the attack Sunday.
   ``This is not true. Nothing of this kind has happened,'' said
Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov. The spokesman said
he had talked with the Soviet ambassador in Kabul.
   Diplomats said the bomb blew up a jeep and killed at least four
Soviets. It also gutted a shop, blew over a tree and hurled debris
several hundred yards. The explosion occurred in a shopping
district of the Afghan capital that is frequented mainly by
Soviets, diplomats said.
   Earlier Sunday, two bombs were defused near the central post
office and Ministry of Communications, the diplomats said. Two
other bombs were discovered and defused in mid-March in the
Ministry of the Interior, they said.
   The diplomats said other incidents in the capital indicated a
new flare-up of factionalism between the mainly urban Parcham wing
and the rural Khalq wing of the ruling People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan.
   The sources said a car bomb exploded March 23 on a bridge
spanning the Kabul river as Khalqi Politburo member Saleh Mohammad
Zeary was driving by, wounding him and killing two bodyguards
riding in a separate car.
   On March 19, national police of the Interior Ministry and secret
police of the State Security Ministry got into a firefight that
killed several Interior police, the diplomats said.
   Both forces are charged with maintaining security in Kabul but
the secret police are aligned with the Parchamis of President
Najib, former intelligence chief, while the national police are
predominantly Khalqi, as is the military.
   Despite the violence in Kabul, the sources said the traditional
battlefield in Paghman, west of the city, has become quiet as
guerrillas apparently have concentrated on resupplying with the
spring thaw.
   The diplomats said it was unclear whether the latest pattern in
fighting reflected expectations of a Soviet troop withdrawal, which
Moscow has said could begin in late spring.
   The Soviets sent troops to Afghanistan in December 1979 to help
the government battle Moslem insurgents. Some 115,000 Soviets
remain.
</TEXT>
