<2ND_LINE>PM-Conn Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush and Dukakis Lead In Connecticut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 3rd graf with voter turnout bgng ``But early'';
SUB 5th graf bgng ``A Hartford'' to add Simon poll figure; SUB 14th
graf bgng ``The newspaper'' to restore dropped figure to 64 percent</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush was likely to
win handily in Connecticut's Republican primary today while Jesse
Jackson hoped to give regional favorite Michael Dukakis a run for
his money in the Democratic contest.
   There are 52 Democratic delegates and 35 Republican delegates at
stake in the Connecticut contest. Voter registrars around the state
reported a surge of last-minute registrations before the noon
Monday deadline.
   But early reports from polling places indicated light turnout.
``It's very, very slow,'' Waterbury deputy Democratic registrar
Gloria Keaveney said. State officials predicted about a third of
the voters would turn out.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, has won all five New
England contests so far.
   A Hartford Courant newspaper poll conducted March 9-20 gave
Dukakis the support of 50 percent of Democrats likely to vote
Tuesday. Jackson had 16 percent and Paul Simon and Albert Gore Jr.
each had 3 percent. Twenty-seven percent were undecided. The poll
of 558 Democrats had a margin of error of 5 percentage points.
   Thirman Milner, Jackson's Connecticut chairman, estimated
Jackson would win at least 24 percent and possibly 30 percent.
   Dukakis has the support of Connecticut's top Democrats,
including Gov. William A. O'Neill, Sen. Christopher J. Dodd and
state Chairman John F. Droney.
   Droney, who is nominally supporting Dukakis, said his loss to
Jackson in Michigan made a strong showing _ 50 percent or better _
even more crucial in Connecticut. Dukakis rejected the thesis.
   ``Look _ a victory is a victory,'' Dukakis said at a news
conference.
   Droney said the results today will depend largely on voter
turnout.
   ``If you had all 650,000 Democrats in the state vote ... then I
think Dukakis would have 50 or 60 percent of the vote,'' Droney
said. ``But only 33 or 35 percent of them are going to vote and of
that ... a third of them are going to be Jackson people.''
   Bush grew up in Connecticut and still retains strong links here.
He was the son of a popular U.S. senator from the state and his
mother and brother still live in Greenwich.
   Bush beat Ronald Reagan in Conecticut's 1980 primary.
   The newspaper poll showed Bush with the support of 64 percent of
the 432 likely GOP voters Tuesday, while Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas
had 20 percent and Pat Robertson had 2 percent. The remaining 14
percent were undecided. The poll of Republicans had a margin of
error of 6 percent.
   Bush has the support of virtually all the GOP hierarchy in
Connecticut, including its four-member congressional delegation and
state Chairman Robert S. Poliner.
   Voter registrars around the state reported a surge of
last-minute registrations before the Monday noon deadline. In New
Haven, officials said hundreds signed up, while the estimate in
Hartford was 400 and in Bridgeport, 200.
   Voter registration figures provided last week by the secretary
of state's office showed that an estimated 648,000 Democrats and
430,000 Republicans were eligible to vote in today's primary. Party
leaders estimated that turnout would be between 30 percent and 40
percent.
</TEXT>
