<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1031EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionFunding     03-29 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Funding,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan AG: No Cutoff Of Funding Abortions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF HOLYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ban on state-funded abortions for poor
women has been put off at least until voters decide the issue this
fall.
   The ban had been scheduled to take effect Wednesday, but
Attorney General Frank Kelley on Monday postponed it until after
the Nov. 8 election.
   ``We simply have to accept his decision. We would like to
emphasize that the law was a duly enacted law, passed by
overwhelming majorities in both houses of the Legislature, and we
felt very strongly that it should go into effect,'' said Barbara
Listing, president of Right To Life of Michigan.
   Kelley said the law should be delayed because pro-choice forces
apparently gathered enough signatures to put the issue on the fall
ballot. Under the state constitution, getting a law put to a vote
suspends it.
   The signatures aren't expected to be certified until next month,
but Kelley said because the petitions appear to meet legal
requirements, the signatures must be presumed valid.
   His opinion carries the weight of law, unless overturned by a
circuit court.
   ``We have to be pleased that there will be no cutoff and that
health care for poor women will continue and we're pleased that
their health is going to be protected at least until November, when
voters go to the polls and settle this issue,'' said Judith Frey, a
spokeswoman for the People's Campaign for Choice.
   The measure easily passed the Legislature last year, and because
it had been initiated by a petition drive, it escaped the
gubernatorial veto that has scuttled 17 previous efforts to cut off
the funding.
   After the law was passed, anti-abortion forces contended it
should take effect immediately, but pro-choice groups sued, and the
courts ruled that it would take effect 90 days after the end of the
1987 legislative session.
   Meanwhile, the pro-choice forces started their own petition
drive, leading to the delay until voters decide the issue.
   Michigan is one of 14 states that uses taxpayer money to finance
abortions for the poor. In 1986, the most recent year for which a
final tally is available, Michigan paid $5.8 million for 18,600
abortions.
</TEXT>
