<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GeneticFingerprinting     03-29 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Genetic Fingerprinting,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King County Council Approves DNA Fingerprints For Sex Offenders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The King County Council has approved an ordinance
requiring sex offenders give up blood samples, which will provide a
``genetic fingerprint.''
   Under the law, which was passed Monday and takes effect Oct. 1,
people convicted of sex offenses will be required to surrender a
blood sample. Police will build a genetic library for future
investigations.
   ``It will be a huge step forward in our ability to apprehend and
prosecute rapists,'' said King County Councilman Ron Sims, one of
eight council members taking part in the unanimous vote.
   A spokesman for the American Civil Liberties Union endorsed
parts of the law but urged the council to delay final action.
   ``This would be the first in the nation, and we therefore are
responsible to be sure all issues are understood and agreed to.
Take time to analyze. Don't be hasty,'' Jerry Sheehan said.
   But the King County prosecutor's office urged the council not to
be intimidated by being first.
   ``The fact that we may be the first jurisdiction (to adopt the
genetic fingerprinting legislation) gives us a sense of
responsibility, but we should not shy away from its extreme
value,'' said Jeffrey Baird, a deputy prosecutor.
   Baird said identifying offenders is often the most difficult
part of prosecuting rape cases. ``This evidence will help resolve
the question of identity,'' he said.
   The ordinance established a technical committee to guarantee the
accuracy and reliability of the genetic process. A separate
committee will study how to store and retrieve genetic data.
</TEXT>
