<HEAD>Sophia Loren Visits Ellis Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Sophia Loren, wearing a hardhat labeled
``Sophia,'' visited Ellis Island to help publicize a Statue of
Liberty-Ellis Island Foundation fund-raising effort, the American
Immigrant Wall of Honor.
   Americans who pay at least $100 can have the names of their
immigrant ancestors inscribed on a plaque on a wall. The names also
will be stored in a computer, along with the person's nation of
origin.
   ``Ellis Island is a milestone of American history,'' Miss Loren,
a French citizen who was born in Italy, said during her visit
Monday.
   She was accompanied by Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca, who
said the foundation needs $15 million to $20 million to complete
renovation of the immigration station as a museum and conference
center.
