<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-ANCKilling 2ndLd-Writethru a0550 03-29 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-ANC Killing, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0550,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African National Congress Representative Shot Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `No group ...,' with one graf to UPDATE with
South Africa denying ANC claim. INSERTS 2 grafs after 17th graf,
`Sebina said ...,' to UPDATE with South African comment. PICKS up
18th graf, `The ANC ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An African National Congress official who recently
told authorities she had received death threats and was being
followed was shot and killed today while entering her office.
   The body of Dulcie September, 45, was found in her northeast
Paris apartment building, which also served as an office for the
group.
   Mrs. September had represented the ANC in France, Switzerland
and Luxembourg since 1984. The anti-apartheid group is outlawed in
South Africa.
   An ANC colleague said Mrs. September recently told Interior
Ministry officials that she had received threats and was being
followed.
   No group or individual immediately claimed responsibility for
the attack, but ANC officials blamed South Africa. South Africa
denied involvement.
   The French news agency Agence-France Press reported Mrs.
September was shot in the face while entering her office about 9
a.m. Her body was found surrounded by shells from a .22-caliber
rifle.
   She was holding letters in her hand and a key was in the door of
the fourth-floor office, AFP reported. Sources at the scene said
her attacker apparently was waiting when she arrived to begin her
normal working day.
   Maurice Cukierman, an ANC treasurer in the office, said Mrs.
September had ``informed the Ministry of the Interior that she had
received threats and that she had been followed during the last few
days.''
   ``It is with anger that I learned of her assassination,
especially since we had advised French authorities that South
Africa was ready to commit assassinations in Europe,'' he said.
   Eddy Amkongo, representative in France for the Southwest African
Peoples Organization, told reporters at the scene of the killing
that he had also been threatened and had requested protection from
the French government.
   ``But until today we have received no response,'' he said.
   The Interior Ministry declined to confirm or deny whether it had
received requests for protection from the African groups.
   Police, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
assassination looked like ``the work of a professional.''
   At ANC headquarters in Lusaka, Zambia, spokesman Tom Sebina
called the killing ``part of a deliberate South African campaign to
assassinate ANC members and ANC leaders.''
   Without citing any evidence, Sebina linked Mrs. September's
killing to a recent series of attacks carried out by the South
African military against what the South African army called ANC
``terrorists.''
   Since Friday the South African army has killed 11 people in
raids in Botswana, near the Botswana border with South Africa and
in the black homeland of Venda.
   Sebina said he did not know whether any of the 11 people killed
in the raids were affiliated with the ANC.
   South African Foreign Minister Roloef Pik Botha suggested the
death may have been the result of an internal quarrel within the
ANC.
   Pretoria ``cannot be held responsible for this death,'' the
foreign minister said in a statement issued through the South
African Embassy. ``While details concerning the assassination are
not yet known, the (South African) government must stress that
serious quarrels exist within organizations which use violence to
attain their political objectives.''
   The ANC, the main black guerrilla group fighting to overthrow
the South Africa government, maintains a worldwide network of about
20 ``information offices,'' including several in Europe, to lobby
for support and receive aid.
   The ANC was banned by South Africa in 1960 for its
anti-apartheid activities. Since then, it has waged a bombing a
sabotage campaign to wrest control from the government in Pretoria.
   The Soviet Union is the ANC's chief military supplier. ANC
leader Nelson Mandela has been jailed in South Africa since 1962.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
