<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-CatholicPriest     03-29 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Catholic Priest,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elderly Catholic Priest Released From Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly Chinese Catholic priest, who spent
much of the last 30 years behind bars for refusing to cut his links
with the Vatican, has been released on parole, the Shanghai
Catholic Association said today.
   An official of the state-sanctioned assocation, who declined to
be identified, said Vincent Chu, also known as Zhu Hongshen, was
paroled Feb. 6 so he could obtain better medical attention. He said
Chu, believed to be about 72, was generally in good health.
   The Jesuit priest was first jailed in 1955 along with Shanghai
Bishop Ignatius Kung (Gong Pinmei), who was convicted of treason
and sentenced to life in prison.
   Kung, now 87, was released in 1985. A Shanghai court earlier
this year ended his parole and restored his political rights.
   Chu was released from prison in 1979 and reportedly resumed his
contacts with priests who secretly remained loyal to the Vatican.
   Chu and three other elderly Jesuit priests were detained in 1981
and charged two years later with colluding with foreign countries
and endangering the sovereignty of the state among other crimes.
   Chu was sentenced to 15 years in prison. The other three
received sentences ranging from 2{ years to 10 years. The Shanghai
church official declined comment on the situation of the other
three.
   China severed relations with the Vatican in 1957 and set up the
Chinese Patriotic Catholic Church as the only recognized
organization for Chinese Catholics.
   The church claims more than 3 million members. An unknown number
of Catholics remain secretly loyal to the pope, and several still
are being held in prison for their religious practices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
