<2ND_LINE>PM-Surrogate Mom, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surrogate Mom Pleads Her Case, Says It's Baby M's Right to See Her</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to update with morning testimony from Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould. Edits below to tighten.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surrogate mother Mary Beth
Whitehead-Gould testified today that Baby M has a right to see her
and would benefit from spending time with her and her family.
   ``It's her right more so than anybody's right for her to see
me,'' Mrs. Whitehead-Gould told Superior Court Judge Birger M.
Sween on the second day of a hearing to determine how much time she
can spend with the child she bore under a $10,000 contract but then
refused to give up.
   Speaking calmly, Mrs. Whitehead-Gould, 30, asked for immediate
visits at her home and eventual overnight stays with expansion of
her time with the child, now 2, to include half the summer and some
holidays. Mother and child now visit once a week for two hours,
supervised at a social services center.
   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould said she has much to offer the child, now
legally Melissa Stern. She said the child could benefit by the
support of Mrs. Whitehead-Gould's family, including her husband,
accountant Dean Gould, and her children by a previous marriage,
Ryan, 13, and Tuesday, 12.
   She said the visitation schedule initially must be carefully
spelled out by the court to make it easier for both sides in the
bitter dispute to get along.
   On Monday, the child's father, William Stern, 42, in bitter
testimony that ended in tears, said Mrs. Whitehead-Gould is
untrustworthy and could undermine the child's relationship with him
and his wife.
   In the final legal phase of the Baby M case, Stern asked the
judge to halt visitation for several years, perhaps until her 10th
birthday, saying contact with Mrs. Whitehead-Gould could
emotionally harm the child.
   ``I'm afraid that she will never let Melissa be her own
person,'' he said in 2{ hours of testimony. ``Mary Beth is a liar.
... I can't trust her.''
   In later testimony, Stern's wife, Elizabeth, said she and Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould were ``poles apart.''
   ``I don't have any respect for her. ... I'd never choose her as
my friend. And quite simply, too much has gone on,'' Mrs. Stern
said.
   Stern said he feared Mrs. Whitehead-Gould, who lost a highly
publicized custody battle, would exploit Melissa to promote her
book about the case.
   The hearing was ordered by the New Jersey Supreme Court in its
landmark Feb. 3 decision that declared surrogacy-for-pay illegal
and restored Mrs. Whitehead-Gould's parental rights, but awarded
Sterns custody.
   The Sterns paid Mrs. Whitehead-Gould $10,000 to bear them a
child because they feared 42-year-old Mrs. Stern, who suffers a
mild form of multiple sclerosis, would suffer complications during
pregnancy. Mrs. Whitehead-Gould was artificially inseminated with
Stern's sperm.
   Under cross-examination, the Sterns acknowledged that Melissa
does not seem to have been harmed by her contact with Mrs.
Whitehead-Gould.
   When the judge asked him what kind of religion Melissa would be
exposed to, Stern, who is Jewish and whose relatives other than his
parents all died in the Holocaust, wept. After composing himself,
he said he expects to expose her to the Unitarian Church. Mrs.
Stern is not Jewish.
</TEXT>
