<1ST_LINE>r i BC-CampaignAbroad     03-29 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Surge Gets Attention in South Africa and Britain</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's surge in the race for the Democratic
presidential nomination has gained attention in South Africa and
Britain. Here are some of the comments of newspapers in those
countries:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTH AFRICA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Business Day of Johannesburg (pro-business): ``It has ... been
a widespread belief that the U.S. is `not ready' for a black
president. The support Michigan gave Jackson on Saturday raises the
intriguing possibility that this may not be true.
   ``It is more than 30 years since Brown vs. Board of Education
ended segregation in American schools, and racial causes have
steadily declined in influence. Could it be that many young
Americans, nurtured in an environment of equal rights, have
outgrown racial prejudice?
   `` ... Jackson probably won't become president this year, but he
could be the man who opens the way to the White House for a black
American.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Daily Telegraph of London (conservative): ``Mr. Jackson
still stands very little chance of securing the nomination: he is
widely perceived as unelectable in November not because he is black
_ America may be ready for that _ but becauppeal even to white hardhats
in industrial Michigan is to strengthen his claim to the vice
presidential spot on the Dukakis ticket, or at the very least to a
say in pulling Mr. Dukakis's platform to the left.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Times of London (conservative-independent): ``Mr. Jackson
is not unelectable because blacks vote for him. ... He is
unelectable because of the kind of whites who vote for him. The
entrails from Michigan show him with disproportionate support from
the sort of voters _ such as those in the state's numerous
university towns _ who were for Mr. McGovern in 1972. He was
unelectable, and white.
   ``Sooner or later, a black presidential candidate will emerge in
the United States who will campaign, not as a black _ emphasizing
links with races and idealogues abroad who have nothing in common
with American blacks either in outlook or standard of living _ but
as a traditional Democrat or Republican.''
</TEXT>
