<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GrandmotherDeath     03-29 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grandmother Death,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man, 45, Charged With Manslaughter In Grandmother's Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW PORT RICHEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he locked his
79-year-old grandmother in her room without food or medication
because she wanted to die has been charged with manslaughter in her
death, a sheriff's spokesman said.
   Alberta M. Bandell probably died between three and four weeks
ago, Pasco County sheriff's spokesman Bob Loeffler said Monday. Her
decomposed body was found Monday morning after her grandson,
Richard William Jones, 45, called the sheriff's office.
   ``He said he couldn't take it anymore, although we're not sure
what he meant by it,'' said Loeffler. ``We went over and saw a
grisly, grisly scene.'' Authorities discovered that the woman's
dog, which also had been shut in the room and deprived of food, had
chewed on the legs of the body, Loeffler said. The dog survived the
ordeal but was taken Monday by county animal health control
authorities and was expected to be put to sleep, Loeffler said.
   Jones was being held on $30,000 bail today.
   Neighbors in this small town 20 miles northeast of Tampa said
they smelled something foul emanating from the mobile home, where
Jones continued to live, for weeks.
   ``Over a month ago, I said, `God, there's a terrible stink out
there,''' David L. Sexton said.
   Neighbors said Jones had told them his grandmother was visiting
friends in Orlando and West Palm Beach.
   According to the arrest affidavit, Jones cashed his
grandmother's personal checks and attempted to sell the mobile home
to a neighbor for $16,500.
   In addition to the cashed checks and the deception of his
neighbors, detectives said they questioned Jones' story of a mercy
killing because of Mrs. Bandell's fairly good health and reports of
frequent arguements between Jones and his grandmother.
   ``He'd lock her in her bedroom different times. He'd curse and
yell at her,'' Sexton said.
   The cause of death was not known yet, but Loeffler said the
woman was a diabetic and required insulin injections.
   Depending on the results of the autopsy, the charge could be
changed to murder, Loeffler said.
</TEXT>
