<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PuertoRico-Fire     03-29 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Puerto Rico-Fire,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Fire At National Guard HQ Is Likely Arson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire was discovered today in the
arsenal of the Puerto Rico National Guard and police said it might
have been triggered by an explosive device.
   ``Everything indicates there was a criminal hand,'' Police
Superintendent Carlos Lopez Feliciano said in a statement. ``We are
investigating if there was an explosive or incendiary device. It's
not conclusive.''
   No other details on the cause of the blaze were available.
   The fire was discovered by an arsenal guard about 2 a.m. when
smoke was seen coming out of the second-floor storage room, the
superintendent said.
   ``When he checked, he saw two people in the interior parking
area who jumped the fence protecting the perimeter of the
arsenal,'' Lopez Feliciano said.
   All National Guard facilities were under police surveillance
today in case the fire was part of a coordinated attack, Lopez
Feliciano said.
   ``We are guarding all the National Guard installations in case
its part of a series,'' the superintendent said.
   Local explosives experts and officials from the FBI were at the
scene gathering evidence.
   Early this moring several fire engines were at the scene
extinguishing the fire. There was no estimate of damages to the
facility.
   About 600 members of the Puerto Rico National guard flew to the
Panama Canal Zone this weekend for a training exercise. The move
has been criticized by groups favoring Puerto Rico's independence
from the United States, as well as by individual members of the
pro-statehood New Progressive Party and the governing Popular
Democratic Party.
   On Monday, National Guard Adjutant Gen. Alfredo Mora denied the
guardsmen were being sent to Panama for anything other than
training purposes and said the possibility that the guards will see
any combat ``is very remote.''
   Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens with most of the rights of
Americans, except that they cannot vote for the president of the
United States.
</TEXT>
