<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Sailor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0595,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Investigating Slaying Of Navy Airman
^Eds: SUBS 4th graf to restore dropped first reference to Lukander</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is investigating the slaying
of a 22-year-old Navy airman whose decomposed body was identified
10 days after she disappeared from her home.
   FBI agents and other law enforcement officials met Monday at the
Duval County medical examiner's office to discuss the case, said
Atlantic Beach Police Chief David Thompson. He would give no
further details.
   ``We don't want to release anything that could come back to
haunt us,'' he told The Florida Times-Union and Journal.
   Detective Dave Archer said police were certain Anita Lukander
was murdered, but he declined to reveal how she was killed.
   The victim was married May 9, 1987, to a naval petty officer who
flew home from active duty aboard a frigate after being notified of
his wife's disappearance.
   Using dental records, authorties on Sunday identified a body
found the day before along the Intracoastal Waterway in
Jacksonville Beach as that of Mrs. Lukander. The woman had been
missing since March 17.
   Archer said Dr. Peter Lipkovic, medical examiner for Duval, told
police the body had been in the water about eight or nine days.
   Cmdr. Richard O'Neal said Mrs. Lukander was a member of the
Mayport-based Helicopter Antisubmarine Squadron Light 42. Her
husband Petty Officer 2nd Class Bill Lukander, also is a member of
the squadron.
   Mrs. Lukander was assigned to shore duty as an administrative
clerk in maintenance control, while her husband is an electronics
technician who often is at sea for the squadron.
   Mrs. Lukander disappeared two days after a Navy paymaster, Lt.
Ratish Prasad, 24, was slain March 15 aboard the USS Hancock in
Mayport. Prasad was shot in the head at close range.
   Navy investigators said $94,629 was stolen from the ship's safe.
No arrests have been made in that case.
   Navy spokesmen said earlier there appeared to be no connection
between the cases, noting that the ship and the helicopter squadron
are in widely separate areas on the huge base.
</TEXT>
