<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-MilitaryTrial     03-29 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Military Trial,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Court Sentences Soldiers Convicted Of Live Burial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court today sentenced two soldiers
accused of burying four Arabs alive to longer prison sentences than
requested by prosecutors, saying their conduct was grave and
shameful, Israel radio reported.
   The court sentenced Pvt. Dror Segen-Cohen to six months in jail
along with a four-month suspended sentence. Pvt. Yair Nissimi was
given five months in jail and a seven-month suspended sentence.
   The prosecution had asked for two months in jail for Segen-Cohen
and 2{ months for Nissimi.
   The soldiers admitted they beat four Arabs from the occupied
West Bank village of Kfar Salem on Feb. 5 after a protest in the
village. The soldiers also admitted burying the four Arabs in about
25 inches of mud.
   The Arabs survived.
   The court ruled the soldiers' behavior had tarnished the army's
image and put Israel in a bad light.
   A third soldier, Sgt. Maj. Charlie Danino, is accused of
ordering the burial. He has pleaded innocent and his trial is still
underway.
   Five other soldiers are also on trial for violating military
orders. One has been charged in the killing of a Palestinian in the
Gaza Strip and four others for beating two Palestinian detainees
after a demonstration in Nablus.
   According to U.N. figures, 119 Palestinians have been killed in
the occupied territories since anti-Israeli protests began Dec. 8.
One Israeli soldier has died.
</TEXT>
