<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Veterans-Cabinet     03-29 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Veterans-Cabinet,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Glenn Says He Won't Allow Amendment to Jeopardize VA Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Governmental
Affairs Committee says he would not allow a proposed amendment to
jeopardize passage of a new cabinet-level Department of Veterans
Affairs.
   The statement Monday by panel Chairman John Glenn, D-Ohio,
improved prosects for the legislation, which passed the House last
November after President Reagan announced his support for a
Cabinet-level department.
   The proposed amendment would allow veterans to appeal any denied
claim to federal courts.
   Glenn said he supported judicial review, but would not attempt
to add the provision in his committee. Judicial review, he said,
was in the jurisdiction of the Veterans Affairs Committee, which
has tentatively scheduled a hearing on the issue for April 21.
   The Ohio Democrat said he believes veterans are treated as
second class citizens, because they do not have the same appellate
rights as those receiving unfavorable rulings from other agencies.
   The Government Affairs Committee reported that old-line veterans
groups lobbied against judicial review, while groups of Vietnam and
paralyzed veterans said they favor the provision. The committee
said mail was split about 50-50.
</TEXT>
