<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Tiger     03-29 0116</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tiger,0119</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man-Eating Tiger Killed in Bangladesh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forestry workers killed a Bengal tiger
after it attacked and killed a woodcutter, who was believed to be
its 17th human victim in five months, police said Tuesday.
   The attack occurred in the Sundarbans Forest, a national tiger
preserve 80 miles southwest of Dhaka.
   Authorities believe the tiger had killed at least 16 other
people. The attacks had spread fear among nearby villagers and
forestry officials, who shot the animal Monday.
   Tigers generally are shy animals and rarely attack humans unless
they are injured, threatened or facing food shortages. They are
protected by law with poaching punishable by up to five years in
jail.
</TEXT>
