<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Song     03-29 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Song,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Army Station Won't Play Protest Song</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army-run radio station has refused to play
a protest song critical of Israeli policy in the occupied
territories, the director of the station said Tuesday.
   ``It attacks Israeli soldiers,'' Col. Nahman Shai said of
``Shooting and Crying,'' written and sung by Israeli rock musician
Si Hyman.
   Ms. Hyman said she wrote the song after hearing about a Feb. 5
incident in which Israeli soldiers beat four Palestinians and
buried them alive under two feet of dirt. They survived the attack,
which occurred after troops dispersed a protest in the occupied
West Bank village of Kfar Salem.
   ``They shoot and cry, burn and laugh. When did they learn to
bury people alive?'' one verse of the song says. ``When did they
forget that our children have also been killed?''
   However, Shai said the song's accusations were unfounded. He
said Israeli soldiers ``are doing their jobs in the best possible
fashion and deserve our appreciation.''
   Israel has faced international criticism for its handling of
Palestinian protests that began in the occupied territories four
months ago.
   State-run Israeli radio has not banned the song, but has not
been playing it, either.
</TEXT>
