<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--London-Weapons     03-29 0123</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--London-Weapons ,0125</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Amnesty Turns up 1,500 Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A month-long citywide amnesty has netted 1,563
weapons, including jackknives, axes, machetes and a stun gun that
can deliver a 45,000-volt electric shock, Scotland Yard said
Tuesday.
   The national police force said the amnesty was intended to
encourage people to hand in knives. However, weapons from
pump-action shotguns to brass knuckles were dumped in special bins
or handed in anonymously at police stations.
   Police Cmdr. Walter Boreham, who supervised the amnesty, said
``these weapons, some of which could have been used to maim or
kill, are now off the streets because their owners have woken up to
the fact that carrying a weapon is dangerous.''
   The amnesty ended March 9.
</TEXT>
