<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PanamaDrugs     03-29 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama Drugs,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ignored or Hid Noriega's Drug Links, Former Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former White House aide said Tuesday that
the Reagan administration either ignored or hid the fact that
Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega was dealing in drugs.
   But Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams disputed that
assertion, saying the government acted legally against Noriega as
soon as it could.
   The former White House official, Norman A. Bailey, told the
House Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control that Noriega
and other high-level officials of the Panama Defense Forces had
been engaged in drug trafficking, gun running and money laundering
since the mid-1970s.
   Bailey, an economic consultant who formerly was a special
assistant to the president for national security affairs until Oct.
13, 1983, said Noriega and the Panamanian military have engaged
``in the past in activities which represent and have represented a
clear, unquestionable and obvious multiple threat to the national
security in a narrow sense, and the national interests in a broader
sense, of the United States of America.
   ``It is also a story of how clear and incontrovertible evidence
was at best ignored and at worst hidden and denied by many
different agencies and departments of the government of the United
States in such a way as to provide cover and protection for these
activities while at the same time assuring that they did the
maximum damage to those very interests that the officials involved
were sworn to uphold and defend,'' Bailey said.
   Bailey said the information available to the U.S. government on
Noriega and the Panama Defense Forces was not only a ``smoking gun
but rather a 21-cannon barrage of evidence.''
   But Abrams told the committee there has been uncorroborated
allegations of illegal drug-related activity by Noriega for many
years.
   ``We were not unaware of these,'' he said. ``Until recently,
however, there was no substantiated evidence of his narcotics
involvement.''
   Abrams said, however, that when the Justice Department unveiled
evidence against him, Noriega was indicted by two grand juries in
Florida earlier this year. Since then, the United States has
applied economic and diplomatic pressure to drive Noriega from his
post as head of the Defense Forces.
   Abrams said he has heard about general corruption in Panama
since he came into office in July 1985. ``Not only drugs, but
anything that can be done for money,'' he said.
   In answer to a question by Rep. Benjamin A. Gilman, R-N.Y.,
Abrams said he would not be surprised to learn that Noriega was
either a double or triple agent.
   ``Noriega is loyal to no one,'' he said. ``He has dealt with our
intelligence agencies. He has dealt with Cuban intelligence. He has
dealt with everyone. He took what information he could get and
passed it on or sold it.''
   Following the hearing, Abrams told reporters: ``I'm unaware of
any documentation (of drug trafficking) during the past five
years.''
   When asked about Bailey's charges, he replied: ``Why do you
think we're going after Noriega?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
