<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-MiddleEast     03-29 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Middle East,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council To Discuss Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council will convene an
urgent meeting Wednesday to discuss the situation in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab diplomats said
today.
   A delegation of Arab foreign ministers and the PLO called on
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar today to schedule the
meeting. They also urged the U.N. chief to send another
fact-finding mission to the occupied territories.
   In the toughest crackdown since Palestinian unrest began nearly
Dec. 8, the Israeli army today enforced a three-day closure of the
occupied lands, barring nearly all journalists, Israeli civilians
and Arab visitors.
   Clovis Maksoud, U.N. ambassador for the Arab League, told
reporters after the delegation met Perez de Cuellar that the
Security Council would convene Wednesday to discuss Israel's
actions in the occupied lands.
   The delegation included Farouk Kaddoumi, head of the political
department of the Palestine Liberation Organization; Ahmed Taleb
Ibrahimi, Algeria's foreign minister; Ibrahim Massoud, minister of
state for foreign affairs of Saudi Arabia; Farouk Al-Shara, the
Syrian foreign minister; and Chedli Klibi, secretary-general of the
League of Arab States.
   The delegation, except for the PLO envoy, left for a meeting at
the State Department in Washington to express Arab views on the
Palestinian demonstrations in the occupied territories, a Middle
East peace conference, U.S. efforts to close the PLO's U.N. Mission
and other issues.
   The Security Council has held several meetings on the Middle
East since the heightened Palestinian unrest began and each time
has condemned Israel's measures to put down the protests.
   ``A meeting is necessary because of Israel's clamp down today,
its banning the press and curfew,'' Maksoud said.
   The delegation also asked the United Nations to send a
second-fact finding mission to the territories. Under
Secretary-General Marrack Goulding recently visited the territories
and submitted a report sharply critical of Israel.
   The secretary-general has called for a U.N.-sponsored Middle
East peace conference, involving all parties to the Middle East
conflict, including the PLO, and the five permanent members of the
Security Council.
   Tunisia on Friday formally requested the Security Council
meeting.
</TEXT>
