<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1257EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Long-TermCare     03-29 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Long-Term Care,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Says Most Americans Want Federal Home-Care Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 80 percent of Americans favor a
federal program to provide long-term home care for the chronically
ill and disabled, according to a poll released Tuesday.
   The survey by Louis Harris & Associates also found that more
than 70 percent would support paying for the program by increasing
Medicare payroll taxes for people who make more than $45,000 a year.
   Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., released the survey in conjunction
with a hearing on his five-year, $25 billion proposal for long-term
home care. House leaders have promised him a floor vote on the bill
although it has not gone through the usual committee scrutiny.
   Many members have criticized the plan as too expensive to pass
this year. Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the
tax-writing House Ways and Means Committee, has said Congress
cannot enact both Pepper's plan and another Medicare expansion
shielding the elderly and disabled against catastrophic health-care
costs.
   Catastrophic-cost bills already have passed both houses and
negotiators are working out differences between the two versions.
   Rep. Edward Roybal, D-Calif., chairman of the House Select
Committee on Aging and a co-sponsor of Pepper's bill, said
virtually no Medicare or insurance coverage is available to
millions of people with a chronic illness.
   ``We have long believed we were seeing a rising tide of public
support for a federal long-term care program, and the Harris poll
shows us Americans are evne more enthusiastic than we imagined,''
Roybal said in a statement.
   The Harris survey found that Americans of all ages, professions,
party affiliations and income levels supported financing a new
home-care program through an increase in the 1.45 percent Medicare
payroll tax on upper-income workers.
   More than 70 percent of people earning above $50,000 supported
that method of financing although they would bear the brunt of it,
the survey found.
   Of those questioned, 82 percent said they could not afford to
pay for the costs of providing long-term care either at home or in
a nursing home _ including more than 60 percent of those making
above $50,000 a year.
   And nearly 80 percent of those polled said they would prefer
long-term home care to care in a nursing home.
   The Harris survey questioned 1,500 adults across the country in
telephone interviews Feb. 18-23. The margin of error is plus or
minus three percentage points.
   The survey echoes an earlier poll last fall that found Americans
by an overwhelming majority were willing to pay higher taxes to
finance long-term care for the elderly.
   Sixty-eight percent of those questioned in the survey by R.L.
Associates were willing to shoulder $10 to $60 a month more in
taxes to pay for the program.
   That survey was commissioned by Long-Term Care '88, a coalition
of senior citizens groups and other organizations hoping to make
the issue a top priority with presidential candidates.
   On a related matter, a government report released Tuesday said
the number of elderly Americans confined to nursing homes is
remaining stable even though the raw numbers are rising because of
an aging population.
   There were 1.3 million nursing home residents at least 65 years
of age in 1985, up 200,000 from 1977, when the last nursing home
figures were collected.
   The report by the Department of Health and Human Services said
the 1985 nursing home population reflected about 1 percent of
Americans 65-74 years old being confined to institutions and about
22 percent of those 85 years and older. Both percentages were
essentially unchanged from the 1977 survey.
</TEXT>
