<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Opposition     03-29 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Opposition,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Street Theater Organizer Freed, But 18 Supporters Detained</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court Tuesday freed the leader of an
opposition street theater group serving a two-month jail sentence,
but 18 of his supporters were detained by police outside the
courtroom, activists said.
   Waldemar ``The Major'' Fydrych, 34, who heads the group Orange
Alternative, was arrested March 8 as he handed out flowers and
sanitary napkins to women to mock official observances of
International Women's Day.
   Leading cultural figures, including film director Andrzej Wajda,
had appealed for the release of the writer, who became widely known
for organizing various Orange Alternative ``happenings'' in which
demonstrators dressed up as Santa Claus, secret policemen and
Lenten penitents to poke fun at communist authorities.
   The appeals court in Wroclaw acquitted Fydrych of causing public
unrest after finding that testimony by prosecution witnesses was
inconsistent with that given by the sole witness at Fydrych's March
9 misdemeanor hearing, said spokesman Krzysztof Albin.
   Fydrych was released after the hearing, which his supporters
were barred from attending, said Barbara Labuda, another opposition
activist in the southwestern Polish city.
   Police detained three Orange Alternative supporters who were
carrying models of a major's uniform hanging from a gallows in a
morning demonstration outside the courthouse, Albin said.
   At least 15 more supporters, most of them wearing orange-colored
apparel, were detained by police while they waited for the verdict
in a corridor outside the courtroom, Albin said.
   Albin said one Orange Alternative member, Grzegorz Francuz, was
beaten on the way to the police station.
   Opposition activists in Poland are frequently detained for up to
48 hours on misdemeanor charges.
</TEXT>
