<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--BearCub     03-29 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bear Cub,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zoo Staff Eat Bear Cub Because of Lack of Space</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at a city zoo killed and ate
a popular bear cub because they didn't have room for it in the
park, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
   The cub, named Molly, was 2 years old and was one of visitors'
favorites at the Skansen Park Zoo when the lack of space last
November forced the zoo to cull the cubs, according to the
newspaper, Expressen.
   The bear was served to the zoo's staff.
   ``Molly was so nice, I didn't take a bite,'' caretaker Tina
Reinhed told the newspaper.
   Because of crowded conditons, the cubs are kept for 18 months
before they are either sold or killed, she said.
   ``First we naturally try to sell them to other zoological
parks,'' Reinhed said. ``Sadly enough, they also have an excess (of
bears).''
   Zoo superintendent Pelle Palm said that while people don't like
to see ``teddy bears'' eaten, ``it's worse to destroy meat in a
world that hungers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
