<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras Troops,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Troops To Be Out of Honduras by Thursday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The withdrawal of U.S. troops from Honduras
will be completed on Thursday, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   Spokesman Dan Howard said the roughly 3,100 soldiers dispatched
to Honduras on March 17-18 were being removed along with their
equipment on a four-day schedule. The first group was airlifted out
Monday.
   The soldiers were dispatched as a warning to the leftist
Nicaraguan government after Sandinista troops moved into Honduras
in pursuit of U.S.-backed Contra rebels. The American troops never
were sent to the border area where the fighting occurred, but
rather staged military exercises with Honduran military units.
   According to the Pentagon, the last contingent of men from the
7th Light Infantry Division will return to Fort Ord, Calif., around
2 p.m. EST on Wednesday. The last unit from the 82nd Airborne will
return to Fort Bragg, N.C., around 9 a.m. EST on Thursday.
   About 2,000 of the troops were scheduled to depart Honduras on
Tuesday, the Pentagon added.
</TEXT>
