<HEAD>33 Police Officers Fired for Corruption in Ghana Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ACCRA, Ghana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government fired 33 police officers for
drug trafficking, armed robbery, accepting bribes and other crimes
as part of a corruption crackdown, authorities said Tuesday.
   Six officers were dismissed for stealing diamonds in the mining
town of Akwatia near Accra, police said. Ten others had smuggled
marijuana to neighboring Ivory Coast by boat.
   Among the fired officers was a deputy police superintendent, but
there were no details on where he had been posted.
   The announcement by the National Police Council, headed by
Ghanaian leader Flight Lt. Jerry Rawlings, did not say if the
officers had been arrested.
   Two weeks ago, 19 officers were fired for armed robbery and drug
trafficking in the crackdown aimed at reducing corruption and
improving police efficiency and credibility.
