<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GolfCourseGang     03-29 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Golf Course Gang,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: 10-Year-Olds Threaten Golfers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gang of 10-year-olds who began
stealing golf balls two months ago have graduated to terrorizing
members of Boca Raton's Executive Country Club with knives,
officials say.
   They've also allegedly dug up the fourth green.
   ``The women golfers are frightened. The men are angry,'' Mary K.
Werre, manager of the country club, said Monday after calling
police.
   ``They're kids who should know better, but they're very, very
nasty,'' said Ed Lombardi, 77, of Deerfield Beach.
   Country club members describe the children as clean-cut,
well-dressed and about 10 years old.
   Lombardi was playing golf last Sunday when some children stole a
friend's ball.
   ``Out on the golf course, we don't want nor expect anything like
that,'' he said. ``I chased them into the woods, but they have
paths. They can go like deer in there.''
   Two foursomes, who played Saturday, told Ms. Werre that children
had sprung from the trees, swiped golf balls and, brandishing
knives, challenged the golfers to ``come and get them.''
   ``A gang of about five 10-year-olds equipped with shovels dug up
the fourth green,'' Boca Raton Officer William Ehrhardt wrote in
his report. ``In addition, the youths were in possession of knives,
intimidated golfers and stole their balls.''
   Country club officials were reluctant at first to report the
juveniles' high jinks.
   ``Whenever we saw them out there we got in our golf cart and
went after them, but they ran and we haven't been able to catch
them,'' Ms. Werre said.
   That was before the children added knives to their arsenal. Now,
Ms. Werre said, she will call police whenever the children are
spotted.
   Ted Wright of Lake Worth was playing last Sunday when he saw
some children playing with remote-controlled cars in the sand trap.
   ``I told them to get off, we were playing,'' he said.
   As Wright went for one of the cars, the youthful owner said they
were leaving, then cursed him.
   About two weeks ago, the children appeared at night wearing
camouflage fatigues, Ms. Werre said. With their faces blackened,
they crept onto the driving range and lifted some golf balls before
a worker saw them and shooed them away, she said.
   Country club officials can't figure out a motive.
   ``If they're stealing range balls, they really can't do well by
selling them anywhere,'' Ms. Werre said. ``If they're stealing from
off the course, you'd think they'd be selling them here, but that
hasn't happened.''
</TEXT>
