<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0616 03-29 0856</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0616,0879</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Witness Says Protocol Fund Wasn't Public Money</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th-8th grafs, `Inaugural Committee ...,' with 7 grafs
to UPDATE with more testimony from L'Ecuyer.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness for Gov. Evan Mecham today told
senators considering whether to remove the governor from office
that a fund Mecham is accused of misuing was not public money nor
controlled by state law.
   Political consultant and lawyer Robert L'Ecuyer testified that
Mecham's inaugural committee chairman lacked the authority to bind
the governor to restrictions on how the money could be used.
   Mecham, a first-term Republican, is being tried by the Arizona
Senate on three impeachment counts, including alleged misuse of
$80,000 from a protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership.
   The defense has contended the fund, created with proceeds from
inaugural activities, was not public money, while the prosecution
contends it was.
   L'Ecuyer testified today that because the protocol fund was not
public money in his opinion, Mecham was not restricted by state
laws that govern the use of public funds.
   He said he thought the loan was ``legal but stupid.''
   Inaugural Committee Chairman William Long had told the Maricopa
County Attorney's office in a 1987 letter that the fund would be
used to either benefit the state or to promote citizen
participation in state activities.
   ``The June 26 letter from William Long to the county attorney
was of absolutely no force or effect in relation to the Mecham
inaugural committee funds'' because the fund already had been
turned over to Mecham, and Long no longer chaired the inaugural
committee, L'Ecuyer said.
   L'Ecuyer also described a meeting in May 1987 in which he
agreed, despite misgivings, to advise the governor on Mecham's
plans to publish a tabloid touting his administration.
   ``The governor and I started off with a shouting match,''
L'Ecuyer said. ``The two of us yelled at each other for the better
part of the hour,'' he said, adding that if the tabloid was used as
a campaign tool to attack lawmakers, ``that could become a
violation; people could go to jail for that kind of a violation.''
He did not elaborate.
   The governor cooperated with L'Ecuyer on campaign finance
matters after that meeting, the consultant said.
   L'Ecuyer was hired by Mecham last fall to provide legal opinions
on the propriety of the governor's failure to report a $350,000
campaign loan. The consultant said last fall that Mecham properly
reported the loan by lumping it in with other amounts.
   Mecham faces a charge of concealing the $350,000 loan in both
the impeachment trial and criminal court. The Senate already has
heard testimony on another charge that he tried to thwart an
investigation on an alleged death threat.
   On Monday, senators indicated they were taking a dim view of
Mecham's proposal that they vote now on two of the impeachment
articles, concerning the death threat and the protocol fund,
against him and promise to drop the third regarding the campaign
loan.
   The chances of that happening are ``about as good of me jumping
off the top of the highest building I can find in the
neighborhood,'' said Senate Majority Leader Bob Usdane, who like
Mecham is a Republican.
   Also Monday, the governor's lawyer, Jerris Leonard, said Monday
that Mecham has ``a firm agreement'' to sell the land and buildings
of his Mecham Pontiac dealership for about $4 million.
   Leonard said he did not know who the prospective buyer was, when
the deal would be closed, or whether Mecham was keeping his Pontiac
franchise.
   During his own testimony Monday on the protocol fund, Mecham
angrily disrupted the proceedings after House prosecutor William
French compared his actions to embezzlement.
   ``I have to make a statement,'' Mecham declared, ignoring orders
from Arizona Supreme Court Justice Frank Gordon to refrain from
comments beyond answering questions asked.
   ``I resent so highly the word embezzlement in my presence,''
Mecham said. ``I'm insulted by it.''
   Gordon admonished Mecham again, telling him: ``I hope you
believe the rules are for you, sir, as well as everybody else.''
   Mecham responded hotly: ``I have seen no witness who has been
insulted as I have been.''
   In his testimony Monday, the governor suggested that the Senate
drop the third charge and vote right away on the first two counts.
   ``If you want to say we'll call this game at the end of six
innings, and do it (vote) then with the fact that that is the game,
why, I don't suppose we could argue with you on that one,'' Mecham
said.
   However, Senate Minority Leader Alan Stephens, a Democrat,
agreed with Usdane that it would be ``ridiculous'' to expect the
Senate to drop the $350,000 loan allegation.
   A two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate on any one of the
counts is required to convict the governor, automatically removing
him from office. A similar two-thirds vote would be needed to
change the rules to allow an early vote on the first two
impeachment counts.
   Mecham, who also faces a May 17 recall election, is the first
U.S. governor to be impeached in six decades.
</TEXT>
