<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1356EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HumorConference     03-29 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Humor Conference,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humor Conference Will Be More Academic Than Knee-Slapping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDEL HUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seventh National Conference On Humor is
no joke.
   ``To tell you the truth, it may be excruciatingly boring,''
Victor Raskin, a Purdue University English professor coordinating
the weekend conference, said Tuesday.
   ``There will be one lecture on the Peanuts cartoon. I have no
idea how that will turn out,'' said Shaun F.D. Hughes, an associate
professor of English who is helping Raskin coordinate the
conference. ``There will be one on the theory of humor. That tends
to be more deadly.''
   The theme is Midwestern humor. ``There will be some papers on
Mark Twain,'' said Hughes. ``There will be one from Northwestern
University on Chicago political humor.''
   Hughes will ``present a deadly paper. It's called `Physician,
Humor Thyself.' It's Icelandic medical humor. Icelandic people,
they say, have no sense of humor and this tends to bear that out,''
he said.
   Raskin said in a recent university statement: ``In the last
decade, humor has been increasingly recognized as an essential and
universal human facility and as such, has become the subject of
high-powered and widely interdisciplinary research.''
   The conference, at Purdue's West Lafayette campus, will be about
80 percent academic, says Raskin. The last six such conferences
were held at Arizona State University _ always on April Fool's Day.
   ``During the breaks, there may be a lot of laughter,'' said
Raskin. ``Then on Sunday night, there is a public joke-telling
contest. They can tell jokes, juggle, anything to elicit laughter.
The winner gets a purse of maybe $60 or something.''
   But the point, or punchline, is quite serious.
   ``Psychologists want to know why we appreciate humor,'' says
Raskin. ``Sociologists are interested in humor's role in society.
Anthropologists want to know why what is funny to one society is
not funny to another.''
   ``Luckily, some parts of it will be funny,'' says Hughes.
``Sometimes they insert jokes into the lecture.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MedicaidCondoms     03-29 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medicaid Condoms,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Plans Program for Free Condoms to Medicaid Recipients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan welfare clients may get free condoms
from their pharmacists in a new program to provide birth control
and help stem the spread of AIDS.
   Ohio, Wisconsin, Illinois, New York and Pennsylvania already
provide condoms for Medicaid recipients by prescription. For
accounting purposes, some state rules require prescriptions for
many items given Medicaid recipients by pharmacists.
   But Michigan apparently will be the first state to provide the
condoms without prescriptions, state and federal officials say.
   The state Department of Social Services is notifying Medicaid
recipients and pharmacists about the program, scheduled to begin
June 1, Chuck Peller, a spokesman for DDS, said Monday.
   The condoms can be obtained by men or women presenting a
Medicaid card to a pharmacist, Peller said.
   There is no specific budget for the program, the state has not
estimated its cost and the DSS has ``no idea of the anticipated
usage,'' Peller said.
   The latest state budget bill included the requirement for free
condoms to Medicaid recipients, Peller said.
   Richard Chambers, a spokesman for the U.S. Department of Health
and Human Services, said from Washington that he knows of no other
state that authorizes free distribution of condoms without a
prescription.
   The federal government reimburses states for 90 percent of the
costs of family planning services, Chambers said.
   To guard against fraud, including what Peller called ``the
`black market' possibility,''' a recipient's Medicaid number will
be recorded each time condoms are picked up. The state will check
those numbers periodically, he said.
   If the DSS determines a recipient has obtained an unusual number
of condoms, that person will be referred to the agency's Recipient
Monitoring Project in which a prescription would be needed for more
condoms, Peller said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
