<DOCNO> AP880329-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1358EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CapitolNotebook     03-29 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Capitol Notebook,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Bring Washington To Houston, Find Humor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Republicans' conference in Houston
last weekend was supposed to be a retreat, but lawmakers joked that
it was more like an advance.
   They led an invading army that included 42 U.S. Capitol police
officers, police dogs, the House physician, the House clerk, office
assistants, reporters, camera crews and the staff of the National
Republican Congressional Committee, which helps run their
campaigns. Many brought their families.
   They traveled with a legion of lobbyists, many of whom helped
finance the three chartered jetliners, lawmakers' hotel rooms and
banquets paid for under the auspices of The Congressional Institute
Inc., a tax-exempt corporation set up for these occasions.
   Sam Richardson, a spokesman for the conference, said the total
cost had not yet been calculated. He said one of the banquets _
canceled later because of a bomb threat _ cost $12,000. Reporters
each were charged $413 for travel and meals, with hotel bills extra.
   One of the goals of the three-day conference was for the 70
lawmakers attending to let their hair down. But the program listed
suit-and-tie or women's business attire for three straight days,
even at a Tex-Mex dinner.
   ``They're going to think we're all a bunch of stuffed shirts,''
complained one member, who got no argument from his wife nearby.
   While in Houston, the Republicans sought some high-tech themes
for their national agenda. They sought camaraderie. They sought a
strategy in their marathon battle to take control of the House back
from the Democrats for the first time in 34 years.
   The thing they surely found, which isn't in evidence much in
Washington, was some humor.
   During the three-day meeting, the GOP squad traveled back and
forth across the city in bus motorcades. Along the way, police
blocked side streets and freeway ramps while frustrated local
motorists didn't know whom to blame.
   ``There is only one thing to do at a time like this,'' one of
the GOP lawmakers said, staring at a line of blocked traffic.
   ``Put a big sign on the bus that says `Mickey Leland Re-election
Committee, Jim Wright, Chairman,''' he said, referring to the local
Democratic congressman and the House speaker.
   The House Republicans didn't use police escorts at their last
get-together a year ago in New York.
   They had asked the NYPD how long it would take to get from their
mid-town hotel to Federal Hall for their meetings.
   ``Thirty-five minutes,'' was the answer. And if they used an
escort?
   ``Forty minutes,'' came the reply.
   At the Houston hotel, a lobbyist from one of the regional phone
companies was handing out complimentary pens. ``Remember, if it
breaks, we only fix the outside. You have to go to AT&T for the
inside,'' he warned.
   The conference was held in a lovely Four Seasons hotel. But
Houston's already summer-sticky weather prompted a reporter to dub
it the ``One Season.''
   Perhaps the highlight of the trip was a spectacular laser and
fireworks show at the Johnson Space Center.
   The climax came when the doors of a huge hangar opened up and
the spectators wandered into a misty night sliced and diced by
lasers stretching across the horizon.
   ``I thought a big clamshell was going to open up and we'd walk
in and fly away,'' one lawmaker quipped about the eerie scene.
   Another seemed concerned that the laser beams were hitting the
nearby Hilton hotel.
   ``I just can't help but thinking,'' he said, ``that there's some
poor salesman up in one of those rooms thinking about fooling
around on his wife. And then he's zapped by a green light beam!
   ``He'll never try that again,'' the congressman predicted.
   By the end of three days, the lawmakers were eager to return to
Washington, and to finish this year's business early so that they
can hit the re-election campaign trail.
   ``We have to go home and tell our constituents this mess isn't
our fault,'' one explained.
</TEXT>
