<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0596 03-29 1062</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0596,990</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS new grafs 10-12 bgng, `White House,' with Fitzwater
comments; picks up 10th graf pvs, bgng, `Leaders of.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House negotiators working on aid for the
Nicaraguan rebels tried today to resolve a dispute over whether
President Reagan should be able to command quick congressional
action on any military aid request.
   ``We still have significant debate over how a future request
from the president for military aid would be treated,'' Rep. Dick
Cheney of Wyoming, chairman of the House Republican Conference,
said after GOP congressional leaders met with the president.
   Cheney said one possibility discussed was that instead of
spelling out the procedures in the bill, the House would rely on a
promise by Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, that there will be a speedy
vote on such a request.
   ``I think if the speaker would give his word, we would find that
acceptable,'' he said. ``If we can work out an arrangement whereby
the speaker would commit in advance to give us timely consideration
for the vote and he would bring it up under a fair rule, I think
that would solve the problem.''
   Rep. Trent Lott, the House Republican whip, said, ``We would be
willing to take the speaker's word, but we are going to have to
have a clear understanding of what that word means.''
   When asked whether such a ``gentlemen's agreement'' could be
sold to House Republicans, Lott said, ``It would be very difficult,
because while they (the Democrats) say they are suspicious of the
president's request for ... expedited procedures, we don't trust
them either.''
   He said, however, that he believed House Republicans would
support such an agreement if it were worked out between Wright and
House GOP leader Robert Michel of Illinois. Wright and Michel were
in New Jersey today, attending the funeral of Democratic Rep. James
Howard.
   Lott said Reagan ``didn't sign on'' to the idea of such an
agreement but ``I know the president has a lot of faith'' in
Michel, Cheney and Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., the principal
negotiators.
   ``If they can get something that they can accept and work with,
I am sure that will carry a lot of weight with the president,''
Lott said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the dollar amounts
of aid mentioned in the negotiations, ranging from $30 million to
less than $50million, were acceptable to Reagan.
   ``The issue is not money but how fast we can get it'' to help
assure the survival of the Nicaraguan Contra rebels as a fighting
force, Fitzwater said. ``We want it as fast as we can get it,'' he
said.
   He added that the issue of an acceptable means of delivering aid
to the Contras is ``still an open question'' to be worked out by
the negotiators, subject to proposals for cease-fire zones in
Nicaragua.
   Leaders of the chamber worked for five hours Monday on the
package, and roughed out a six-month, $40 million aid bill that
would send strictly ``humanitarian'' aid _ food, clothing, medicine
and shelter _ while the rebels negotiate a permanent peace with the
country's leftist Sandinista government.
   ``We reached some general understandings in a number of areas,
but there were some stumbling points,'' said House Democratic Whip
Tony Coelho of California, who added that meetings would resume
today.
   Coelho held out hope that an agreement still could be forged in
time to bring the matter to the House floor on Wednesday and permit
the Senate time to act and get the aid flowing before Easter. He
cited reports that the rebels may exhaust their basic supplies
within a week or two.
   The $40 million would keep supplies flowing to the rebels as
they wait out the continuing negotiations in cease-fire zones
inside Nicaragua. The aid would flow at a rate comparable to that
provided before Feb. 29, when the last U.S. support ran out. The
package also would include $10 million to pay the expenses of a
commission to verify compliance with the peace accord.
   ``For this (peace) effort to work, there's got to be this aid,''
said Adolfo Calero, a leader of the rebel political directorate,
who met with Wright and other congressional leaders on the aid
package.
   Any new aid for the Contras would have to conform to the
requirements of a 60-day truce reached last week between the rebels
and the Managua government.
   That agreement said the Contras would receive only humanitarian
aid and that the aid would be routed through ``neutral
organizations.'' The CIA has delivered past U.S. aid supplies to
the Contras.
   Calero said he told Wright and House Minority Leader Robert
Michel, R-Ill., that the term ``neutral organizations'' meant a
commercial transport company acceptable to the rebels, and not a
relief organization such as the Red Cross, which Wright had
previously mentioned as the delivery agent.
   Other details of the package remained to be determined, such as
whether it would include communications gear for the rebels or
special programs such as a $14 million effort to help children who
are victims of the nearly 7-year-old civil war, which has claimed
some 40,000 lives.
   Republicans wary of Sandinista promises have sought to give
Reagan the right to a quick, guaranteed vote in Congress on a later
request for new military aid to the Contras if the peace process
breaks down. As expected, that was proving to be the most difficult
issue.
   Wright and Michel were seeking a compromise that would indicate
continued U.S. backing for the rebels during the cease-fire, but
would give Congress the final say on the nature of any future aid
package.
   After meeting Monday with the Contra leadership, Secretary of
State George P. Shultz told reporters it would ``certainly be
desirable'' to have assurances of quick action on additional aid to
the Contras if the peace talks break down, and Calero agreed.
   In last wek's agreement, the Sandinistas promised a general
amnesty for the rebels, which began with the release Sunday of 100
prisoners. They also committed themselves to a restoration of the
rights of free speech and political participation, in return for
the 60-day cease-fire and the relocation of Contra forces into
special zones.
   Representatives of the two sides are meeting this week to work
out the details of a long-term cease-fire, including when the
rebels will lay down their weapons.
</TEXT>
