<DOCNO> AP880329-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1413EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reporters'Notes     03-29 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reporters' Notes,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Expands Protections For New York Journalists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalists have special protection against
court-ordered disclosure of notes, photographs and other
information gathered on a non-confidential basis, New York's
highest court ruled Tuesday.
   In a 6-0 ruling, the state Court of Appeals formulated for the
first time a test to be used when courts are asked to require
disclosure. The test, the court said, protects reporters more than
other people against divulging information.
   ``The autonomy of the press would be jeopardized if resort to
its resource materials, by litigants seeking to utilize the
newsgathering efforts of journalists for their private purposes,
were routinely permitted,'' Judge Stewart Hancock Jr. wrote for the
court.
   Hancock added that ``because journalists typically gather
information about accidents, crimes and other matters of special
interest that often give rise to litigation,'' requiring routine
disclosure of those materials ``would be widespread.''
   The ruling said courts can order journalists to turn over
non-confidential information only if it is ``highly material'' to
the litigation, ``critical'' to the claim being brought in court
and ``not otherwise available.''
   The case before the court involved attempts by a man injured in
an auto accident at a construction site to sue the contractors. A
photographer for the Gannett Rochester Newspapers took 58
photographs of the accident scene, one of which was published in
the Rochester Democrat and Chronicle.
   Lawyers for the man sought copies of all the pictures in the
process of building its case.
   Gannett refused, but two state courts, state Supreme Court in
Monroe County and the Appellate Division of state Supreme Court,
ruled that since the photographs were gathered on a
non-confidential basis, their disclosure wasn't protected under the
state Shield Law.
   Peter Danziger, who filed a brief with the court in the case on
behalf of the New York State Newspaper Publishers Association and
several news organizations, called the ruling ``a tremendous
victory for the public and the press.''
   Danziger's brief was filed on behalf of The Associated Press,
Newsday, The New York Times, Ottaway Newspapers, Advance
Publications, Capital Cities-ABC Inc., CBS Inc. and NBC Inc.
</TEXT>
