<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NixonLibrary     03-29 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nixon Library,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Clemente Ponders Future Without Nixon Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN CLEMENTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some merchants in this beach city
say the loss of the Richard M. Nixon Presidential Library will hurt
tourism so much they may be forced to close.
   But one historian suggests a museum dedicated to the president
who once lived here could be the answer.
   ``Nixon was here for 11 years and cannot be neglected,'' said
San Clemente Historical Society President Charles Ashbaugh. ``It's
not a case of apathy in the city. It's just that everyone has
thrown their hands up and said, `What can we do now?'''
   A 13-acre blufftop property owned by the Lusk Co. was targeted
for several years as the future home of the library. But it was
tied to a private development, and after numerous delays, Nixon
decided to put the library in Yorba Linda, where he was born. Nixon
now lives in Saddle River, N.J.
   With the library and its estimated 40 million pages of official
documents, photographs, videotapes, recordings and gifts from
foreign leaders went merchants' dreams of tourist dollars.
   ``I'm going to close my business,'' said Mike Lazarus, who has
owned a shop called Jeans Alley for 13 years. ``Now that the town
blew it and lost the library ... that really killed the town
business-wise. The city had expected it to bring anywhere from
300,000 to 600,000 people here a year.''
   A group called Citizens for a Responsive Council tried
unsuccessfully to recall three City Council members after the loss
of the library.
   ``I think there are some people who are bitter out there, who
have invested some time and money into the city becoming a resort
center and who thought they were going to make some money on the
tourist thing,'' said Tom Davis, spokesman for the Chamber of
Commerce.
   The historical society holds such trinkets as presidential
matchbooks and playing cards, toothpaste from China and menus from
state dinners.
   Meanwhile, Ashbaugh is trying to establish a museum in honor of
the nation's 37th president, and Olen Hanson, the city's founder.
It would be located in Hanson's former home, a 20-room villa called
Casa Romantica.
   The home's current owner, George Welsh, wants to sell, but does
not want the estate bulldozed for development. Interested buyers
include two developers, one of whom would give the house to the
historical society and build condos nearby; and the city, which
would provide half the house for a museum.
</TEXT>
