<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Panama     03-29 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Panama,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Sees Evidence Noriega Forces Trying to Sabotage Canal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, R-N.Y., said Tuesday
he has evidence that Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's troops are
trying to sabotage the Panama Canal, and he called on President
Reagan to quickly take ``whatever steps necessary to bring about
Noriega's removal.''
   D'Amato, while declining to specify his sources, said he has
obtained ``information that the Panama Defense Forces are now
actively looking to sabotage the canal.''
   He said he knows of one attempt ``to cut the wires to disable
one of the locks,'' and of other episodes in which canal employees
were threatened and beaten.
   With Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., and Panamanian Ambassador Juan B.
Sosa, a Noriega opponent, at his side, D'Amato declared at a news
conference that ``the crisis in Panama is becoming more and more a
danger to the security of the United States.''
   ``Many Cuban intelligence officers and technical people are
being flown into Panama,'' he said. ``The strategically important
canal is the next step. It would be tragic if the canal fell into
(Cuban President Fidel) Castro's hands.''
   Neither senator called directly for armed intervention by the
United States, but D'Amato declared that ``decisive action is
imperative. The longer we delay, the Cubanization of Panama becomes
a very real threat ... and we run the risk of losing the support of
the people of Panama.''
   ``I'm not going to specifically suggest the means,'' said
D'Amato. ``But we have the force necessary to bring about the legal
removal of Noriega.''
   Kerry agreed, saying he cannot understand why ``part of the
administration is working on a policy that says `Noriega must go,'
and part of it is working on how we deal with him if he manages to
stay on.''
   D'Amato said he had expressed his views earlier in the day to
Defense Department officials, and expected Reagan to get the
message via the media. ``We have not seen the decisive action from
the president that this situation calls for,'' he said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, in decrying the use of
violence by Noriega's forces, restated Tuesday that it has been
U.S. policy not to intervene militarily. But he also said, ``It has
always been a principle that we will protect American citizens as
best we can.''
</TEXT>
