<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Military     03-29 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Military,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Court Sentences Soldiers Convicted of Live Burial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two soldiers who admitted beating and burying
alive four Arabs were sentenced Tuesday to jail terms that were
stiffer than those requested by prosecutors, Israeli radio reported.
   In passing sentence on Pvt. Dror Segen-Cohen and Pvt. Yair
Nissimi, the military court ruled that their conduct was grave and
shameful in the Feb. 5 incident in the village of Kfar Salem, the
radio said.
   The court sentenced Segen-Cohen to six months in jail along with
a four-month suspended sentence; Nissimi received five months in
jail along with a seven-month suspended sentence.
   The soldiers admitted they beat four Arabs from Kfar Salem in
the occupied West Bank to put down a demonstration there, then
buried them in about 25 inches of mud.
   Lt. Aryeh Moscona, the military prosecutor, reached a plea
bargain agreement with the soldiers' lawyers and asked for two
months in jail for Segen-Cohen and 2{ months for Nissimi.
   The court ruled, however, that the soldiers' behavior had
tarnished the army's image and put Israel in a bad light.
   A third soldier, Sgt. Maj. Charlie Danino, is accused of
ordering the burial. He has pleaded innocent and his trial is still
under way.
   Five other soldiers also are on trial for violating military
orders. One has been charged in the killing of a Palestinian in the
Gaza Strip, and four others are accused of beating two Palestinian
detainees after a demonstration in Nablus.
</TEXT>
