<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MiamiPolice     03-29 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miami Police,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Ex-Officers Sentenced To 20 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former police officers and the father of one of
them were sentenced Tuesday to federal prison for their roles in a
cocaine-ripoff ring organized by rogue officers.
   Former Officer Felix A. Beruvides, 30, told U.S. District Judge
James W. Kehoe that he had ``disgraced the members of the Miami
Police Department, disgraced the badge I wore and disgraced my
family.''
   Beruvides asked Kehoe to ``give my father probation and give me
any sentence that you would have given him,'' but the judge
rejected the request.
   The younger Beruvides and former Officer Armando Lopez, 26, were
sentenced to 20 years in federal prison on counts of racketeering
and a tax violation.
   Felix C. Beruvides, 59, was sentenced to eight years under a
plea bargain for conspiracy to possess cocaine. He was permitted to
remain free pending a decision by the U.S. Bureau of Prison on
where the term would be served.
   A fourth defendant, former Officer Ricardo Perez, still faces
trial. No date has been set.
   The government charged the officers were involved in the theft
of 147 kilograms of cocaine from a boat on the Miami River on May
31, 1985.
   The father was accused of participating in the theft and earning
$21,500 for guarding 180 pounds of marijuana stolen during a
traffic stop on Oct. 24, 1984.
   The drownings of three drug boat guards and a drug dealer whose
body was found in a box in the field have been linked to the police
ring. None of the three men sentenced Tuesday were charged in the
deaths.
   Other people were charged with civil-rights murder, and those
charges are pending.
</TEXT>
