<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     03-29 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Of Shakeup in Czechoslovak Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia has requested that
Chancellor Franz Vranitzky of Austria postpone a visit to Prague,
and there were reports Tuesday that a government shakeup was
planned.
   There have been rumors that Premier Lubomir Strougal, a leading
advocate of reform in Czechoslovakia, is on his way out.
   Vranitzky told Austrian journalists Monday that the Czechoslovak
leadership had asked him to postpone a visit set for April 17-20.
The Austrian Press Agency reported the reason given for the
postponement was a planned government shuffle in Prague.
   The Czechoslovak government spokesman told journalists in Prague
that a bill would be presented at a National Assembly meeting April
19 for the abolition of some ministries by merging them with others.
   However, the Austria Press Agency quoted sources close to
Vranitzky as saying that Austria's charge d'affaires in Prague was
called to the Czechoslovak premier's office Monday.
   The news agency said an official in Strougal's office asked that
the visit be postponed because the country was in a ``delicate
situation'' in view of pending government changes.
   It quoted the sources as saying the Czechoslovak leadership did
not want Vrantizky to have to meet with negotiating partners when
``we don't know how long they will remain in the government.''
   There have been increasing rumours that Strougal was on his way
out since Gustav Husak stepped down as Communist Party chief in
December and was replaced by Milos Jakes. Husak retained the
presidency.
   Jakes is not seen as a reformer likely to initiate the kind of
economic and politial reforms now being enacted in the Soviet
Union, Poland, Hungary and Bulgaria.
</TEXT>
