<2ND_LINE>AM-Secret Agent, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0693,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Can't Believe Daughter is Israeli Secret Agent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts top 7 grafs to clarify that Vanunu claimed he was
arrested in Rome, but not confirmed; delete 2nd full reference to
Cheryl Hanin Bentov</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a young woman identified as
the agent who lured Israeli nuclear dissident Mordechai Vanunu to
his capture says he was startled to hear of his daughter's alleged
espionage activities.
   ``Of course I was shocked,'' said Stanley Hanin. ``Could you
picture your daughter involved in anything like this?''
   Hanin, owner of the Allied Discount Tires chain, spoke to
reporters Monday after viewing a television program Sunday that
described Cheryl Hanin Bentov's alleged role in the capture of
Vanunu, who disclosed details of Israel's nuclear weapons program
to a British newspaper in 1986.
   ``This is the first I've heard of anything like this,'' said
Hanin. ``I find this totally unbelievable.''
   Days after The Sunday Times published Vanunu's revelations, he
disappeared from a London hotel where he had been living under an
assumed name and later surfaced in an Israeli jail. Vanunu was
tried in secret in Israel and sentenced Sunday to 18 years in
prison for treason.
   Vanunu's brother Meir, who lives in London, has claimed that
Israeli secret service agents used a woman named ``Cindy'' to lure
his brother to Rome with the promise of sex. He says agents
captured and drugged his brother there and spirited him to Israel
for trial.
   The CBS program ``60 Minutes'' Sunday identified ``Cindy'' as
Mrs. Bentov, an agent of the Israeli secret service Mossad and wife
of Ofer Bentov, a major in Israeli military intelligence.
   Hanin said his daughter moved to Israel 10 years ago at age 17
after studying there in a student exchange program. He said they
are not close and he has not heard from her ``for some time,'' and
that he doesn't know where she lives.
   ``I would be concerned for her safety if I thought there was a
shred of truth to this,'' Hanin said. ``But I don't think there's a
speck of truth to it.''
   Lowell Boggs, assistant principal at Edgewater High School,
where Cheryl Hanin went to school, said she was a good student who
spent the final semester of her senior year studying in Israel for
about five months.
   Boggs said that over the past 1{ years, the school has been
visited by two private detectives who asked to see her yearbook
picture, a reporter from London and another from Miami asking about
her, and, last spring, a man with credentials showing him to be
from the CIA.
   Edgewater Principal Charles Rohrer said the FBI also came by the
school to ``go through her records three or four times.''
</TEXT>
