<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PregnantPrisoner 1stLd-Writethru a0673 03-29 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pregnant Prisoner, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0673,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Close To Giving Birth Arrested On Minor Traffic Violation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS ``was'' to ``said'' in 10th graf bgng Mrs. Taylor</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EDGEWATER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21-year-old woman near delivery with
her first child ended up jailed and in handcuffs instead of in a
hospital, all over a traffic violation.
   Kimberly Taylor was arrested at her home at 5:20 a.m. Saturday
because she had failed to appear in court March 18 on the traffic
charge.
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Mrs. Taylor said Monday, after a
visit to her doctor, who said the baby could arrive any time. ``It
was so stupid. You'd think they'd have better things to do than
bother me on a Saturday morning.''
   Mrs. Taylor said her doctor told her the stress from the
incident with the police may be prolonging her labor. She said the
sac of water surrounding the baby broke Saturday about an hour
before she was arrested.
   Police said officer Brad Maerz was near the end of his shift
Saturday when he knocked on the Taylors' door, told her to get
dressed and took her to the police station.
   Mrs. Taylor said she was in a holding cell when she overheard
Maerz tell another officer he made the arrest because ``I was
bored.''
   Police Chief Henry Smith said the Taylors had filed a complaint.
   ``There will be an internal investigation to look at the
circumstances and determine whether good judgment was used in the
matter,'' Smith said. ``We'll look at any possible violation of
procedure.''
   Smith said Mrs. Taylor was arrested on a bench warrant from
Jefferson County Court for failure to appear at a hearing. She was
cited Jan. 21 for driving a car with expired license plates and not
having a valid driver's license.
   Mrs. Taylor said that when she was taken from the police
department to the county jail, ``they didn't want anything to do
with a woman whose contractions were coming about 15 minutes
apart.''
   As she was being released from the county jail, she said she was
taken from her cell to the release area in handcuffs.
   Mrs. Taylor's husband, Paul, said his wife just didn't have her
driver's license with her that day.
   As for the expired plates, ``We had just bought that car, and we
were waiting for the title to get new plates,'' he said. ``We have
that all taken care of now, but we forgot about the court date
because we've been dealing with complications with the pregnancy
for the last month. We've been worried about that, and we spaced
out the court date. But we think the whole thing has been handled
unfairly and unprofessionally.''
</TEXT>
