<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1540EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AdoptionBattle     03-29 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Adoption Battle,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Nullifying Adoption Of Son Of Murder Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The case of a 4-year-old boy adopted in two
states by sets of warring relatives after his father killed his
mother came nearer resolution Tuesday when the Indiana Court of
Appeals upheld the voiding of the adoption here.
   The court unanimously affirmed an April 1987 Grant County
Circuit Court decision invalidating the adoption of Phillip Taylor
by his paternal grandparents, Everett L. and Jean K. Taylor, of
Marion.
   The boy has since been adopted by Celeste Benigno White, sister
of the boy's mother, and her husband, Jefferson White, of the New
York City borough of Staten Island.
   A legal fight over the child followed the Nov. 11, 1984, murder
of his mother, Teresa Benigno Taylor, in New Jersey. Her husband,
Dr. Kenneth Taylor, was convicted in 1985 of first-degree murder
and sentenced to life imprisonment.
   After the murder, a New Jersey court granted joint custody of
the child to the Whites and the Taylors with the Taylors to have
custody in July and August and during the week after Christmas each
year. The Whites were to keep the child the rest of the year.
   In late 1985, the Whites filed a custody petition in New York,
and in January 1986, the Taylors filed an adoption petition in
Grant County. The Taylors had earlier filed an adoption petition
that wasn't acted on in New Jersey.
   As part of their Indiana petition, the Taylors filed Kenneth
Taylor's consent to the adoption. However, according to court
records, the Whites weren't notified of the proceeding, and the
petition didn't mention that the boy's father had been convicted of
murder or that a New Jersey court had acted on the child's custody.
   During a visit to Indiana in August 1986, Phillip was formally
adopted by the Taylors. In a telephone call to Mrs. White, Mrs.
Taylor said that ``the Taylors had adopted Phillip and that the
Whites would never see him again,'' court records said.
   The Whites challenged the adoption by arguing that their consent
and that of the New Jersey court was required.
   The Taylors contended that because they had the consent of their
son, Phillip's only living parent, they needed no one else's
consent.
   The lower court held and the appeals panel confirmed Tuesday
that consent of all parties involved _ including the other court
and custodial parents _ must be obtained before Indiana law permits
an adoption.
   ``A decree of adoption may be entered only if the required
consents were obtained,'' Judge William Garrard wrote for the
court. ``As the Taylors failed to obtain all the required consents,
the judgment of the adoption was voidable.''
   The Taylors have not said whether they will appeal Tuesday's
ruling to the Indiana Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1546EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentEspionage     03-29 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Espionage,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Virginia University Forms Committee To Study Possible
Conflicts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Virginia University administrators
set up a committee Tuesday to explore the ethical obligations of
students who do ``corporate espionage'' for companies under the
auspices of the university.
   The announcement, made by Frank Franz, vice president for
academic affairs, comes one week after the Wall Street Journal
reported that graduate students in the business school divulged
sales and inventory figures gained in a study to competitors of the
businesses they surveyed.
   ``The article points out that the confidentiality of respondents
was promised but not observed,'' Franz said.
   ``The key problem is that the students were put in a very
unfortunate position by the sponsors of the project and I think
inappropriate things were asked of them.''
   Franz said the seven-member committee will consider whether
students should be required to disclose routinely the sponsor of a
study, its purpose and who will receive the information obtained.
   He said the committee also will suggest ways to avoid conflicts
of interest in internships, research projects and other
opportunities that arise through consulting performed by faculty
members for private companies.
   The Journal reported that two groups of students who conducted
competitive analyses for two Caterpillar heavy-equipment dealers
were asked by the dealers to identify the competitors they
interviewed.
   Several students said they did. One of those involved likened
the work to ``spying.''
   Representatives of two of the dealerships interviewed for the
1987 study said they would not have given out the information if
they had known the students were working for other dealers.
   ``I feel the way they went about it was very underhanded,'' Gary
Clark, executive vice president of Clark Co., one of the companies
in the study, told the Daily Anthenaeum, the student newspaper.
   ``Now I will probably be on my guard whenever I talk to
students. But I don't blame the students. I blame the professor.''
   Terry Wilson, professor of the Marketing 321 class, told the
Journal that the students ``should not have divulged confidential
information to their clients.''
   Franz said there is no evidence that Wilson, who is a consultant
for Caterpillar, encouraged the students to give the information to
the dealerships.
   Wilson, who is on a yearlong sabbatical from the university, did
not return telephone messages left with his office.
</TEXT>
