<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthStatistics     03-29 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Statistics,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women's Enrollment Up Sharply In Health Profession Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proportion of women enrolled in schools
for health professions has skyrocketed in recent years, according
to a federal statistical analysis issued Tuesday.
   The most striking increase was in dental schools, where women
made up only 1 percent of enrollment in the 1971-72 school term. By
the 1985-86 term, the figure was 25 percent.
   Enrollment of women in medical schools jumped from 11 percent to
33 percent over the same period, and in pharmacy schools from 24
percent to 56 percent.
   Those are among figures contained in the 207-page ``Health
United States 1987,'' a report issued annually by the Department of
Health and Human Services.
   Most of the figures were released previously as they were being
compiled by one or more of the dozens of agencies within HHS, and
tend to lag a year or two behind the volume's publication.
   The National Center for Health Statistics, an arm of the Centers
for Disease Control, organizes the material into an annual report _
as required by law _ to provide a central storehouse of statistical
data.
   The 1987 volume documents that life expectancy at birth has
increased dramatically since 1900 for all Americans, regardless of
race or sex.
   For example, a black female born in 1900 could expect to live
only 33.5 years compared with 62.7 years for one born in 1950 and
73.5 years for one born in 1985.
   Although there have been life expectacy gains across the board,
the smallest increase _ 25 years _ was among white males. A white
male born in 1900 could expect to live 46.6 years compared with
71.9 years for one born in 1985.
   Some other highlights:
   _Infant mortality declined only 2 percent between 1984 and 1985,
the smallest drop since 1965. The black infant mortality rate, 18.2
per 1,000 live births, is almost twice as high as for white
infants, 9.3 per 1,000.
   _Births to unmarried mothers doubled between 1970 and 1985, from
11 percent to 22 percent.
   _Between 1970 and 1985, mortality from cancer, the second
leading cause of death, increased slightly overall. However, lung
cancer deaths among women more than doubled. Heart disease remains
the No. 1 killer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
