<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietPostal     03-29 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Postal,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Mail Handling Criticized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union stops or delays mail to put
pressure on dissidents, former Moscow activist Vladimir Slepak told
a congressional subcommittee Tuesday.
   ``The goal of the Soviet authorities is to isolate people from
any contact with the outside world. This is an effort to break our
spirit and determination,'' Slepak said.
   Telephones, mail and telegrams are all cut off or interfered
with, Slepak told the House Post Office and Civil Service
subcommittee on postal operations. The subcommittee is
investigating complaints of returned and undelivered mail sent to
the Soviet Union.
   ``The problem is not the bad work of the Soviet post office. It
is because of the order of the KGB or other authorities,'' said
Slepak.
   He cited his five years in exile in Siberia, when he regularly
received mail from other countries. Upon his return to Moscow in
1982, mail was cut off, he said.
   Slepak was allowed to leave the Soviet Union last year following
a pair of hunger strikes by himself in Moscow and his son in
Washington.
   Rep. Benjamin A. Gilman, R-N.Y., noted that the subcommittee
first started looking into the problem in 1977.
   With better international relations there may be hope for
improvement, Gilman said, but ``we must not be lulled into
believing that the problem has been or is close to being resolved.''
   Assistant Postmaster General William T. Johnstone said in
prepared testimony that the rate of returned parcels has declined
in the past year. Yet, he added, ``while fewer parcels apparently
are being returned, the practice remains a troublesome one.''
   The Soviet Union has a long and complex list of unacceptable
goods, Johnstone said.
   Another problem exists with registered mail, which many people
use because the item must be signed for, he added.
   Unlike the United States, where the person receiving the mail
must sign, Soviet policy is for a postal official to sign the
receipt, Johnstone said.
   ``We plan to exert every effort to try to persuade the Soviet
Union to change its policy,'' he said.
   One new problem will be arising shortly, Johnstone added.
   Starting May 1, the Soviet Union will require customs
declarations on parcels to be written in either French or Russian.
   It is common practice to require declarations in either French
or the language of the receiving country, he said. But in the past
the Soviets have made exceptions to allow English.
   They announced the change to only French or Russian early in
1987, but postponed implementation twice to accommodate the United
States, Johnstone said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
