<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Venezuela-Drugs     03-29 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela-Drugs,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Resigns Amid Drug-Corruption Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The justice minister has resigned
after a former policeman said the minister headed a secret
anti-narcotics police that sold confiscated drugs and weapons.
   Minister Jose Manzo Gonzalez's resignation was effective Monday.
He had been justice minister since 1984.
   He was replaced Tuesday by Pedro Torres Agudo, former head of
the Technical Judicial Police, Venezuela's principal investigative
police corps.
   The newspaper, El Universal, reported Tuesday that Gonzalez
resigned to aid a police investigation and to take legal action
against people who allegedly injured his prestige.
   Manzo's resignation came on the same day as the resignation of
his counterpart in Colombia, Alfredo Gutierrez Marquez. Gutierrez
stepped down after reports that an airstrip at his brother's ranch
was used by drug runners linked to Colombia Medellin cartel.
   The cartel smuggles most of the cocaine reaching the United
States, the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration says.
   In a videotape played two weeks ago before the Investigations
Committee of the Venezuelan Congress, former police Roberto Eduardo
Dipucci Ponti said Manzo set up a secret police unit to infiltrate
narcotics rings in Venezuela.
   Dipucci Ponti said the unit captured drugs and weapons from
narcotics traffickers and then resold them.
   The former officer said he was a member of the secret force and
that he made the videotape because he feared for his life. Dipucci
reportedly is in hiding in Venezuela.
   The president of the Investigations Committee, Paciano Padron,
called for Manzo's removal after initial investigations indicated
the existence of the secret unit and irregularities in its
activities.
   The committee began its investigations in February after a
leftist politician claimed Venezuela's political parties were
financing their presidential campaigns with drug money.
   Padron also maintained the police unit itself was illegal since
it depended directly on Manzo rather than one of the official
Venezuelan security forces.
   Manzo has said that the secret force existed between 1982 and
1986 but claimed it was a military agency.
   Defense Minister Eliodoro Guerrero Gomez has denied the unit
ever operated within the military.
</TEXT>
