<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     03-29 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filipino Troops Seize Six Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military said its troops stormed
a capital suburb Tuesday and captured six communist guerrillas,
including three top leaders, as rebels marked the anniversary of
their struggle.
   Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa hailed the arrests in the
Manila suburb of San Juan as ``a big loss'' to the communists. He
said those captured were ``very high-ranking personalities who have
been the subject of many manhunts and many operations in the past.''
   Troops in Manila and five other regions had been placed on
heightened alert in anticipation of rebel attacks on the
anniversary of the 24,000-member New People's Army, a communist
group that began fighting the government 19 years ago.
   The top leaders were identified as Rafael Baylosis, secretary
general of the Communist Party of the Philippines; Benjamin de
Vera, a party central committee member; and New People's Army Chief
of Staff Napoleon Manuel. A military report says de Vera also heads
the party's commission in charge of operations on Mindanao, the
country's second-largest island where the rebels have been strong.
   No major rebel attacks were reported Tuesday. However, such
reports often take days to reach Manila from the countryside.
   A Japanese tourist was shot and killed near the Manila airport
by an unidentified gunman who escaped, police said. Akihiro Sato,
49, died from bullet wounds in the neck and shoulder.
   Police said they had no idea who the killer was.
   Military leaders also announced Tuesday they had determined that
rebels from the Alex Boncayao Brigade, the Manila branch of the New
People's Army, were responsible for Monday's ambush on suburban
Manila Mayor Prospero Oreta. Seven of his bodyguards were killed
and the mayor, a distant relative of President Corazon Aquino, was
wounded.
   Officers said those captured Tuesday might not have been
directly involved, but they definitely came from the same
organizations.
   ``In general, the (Oreta) case is solved,'' said Brig. Gen.
Alexander Aguirre. ``All we have to do is to arrest the people who
perpetrated it. But we are happy to say now that we did not only
arrest the (people) that did the hitting but the leaders who are
orchestrating these assassination activities.''
   The rebel leaders were arrested Tuesday in two separate raids.
An AK-47 rifle, grenades, computers, radio equipment, and
underground documents were confiscated in the raids, Aguirre said.
   He said Mrs. Aquino had been informed about the arrests and
``she was elated, she was glad.''
   On Monday, the Alex Boncayao Brigade admitted responsibility for
Sunday's murder of bus driver Ruben Saulog. They accused him of
ordering the killings of two unions leaders.
</TEXT>
