<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria-Births     03-29 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria-Births,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Health Minister Predicts Doubling Of Population</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nigeria's estimated population of 100
million will double in the next two decades unless Nigerian women
have fewer children, the health minister said Tuesday.
   The News Agency of Nigeria quoted Health Minister Ransome-Kuti
as saying the military government's new population policy was aimed
at preserving the health of the ``mothers and their children''
rather than simply reducing population growth.
   The government has adopted a policy calling on women to limit
themselves to four children each. Womens' groups and Christian
churches say the policy is unfair because it would allow polygamous
men to have many children and favors the Moslem religion.
   Ransome-Kuti, in detailing the policy, said efforts would be
made to counsel men on their responsibilities to their spouses and
children.
   He said the government would make family planning services
available nationwide, but would not try to force couples to limit
births.
   ``Couples will be encouraged to have the number of children they
can adequately care for,'' he said.
   Ransome-Kuti said the government hopes to persuade women to
marry after age 18 and to space births at least two years apart.
   He said the policy seeks to reduce annual population growth from
3.3 percent to 2.5 percent in 1995 and 2 percent by 2000.
   Nigeria is Africa's most populous country.
</TEXT>
