<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Harold'sNewStart     03-29 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harold's New Start,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harold's Back in the Riverside Shack Part Time, with Prospects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Thomas was back in his shack Tuesday
alongside the Chicago River after a failed journey to New Mexico in
search of a new life, but he said he was trying to find work and a
decent home.
   ``I've been trying to get me a decent place to stay and I got an
interview about a regular job tomorrow,'' he said. ``I feel like
I've got to make something out of myself some way or other, because
so many people were concerned.
   ``And besides, I owe it to myself,'' said Thomas, who hopes to
find a construction job with a former employer.
   Since his return from Portales, N.M., a week ago, Thomas has
divided his time between a girlfriend's apartment and the
wood-and-tarpaper shack he and friend Tommy Ray built late last
year on a vacant, bottle-strewn lot in the shadow of the city's
glittering downtown.
   ``I go by and help clean it up, and I stay there sometimes,'' he
said of the makeshift shelter by the Chicago River. ``Tommy and
them are sort of my people, like family.
   ``And that's the place where it all happened.''
   Thomas' sojourn to the Southwest began when a New Mexico couple,
Roy and Ethel Gilman, read an Associated Press story describing his
life in the open shack during sub-zero weather.
   They offered him a job and a place to stay.
   Thomas arrived in Portales on Jan. 17 and spent two months with
the Gilmans, receiving room and board in exchange for work at the
couple's wrecking yard.
   But Thomas said he was paid no wages until reporters raised the
issue and the Gilmans put $300 in a bank account for him.
   Thomas withdrew the money and bought a bus ticket home.
   ``They were hard-working, good people, but the money situation
disappointed me,'' said Thomas.
   ``A man needs a regular wage, he needs to be able to buy himself
a cup of coffee or a sandwich. And I think the Gilmans got tired of
all the attention that came with me,'' he said.
   One thing was simplified by his brief fling with celebrity:
reinstatement of the $154 a month in public assistance and food
stamps he had been receiving before he went to New Mexico.
   When he attempted Monday to pick up his March check, Thomas was
told he would have to furnish proof he had worked the two previous
months, and that his job had ended, said social worker Clara
Collins with the non-profit Travelers and Immigrants Aid.
   ``He went back to the shack and brought them his newspaper
clippings,'' Ms. Collins said. ``At first, they said there were
plenty of Harold Thomases, but I guess they finally gave in.''
   So Tuesday, $154 richer and buoyed by the prospect of a job
interview, Thomas picked up some Italian beef sandwiches and headed
for the hovel he still calls home sometimes.
   There, Ray, 37, and 62-year-old Arthur Haymond, another of the
five or six men who share the rotting, often-leaky shack, waited
eagerly for his arrival.
   ``It's funny,'' said Ray. ``After people first read about us,
they came by with a can of coffee, or a loaf of bread to help out.
Or talk about where we might find work.
   ``But since then, hasn't been much but the gang kids throwing
stones and busting us up.
   ``I guess,'' said Ray, rubbing his chin and pulling up closer to
the fire burning in an oil drum, ``people just got short memories.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
