<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AgeDiscrimination     03-29 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Age Discrimination,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEOC Says Lack of Money Short-Circuited Many Job Discrimination
Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission
mishandled hundreds of age discrimination complaints partly because
Congress failed to give it enough money, EEOC Chairman Clarence
Thomas said Tuesday.
   In testimony to the House Government Operations subcommittee on
employment and housing, Thomas said there was no excuse for agency
offices having let the two-year statute of limitations expire on
some 1,600 complaints from Oct. 1, 1986, to Jan. 31, 1988.
   But he said that in order to prevent such situations from
recurring, the agency needs more money.
   ``I have been through the budget process seven times now, and
each time, Congress has appropriated less than what was requested
by President Reagan,'' Thomas said in his statement.
   For example, he said, the agency sought $193.4 million this year
but received only $179.8 million, and it has been told its
prospects for receiving a requested $194.6 million in 1989 do not
look good.
   ``If EEOC is held to a 2 percent increase over the fiscal 1988
appropriation, we will lose 244 positions and the pending inventory
of charges will grow by 20,000,'' Thomas said.
   Subcommittee chairman Tom Lantos, D-Calif., said a recent panel
investigation of the National Labor Relations Board found that 92
percent of unfair labor charges are fully investigated within 30
days.
   ``If the NLRB regional offices can meet a 30-day time target,
why does it take EEOC regional offices more than two years to
perform similar investigations?'' Lantos said. ``We should not need
repeated hearings and legislative action to ensure and to restore
workers' basic civil rights which have long since been established
in law.''
   In his statement, Thomas said the regional offices attributed
their problems to, among other things, short staffing, complex and
unprecedented cases, poor case tracking, heavy workload and charges
filed six months to 18 months after an alleged violation.
   He said the worst offender was the Philadelphia regional office
with 241 charges that expired, followed by Los Angeles with 222;
Baltimore with 175; New York with 150; Chicago with 137; and
Detroit with 105. San Francisco had no instances, while Atlanta and
Charlotte, N.C., had one apiece.
   Helen McDonald, representing the American Association of Retired
Persons, said the EEOC must give people realistic advice about
whether their cases will be pursued and tell them clearly about the
two-year deadline.
   She also said the EEOC should change its policy of refusing to
notify people who might benefit from a class action, even when the
agency already has determined an employer has discriminated.
Currently it is the responsibility of potential members of the
class action to find out about the complaint and join it.
   The House on Tuesday passed a bill extending the statute of
limitations another 18 months for people whose cases expired
without EEOC action. The Senate already has passed a similar
measure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
