<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MailEscorts     03-29 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mail Escorts,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postman Defies Sleet, Snow But Needs Bodyguards For Dogs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fed up with dog bites, mail carrier Jim Codner
made his rounds in the company of two dog catchers from the city's
animal control department when he delivered mail Tuesday at a
housing project.
   Unlike Monday, when three dogs were taken into custody, there
wasn't a canine in sight as Codner delivered the mail with his
companions, who were armed with dog snares _ three-foot and
five-foot sticks with rubber-coated wires at the end to catch any
pooch on the loose.
   ``At least if the dogs come out, they'll have a few more
targets,'' Codner said, when he resumed deliveries. ``Usually it's
just me and the hallway.''
   Mail delivery to 240 households at the Orient Heights rojects
was suspended March 12 after Codner, who has delivered mail there
for seven years, was attacked for the fourth time this year by one
of the dogs roaming the halls.
   For the two weeks Codner didn't bring any mail, it was left at a
post office more than half a mile away.
   ``It was really hard for the elderly people who needed their
mail and couldn't get it,'' said Jackie Thurston, who lives in the
project.
   ``It feels good to have Jimmy and the mail back,'' said Connie
Durbano, another resident.
   The escorted service will last a week. If Codner's customers
don't get the message by then, the Postal Service has threatened to
deliver mail to a single drop instead of door to door.
   Steven O'Donnell, the city's chief dog catcher, said he has
eight inspectors and two trucks _ one currently broken _ to cover a
city of 65,000 dogs. O'Donnell complained that the city won't
invest in better dog control. He also has proposed stiffer fines
for violators.
   The city requires dogs to be restrained at all times. But while
the dog owners are fined $50 if their pets are caught defecating on
the sidewalk, they are fined only $25 for dogs picked up roaming
free.
   In other carrier battlefronts of Massachusetts, mail delivery
was suspended temporarily in parts of Medford a few years ago to
protect carriers, and a carrier bitten in the face by a dog in
Winthrop last weekend may need plastic surgery.
   Every day, somewhere in America, a mail carrier is probably
being bitten, said delivery supervisor Phil Auciello, Codner's boss.
</TEXT>
