<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea-Corruption     03-29 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Corruption,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother of Former President Denies Corruption Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Chun Doo-hwan's younger
brother denied Tuesday that he stole millions of dollars from a
semi-official development agency, but prosecutors said they had
enough evidence to try him.
   A close associate of Chun Kyung-hwan, 46, tried to kill himself
while under interrogation and arrest warrants were issued for five
other people in the growing scandal.
   ``He keeps denying all charges, passing the buck to his
subordinates, but it would not work. We have enough evidence,''
senior prosecutor Lee Chong-chan said of Chun.
   Twelve hours after questioning, prosecutors gave no indication
whether he would be put under formal arrest. Officials had said
Monday he was not likely to be released.
   Prosecutors said their initial investigation indicated Chun
embezzled or otherwise pocketed the equivalent of $14 million
belonging to the Saemaul (New Community) Movement, which he headed
for seven years.
   The semi-official organization is dedicated to urban and rural
development. Chun Kyung-hwan was its director from 1981 until he
resigned last year after reports that he had links with the
underworld.
   According to the prosecutors, he is suspected of using the money
allegedly taken from Saemaul for such purposes as speculation in
land and stocks.
   Legal experts say charges being contemplated in the case could
result in more than five years in prison if Chun is convicted.
   Chun was summoned by prosecutors Tuesday morning for questioning
about allegations that he abused power to get government funds for
Saemaul and cash donations from business executives.
   When Chun arrived at the prosecutor general's office, a man
rushed from the crowd yelling an insult, hit him in the face and
fled.
   A ranking official of Saemaul, Hwang Hung-sik, 37, made two
suicide attempts during interrogation, once by trying to jump from
a fifth-floor window, officials reported.
   Hwang is accused of keeping secret ledgers on transactions
involving money Chun allegedly embezzled.
   About 200 government officials and business executives have been
questioned about allegedly helping Chun either to amass a fortune
or cover up the activity.
   Opposition parties demanded Tuesday that the former president
cut short a trip to the United States and state whether he was
involved in the scandal.
   Chun Doo-hwan was succeeded last month by Roh Tae-woo, who won
the presidential election in December.
   Roh, a former general who helped put Chun in power with military
backing in 1980, has promised to root out and end official
corruption.
</TEXT>
