<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SriLanka-Bomb     03-29 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka-Bomb,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb in Bag of Onions Kills 10 on Bus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A time bomb in a sack of onions being
taken to market exploded on a rural bus Tuesday, killing 10
Sinhalese farmers and critically wounding 15, police reported.
   A spokesman said nine of the dead were blown to pieces.
   Police blamed the explosion in north-central Sri Lanka on Tamil
militants who have fought since 1983 for a separate homeland for
the ethnic minority in the northern and eastern parts of the island.
   The bomb went off as the bus neared Ratmalagawewa, a village
near Anuradhpura City, about 100 miles northeast of Colombo, police
reported.
   ``Nine persons were blown to bits in the blast and one died in
the hospital. Fifteen more are in critical condition,'' said a
police spokesman at Anuradhpura. ``All are Sinhalese farmers taking
their produce to towns nearby.''
   He said, speaking on condition of anonymity, that the bomb was
the work of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the most powerful
rebel group. Eelam is what the Tamils would call a separate
homeland in the parts of Sri Lanka where the ethnic group is
dominant.
   More than 135 people, most of them Sinhalese, have been killed
in the Eastern and North Central provinces in the past 29 days,
since the latest round of violence began. Residents of Anuradhpura
said large numbers of soldiers were moving into the area for a
``cordon and search'' operation.
   In the southern region, a police sergeant was reported killed
and a constable seriously wounded by a man who opened fire with an
automatic rifle Monday in Tangalle, a town 90 miles southeast of
Colombo.
   Police in Tangalle said the gunman was from the outlawed
People's Liberation Front, a Sinhalese organization opposed to an
Indian-sponsored peace accord intended to halt the Tamil civil war.
   The agreement, signed last July, gives some autonomy to Tamil
areas. Sinhalese nationalists say it makes too many concessions.
   At least 220 killings have been blamed on the radical Sinhalese
group, which has vowed to kill anyone who supports the agreement.
   Sinhalese, most of whom are Buddhists, make up 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. Tamils, about 18 percent, are
predominantly Hindu and claim discrimination by the Sinhalese, who
control the government and army.
   At least 7,000 people have been killed in the five years since
the Tamils began fighting. India became involved as a peacemaker
because its 800 million people include about 60 million Tamils,
most of whom live in Tamil Nadu state just across the narrow Palk
Strait from Sri Lanka.
</TEXT>
