<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     03-29 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Counsel Asks State Attorneys General for Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Utah's attorney general has blasted
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh for asking judicial officials
around the country for help in the Iran-Contra case, but others
appear unconcerned about Walsh's activity.
   ``I wasn't going to give Lawrence Walsh's people the time of
day,'' David Wilkinson, the Utah official said, commenting on a
letter he received from the independent counsel's office.
   Jeffrey Toobin, an associate in Walsh's office, sent a letter
March 15 to U.S. attorneys and attorneys general in 50 states
seeking information about other cases involving immunity.
   James Wieghart, Walsh's spokesman, said Monday the letter was a
routine request to ensure that prosecutors are up-to-date on the
most recent case law.
   The letter asks judicial officials for ``anything you think
might be helpful _ established procedures, transcripts, briefs or
even informal office lore.'' The existence of the letter was first
revealed on the editorial page of The Wall Street Journal.
   Defendants in the Iran-Contra case are expected to challenge
Walsh on immunity because they received such grants from Congress
in exchange for testifying about the Iran-Contra case last summer.
   Former White House aides John M. Poindexter, Oliver L. North and
businessman Albert Hakim were granted immunity, but Richard V.
Secord, Hakim's partner, was not. The four are charged with
conspiracy and theft in the Iran-Contra case.
   Walsh cannot use any information from the congressional hearings
in court, and he must prove that his data was gathered
independently. Walsh has hired former federal Judge Herbert Stern
to supervise the handling of legal challenges.
   U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard Gesell has set April 12 for a
hearing on the immunity issue. Attorneys in the case must file
their papers by April 7.
   Wilkinson, who provided The Associated Press with a copy of the
Toobin letter, said he considered it a ``little bizarre that an
independent counsel would be seeking help from the state attorneys
general.''
   Wilkinson, a Republican, noted that there is a constitutional
dispute over the existence of the independent counsels, which were
created by Congress under the 1978 Ethics in Government Act.
   The Supreme Court is scheduled to hear arguments on April 26 on
a lower court decision that struck down the constitutionality of
the special prosecutors.
   Wilkinson said his ``sympathies are with the executive branch,
not the legislative branch.''
   But not everyone was as perturbed as Wilkinson about the letter.
   LeRoy Zimmerman, the GOP attorney general in Pennsylvania, has
directed his staff ``pass along any information or experiences
which would be helpful'' to Walsh's people, according to Bob
Gentzel, his spokesman.
   Attorneys in the office of Travis Medlock, South Carolina's
attorney general, are still reviewing the letter, according to Mark
Dillard, his spokesman.
   Alan Ashby, spokesman for California Attorney General John Van
de Kamp, said he didn't know if his boss had received the letter.
But he said the state and federal judiciary have a ``pretty close
working relationship'' on many issues when the jurisdictions
overlap.
</TEXT>
