<1ST_LINE>u p AM-OnToWisconsin     03-29 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-On To Wisconsin,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wisconsin Primary Comes At A Crossroads For Democrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Wisconsin presidential primary comes at a
crossroads for the Democratic candidates, with Michael Dukakis
trying to wrest momentum from Jesse Jackson and long-shots Albert
Gore Jr. and Paul Simon trying to keep their campaigns alive.
   ``The results of Michigan have increased the importance of
Wisconsin,'' Tony Tsakakis, a national campaign aide to Dukakis,
said Tuesday.
   After his loss to Jackson in Saturday's Michigan caucuses, the
Massachusetts governor has stepped up his campaign schedule in
Wisconsin ahead of the state's primary next Tuesday, Tsakakis said.
   Dukakis won an endorsement Tuesday from former Wisconsin Gov.
Patrick Lucey, who said the Wisconsin primary and its 81 Democratic
delegates ``is every bit as significant as it was for another
Massachusetts candidate, John F. Kennedy, in 1960.''
   ``We've always felt every state is a must state,'' Tsakakis
said, noting however that Wisconsin now has added significance for
Dukakis' candidacy.
   Dukakis' third-place finish in Illinois behind Simon and Jackson
and his second-place showing in Michigan have tossed uncertainty
into the Democratic race.
   ``We're looking to Wisconsin to continue our ever-broadening
base of support,'' said Jackson aide Bob Burns. ``If we have
reasonably good back-to-back showings in large industrial states,
it will give us a head of steam going into New York'' on April 19.
   Polls indicate the race is a dead heat between Jackson and
Dukakis.
   Jackson has won compliments from Wisconsin's GOP governor, Tommy
Thompson, and even from Vice President George Bush.
   ``His campaign was diminished in the beginning by a lot of
sophisticated observers, politicians,'' Bush said in a Wisconsin
campaign appearance Monday. ``They never gave him much of the time
of day, and he's doing very, very well taking his case to the
people.''
   Bush should literally walk away with the 47 Republican
delegates. Rival Bob Dole quit the race on Tuesday. The only
remaining GOP opponent, Pat Robertson, has made no effort here.
   Colorado's caucuses on Monday, a day before the Wisconsin
primary, are also shaping up as a Jackson-Dukakis fight.
   ``The worst Jackson will do is finish second. But I think he has
a good chance of winning,'' said Mike Stratton, a Denver Democratic
consultant who ran Gary Hart's 1984 Colorado campaign. Stratton
said Jackson's liberal, anti-establishment message was attractive
to many former Hart supporters.
   In Wisconsin, Simon badly needs a good showing in Wisconsin to
keep his campaign alive. After his win in home state Illinois two
weeks ago, Simon said he was pinning his hopes on Wisconsin.
   Gore also has campaigned heavily in Wisconsin and has flooded
television airwaves with his advertisements.
   Gore's father, former Sen. Albert Gore Sr., said Tuesday his son
needs a ``respectable showing'' in Wisconsin, which he defined as a
``strong third.''
</TEXT>
