<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-JapanConstruction     03-29 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Construction,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Will Allow U.S. Builders To Bid on Japanese Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American builders will be allowed to bid on
Japanese construction projects under a new agreement aimed at
ending a trade dispute that has soured relations between the two
countries.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter told a joint news
conference Tuesday he was pleased that the prolonged, on-and-off
talks had reached ``a fruitful conclusion,'' proving that the two
countries through negotiations are able ``to manage difficult
bilateral trade disputes.''
   Japanese chief negotiator Ochiro Ozawa said he hopes U.S.
construction companies will take full advantage of the agreement
``by taking concrete action to obtain construction licenses in
Japan and actually participating'' in the Japanese construction
boom.
   Ozawa, deputy chief cabinet secretary for Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita, headed the talks as the personal representative of the
prime minister in accordance with Takeshita's agreement with
President Reagan in January that the construction dispute would be
solved amicably, he said.
   ``It is my great pleasure to see a settlement that is amicable,
mutually satisfactory and fruitful,'' Ozawa said.
   Yeutter's deputy, Michael Smith, said the agreement provides for
the Japanese government to facilitate the admittance of American
firms to the bidding on Japanese projects.
   ``It is up to the U.S. firms'' to take advantage of the
agreement, he added.
   Smith said the accord provides for U.S. participation in
construction of the Kansai International Airport and some other
projects on which the two governments had basically agreed last
year.
   Added to it were procedures for bidding on other public works
projects financed by the central government, he said.
   Smith said a third category being opened to U.S. bidders was
local public construction as well as private projects franchised or
approved by the central government.
   These include airport terminals which U.S. builders said they
have been prevented from bidding on despite very competitive
standards.
   The agreement means it will be easier in the future for them to
enter the bidding, Smith said.
   Deputy U.S. Commerce Secretary W. Allen Moore told reporters,
``Our side feels fairly good about the outcome of these talks, but
the real proof of access will be in the future.''
   Moore said Commerce Secretary C. William Verity next week plans
to call heads of major U.S. construction companies to Washington
and ``urge them to take advantage of what we sincerely believe is a
real opportunity.''
   Officials said that besides the multibillion-dollar Kansai
airport project off Osaka the agreement specifically covers entry
of U.S. builders into the bidding for work on such projects as the
Tokyo Bay causeway, the new headquarters of Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone Public Corp., the Tokyo Haneda Airport, coastline
development, a new Hiroshima airport, the Tokyo Bay redevelopment
project, the Akashi Straits bridge, the Ise coastal road south of
Nagoya, the new Port 21 planned for Yokohama and a new Kansai
research city planned for the Osaka-Kobe area.
</TEXT>
