<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nancy-Cancer     03-29 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nancy-Cancer,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Lady Receives `Courage Award' From Cancer Society</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan, who underwent
successful breast cancer surgery last October, received a surprise
``courage award'' from the American Cancer Society on Tuesday for
encouraging other women to seek early detection of the disease.
   ``I can't say this is an award I dreamed of getting when I was
growing up, but if you can help other people deal with this
problem, that makes you feel good,'' she said. ``I hope that's what
has happened.''
   Mrs. Reagan received the award during a Rose Garden ceremony for
60 award winners including actress Jill Ireland, who is the
society's honorary fund-raising chairman.
   Mrs. Reagan and the actress both had a breast removed because of
malignant tumors. The society said the president's wife was honored
for her example of ``strength and courage'' in overcoming breast
surgery and encouraging other women to use mammography, an X-ray
technique for early detection of breast tumors.
   President Reagan told the ``courage award'' winners they had
proved that ``fear was not the end for you but a challenge'' to
triumph over cancer and help others confront the disease.
   ``People need to know that cancer isn't something to run and
hide from, but cancer is a fact that must be faced and dealt
with,'' he said.
   Reagan said he and his wife learned that ``good medical
supervision, early detection and prompt treatment were the keys to
victory over cancer.''
   Reagan underwent surgery in July 13, 1985, for removal of a
small, malignant polyp from his colon. Doctors found another,
larger cancerous polyp that was removed the following day along
with two feet of intestinal tract. They said the cancer had not
spread beyond the tissues that were removed.
</TEXT>
