<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShipwrecksBill     03-29 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shipwrecks Bill,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Rejects Bill Giving States Title to Historic Shipwrecks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House narrowly rejected a bill Tuesday
that would have awarded the states title to abandoned shipwrecks of
historic significance lying within their waters, a proposal
strongly opposed by sport divers and some commercial salvage
operators.
   The House defeated the measure, 263-139, which was five votes
short of the two-thirds majority required for passage. The bill
passed the Senate by voice vote on Dec. 19.
   Opponents complained that the bill was brought to the floor
under parliamentary ground rules usually adopted for abbreviated
debate on non-controversial bills, with no amendments allowed.
   The bill's supporters, led by Rep. Charles E. Bennett, D-Fla.,
were expected to try to return the measure to the House floor under
different rules which would allow opponents to introduce amendments
and would require only a simple majority for passage.
   Rep. Norman D. Shumway, R-Calif., complained that under the
bill, ``there is no legal, binding or enforceable way ... to ensure
that the sport divers' right to dive on these wrecks, even for
purely recreational purposes, will be protected by states.''
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., countered that ``its passage will
go a long way toward preserving these archaeological treasures,''
although he agreed with Shumway that the bill may discourage
private exploration for undiscovered shipwrecks.
   Without the bill, said Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn., dynamiting and
other abuses by some reckless treasure hunters ``would absolutely
guarantee for future generations that these shipwrecks, these
valuable pieces of history, (would) be lost for all time.''
   Vento said guidelines to be published by the National Park
Service under the bill would protect historic shipwrecks in state
waters while permitting orderly access by sport divers, fishing
enthusiasts and others.
   The bill would give states title to the estimated 5 percent to
10 percent of the shipwrecks in state waters that are considered
historically important. All others having no historic interest,
plus all shipwrecks lying beyond 3 miles offshore would be governed
by federal admiralty law.
   Admiralty law awards shipwrecks and cargoes to the finders and
permits salvage operators to claim a major portion of the cargoes
they raise.
   Under the bill, admiralty law would not apply to the small
number of historically significant shipwrecks in state waters, and
Indian tribes would have title to shipwrecks on their lands. The
federal government would retain title to any abandoned wrecks on
public lands.
   Until now, both states and federal admiralty courts have claimed
jurisdiction over abandoned historic shipwrecks in state waters.
   The Submerged Lands Act of 1953 gave the states ownership of all
natural resources and submerged lands up to 3 miles offshore but
did not cover artificial objects such as shipwrecks on those lands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1804EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Shultz-Arabs     03-29 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Arabs,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Meets With Arab League</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz failed on
Tuesday to persuade the Arab League to support his proposal for
Mideast peace talks.
   But a spokesman for the 21-nation group, which also includes the
Palestine Liberation Organziation, said the Reagan administration
seemed to be more sensitive to the Arab viewpoint.
   The 90-minute meeting at the State Department was part of
Shultz's preparation for his trip to the region beginning Sunday
night. He will try to nudge Israel and a mixed delegation of
Jordanians and Palestinian Arabs to open talks May 1.
   Shultz met with Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Al-Shara',
Algerian Ambassador Mohammad Sahnoun, Saudi Arabian Ambassador
Bandar Bin Sultan and other league representatives.
   The league spokesman, Clovis Maksoud, said they disagreed with
Shultz on several issues, including the league's demand for a seat
at the negotiating table for the PLO.
   ``We think the PLO should be represented on an equal footing,''
Maksoud said.
   Shultz met Saturday with two members of the Palestine National
Council, the legislative arm of the PLO. But State Department
spokesman Charles E. Redman said Monday this did not conflict with
the U.S. policy of not dealing with Yasser Arafat's organization.
   Both the United States and Israel consider the PLO a terrorist
group. Shultz has demanded it recognize Israel's right to exist and
disavow terrorism as conditions for U.S. acceptance.
   Maksoud said the league and Shultz also disagreed on the scope
of a peace conference on the Middle East. The Arabs want the United
States, the Soviet Union and the three other permament members of
the U.N. Security Council _ China, Britain and France _ to play an
active role in Arab-Israeli negotiations.
   Shultz would restrict the conference to launching direct
peace-making talks. The Soviet Union and China do not have
diplomatic relations with Israel and provide modern arms to Syria
and Saudi Arabia, respectively.
   ``I cannot say we reached any conclusive agreements,'' Maksoud
said.
   Still, he said ``the secretary of state showed a measure of
openness'' to the league's views. ``We found the United States
perhaps more sensitive to some of our concepts.''
   Shultz has called for an Israeli withdrawal from at least some
of the West Bank and Gaza, which Jordan and Egypt lost in the 1967
Six-Day war. Maksoud said the league wants the Israeli-held
territories evacuated completely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
