<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1810EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WrightAssets     03-29 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright Assets,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Discloses Assets He Held With Business Partner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright has filed amended
financial disclosure statements covering the past seven years to
list assets he held with a Fort Worth business partner, including
stocks, real estate and ``precious and semi-precious stones.''
   Wright filed the disclosures, required by House reporting forms,
after failing to do so since he and developer George A. Mallick and
their wives formed the venture, Mallightco Inc., in 1979. The name
of the business is a combination of the two couples' last names.
   In the past, the Texas Democrat has listed the company on his
disclosure forms with an aggregate value category, but never has
detailed the underlying assets of the venture. In some cases, the
total values given in the new forms conflict with those filed
previously.
   An aide to Wright, Marshall Lynam, said the speaker had been
simply unaware of any requirement for disclosure of the
corporation's assets until his attorneys told him about it last
year while preparing to put the assets in a blind trust.
   The corporation's holdings at that time were detailed in the
blind trust announcement, but the new disclosure filings are the
first public record of the trust's holdings and activities for
previous years.
   On March 18, Wright filed amended reports with the House Clerk's
office detailing those holdings for the years 1980 through 1986.
The speaker's office did not call attention to the filings, and the
existence of the amended forms was disclosed Tuesday by Rep. Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., who has harshly criticized Wright for alleged
ethical shortcomings.
   In each of the seven years, the amended forms show Mallightco's
total value at between $100,001 and $250,000. The forms require
disclosure of values only in broad ranges, so it is impossible to
tell precise amounts.
   In 1980, the first year in which Mallightco appears on Wright's
disclosure statements, Wright's one-half share of the company
included savings accounts and ``fixed assets'' worth less than
$5,000 each; stocks and bonds worth $50,000 to $100,000; and notes
receivable owed by Wright (under $5,000), his wife Betty ($15,001
to $50,000) and Marlene Mallick ($15,001 to $50,000).
   The stocks included Tandy Corporation, Gulf Oil, American Quasar
Petroleum and First National Bank of Weatherford, valued at less
than $5,000 each, and Supron Oil, Delphi Oil and Western Co. of
North America, each valued at $15,001 to $50,000.
   The value of the venture's stock portfolio declined over the
next three years as values dropped and some stocks apparently were
sold. At the same time, Wright's debt to the partnership climbed to
the range of $15,001 to $50,000.
   In 1983, the disclosure form adds ``precious and semi-precious
stones'' worth $15,001 to $50,000 to Wright's share of the assets.
Also added to the assets list is a $5,001 to $15,000 note
receivable from The Mallick Company.
   Wright apparently paid off part of his debt to the business in
1985, and his debt dropped to the range of $5,001 to $15,000.
   In the final year for which an amendment was filed, 1986, the
assets list is enlarged to include ``real estate near Orlando,
Fla.,'' with a value in the range of $50,001 to $100,000.
   The total values for Mallightco were increased in the amended
forms for the years 1983 and 1984, when previous filings had put
the value in the range of $50,001 to $100,000.
   Mallick has figured in news reports about Wright's efforts to
get a federal grant for the renovation of Fort Worth's stockyards,
a project in which Mallick was involved. Wright said he had been
unaware of his associate's involvement when he was seeking the
grant.
   After criticism about those financial dealings and others
mounted last fall, Wright put his assets in a blind trust and said
he had instructed his attorneys to sell his interest in Mallightco.
   Wright's attorney, Charles M. Levy, put the total assets of the
speaker and his wife at the time at $187,317, not counting their
house in McLean, Va., personal retirement funds and 57 acres of
property in Arkansas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0185 </DOCNO>
