<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Robertson-Libel 1stLd-Writethru a0757 03-29 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson-Libel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0757,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McCloskey Considers Suing Robertson for Legal Fees</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th graf pvs, bgng: ``Now we, with
Robertson comment; ADDS 4 grafs on McCloskey's lawyers asking for
court costs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Paul McCloskey Jr. said Tuesday he
is considering suing Pat Robertson to recover $400,000 in legal
fees he incurred when the Republican presidential candidate sued
him for libel.
   McCloskey said his lawyers believe they can be prove that
Robertson made frivolous use of the court system in suing McCloskey
over his statements about Robertson's Korean war record.
   At a National Press Club luncheon, McCloskey repeated the story
he has told for years about being in Marine officer training school
with Robertson and then being shipped to Korea in 1950. McCloskey
contends that while he and others were sent off to combat,
Robertson ducked combat duty using the influence of his father, the
late Sen. A. Willis Robertson, D-Va.
   McCloskey said he and others recall Robertson boasting about how
``I'm going to call my daddy to get me out of this thing.''
   Robertson dropped his legal suit against McCloskey earlier this
month, citing a trial opening set for March 8, the date of the
critical Super Tuesday series of presidential primaries and
caucuses in 20 states. He said the trial would force him to choose
between his campaign and the legal case.
   However, McCloskey contended Tuesday that Robertson dropped the
lawsuit because the evidence supporting the former California
congressman's story was unbeatable.
   He said 21 former Marines were ready to testify on his side and
that letters from Robertson's father supported his case.
   The evidence that Robertson brought suit frivolously is in a
letter written by Robertson to a California politician in 1985 in
which Robertson said that McCloskey believed he was telling the
truth but that his memory was faulty, the ex-congressman said.
   That would negate the veracity of a suit claiming McCloskey
willfully lied about the former television evangelist's record,
McCloskey said.
   ``Now we have enough to sue him for misusing the legal
process,'' he said.
   Robertson, however, insisted he could have won the case.
   ``Every testimony that was to be was already in the record. The
record was closed. The record was complete. In the record, I won,''
Robertson said at a news conference Tuesday in Chesapeake, Va.
``Unfortunately, the judge gave me a Hobson's choice that I could
not abide with.''
   A federal judge dismissed the case on March 7 after Robertston
agreed to pay court costs, but not McCloskey's $400,000 in legal
fees.
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green signed the order dismissing
the case ``with prejudice,'' which means that McCloskey was legally
the victor in the case.
   McCloskey's lawyers, meanwhile, asked Robertson to pay $42,845
in court costs now that the libel suit has been dismissed.
   In a bill of court costs that was made public Tuesday in U.S.
District Court, McCloskey's lawyer George Lehner aksed for, among
other things, $15,794 to cover the cost of taking depositions from
witnesses and $19,458 for photocopying documents.
   Lehner said this figure included $16,000 to make large-size
trial exhibits of 30 to 35 documents.
   Robertson's lawyer, Douglas V. Rigler, who has 11 days to file
any opposition to the bill declined to say if he would make any
objection. ``I would want to discuss that with my client, but just
on first glance it looks extravagant.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
