<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NBC-Rukeyser 2ndLd-Writethru a0726 03-29 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NBC-Rukeyser, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0726,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Spokesman Leaving Network</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf and deletes penultimate graf to CORRECT
reference to retirement option. NBC says Rukeyser not covered by
early retirement plan.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   M.S. ``Bud'' Rukeyser, NBC's executive vice
president for communications, said Tuesday he is leaving the
network to go into business for himself, giving ``advice and
counsel to media companies.''
   Rukeyser, 56, has been at NBC for 30 years, the last 15 as the
network's chief spokesman.
   ``For 15 years, I've been whispering in the ears of four
different chief executive officers. I thought if I was ever going
to do something else, try something on my own, it was going to have
to be now or never,'' Rukeyser said.
   He said NBC President Robert C. Wright reacted to the news by
saying NBC would be Rukeyser's first client.
   Asked if he would be working with his former boss Grant Tinker,
now head of GTG Entertainment, Rukeyser said he had had no such
discussions with Tinker, but added, ``I certainly would hope so.''
   Betty Hudson, now head of publicity for NBC, will become
spokeswoman for the network, Rukeyser said.
</TEXT>
