<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt said Tuesday he
regretted not doing better in the Democratic presidential race but
was determined to work in Congress toward the same goals of his
campaign for the White House.
   Reflecting on his failed White House bid after filing for
re-election to his St. Louis congressional seat, Gephardt said he
knew his campaign was in trouble March 8 when he lost 19 Super
Tuesday states and won only Missouri.
   ``Super Tuesday was the hard night because that was when you
really knew you were on the ropes,'' Gephardt said. But he added
there was a positive side to being out of the race.
   ``There's always a bittersweet in everything in life. We're
disappointed, and yes, we wanted t  The 47-year-old congressman said he
was somewhat relieved he and
his wife ando do this.''
