<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-NIreland     03-29 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-NIreland,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Minister Meets With Northern Ireland Catholics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tom King, Britain's minister
for Northern Ireland, met Tuesday with leaders of the main Roman
Catholic political party in an effort to resolve a political
stalemate in the troubled province.
   King and leaders of the Social Democratic and Labor Party (SDLP)
conferred for about two hours on the political situation and new
surge of sectarian violence in Northern Ireland.
   SDLP leader John Hume said after the meeting, ``We are ready to
sit down and talk with anyone,'' including the Ulster Unionists who
represent the Protestant majority.
   Hume said the negotiations would have to be about ``how we solve
the problem in our society'' rather than who wins power. ``We
believe we should be talking face to face with the Unionists. The
sooner we get there the better,'' he added.
   Hume recently met with Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Fein, the
legal political wing of the outlawed Irish Republican Army. The
Unionists denounced that meeting, saying the SDLP was giving
credibility to terrorists.
   The predominantly Catholic IRA has been waging a violent
campaign since 1969 to unite Northern Ireland, where Protestants
outnumer Catholic 3-2, with the overwhelmingly Catholic Republic of
Ireland.
   Five people have died this month in murderous rampages at two
IRA funerals. The killings climaxed two weeks of rising tension
after British commandos shot dead three unarmed IRA guerrillas in
Gibraltar.
   Hume said his delegation told King of their party's desire to
see all factions work together to create stability in the British
province, where more than 2,600 people have been killed in
sectarian violence since 1969.
   A British government statement said the meeting ``had been
arranged to consider the possiblity of moving to a wider dialogue,
involving the constitutional parties, about the future government
of Northern Ireland.''
   The British Broadcasting Corporation reported King and the party
leaders discussed setting up of some form of power-sharing
administration involving Protestants and Catholics.
   Hume said his talks with Adams were not mentioned at the meeting
with King.
   The Hume-Adams talks had drawn speculation of a possible
temporary cease-fire. But Irish nationalists insisted the IRA had
no intention of halting its campaign and Hume told Independent
Television News he was only interested in discussing a permanent
truce.
</TEXT>
