<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gore 2ndLd-Writethru a0807 03-29 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0807,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Attacks Jackson, Saying He Lacks Experience</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Jackson retort in grafs 3-4</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. said Tuesday that Jesse
Jackson has a ``complete and total lack'' of experience to be
president and criticized what he said was Jackson's ``notion that
there's a moral equivalence between Israel and the PLO.''
   He also said of Jackson, an ordained minister known for his
ringing speeches, ``We're not choosing a preacher; we're choosing a
president.''
   Jackson, campaigning in East Harlem when told of Gore's remarks,
said, ``The senator should not discriminate against someone because
they are a preacher, a priest or a rabbi.''
   ``I assume that he is stimulated by his own status in the
campaign to attack me. I am stimulated to keep hope alive,''
Jackson said.
   Addressing Jewish audiences in New York, Gore also criticized
another Democratic presidential rival, Michael Dukakis, for ``naive
legalism'' in his approach to foreign policy and ``an exaggerated
faith in the United Nations.''
   Gore said he was dismayed by Jackson's ``embrace of'' Palestine
Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat and Cuban leader Fidel
Castro.
   Venturing where other Democratic candidates have feared to
tread, Gore sharply criticized Jackson's foreign policy views and
contrasted his own experience and beliefs with those of the civil
rights activist.
   Other Democratic candidates have shied away from attacks on
Jackson, apparently assuming he won't win the nomination and
wanting to pick up his supporters. But there had been speculation
that that would change after Jackson's victory in last week's
Michigan caucuses solidified his position in the forefront of the
Democratic race.
   Gore credited Jackson with having ``energized millions of
voters'' and having offered ideas on drugs and the economy.
   ``But I part company with him over his opposition to such
mainstays of our national defense as the F-15 and the cruise
missile,'' Gore said. ``I categorically reject his notion that
there's a moral equivalence between Israel and the PLO. And I am
dismayed by his embrace of Arafat and Castro.''
   As for Dukakis, Gore pointed to his disagreement with the
Massachusetts governor over a recent letter signed by 30 Senate
members. Gore said he was asked and declined to sign the letter,
which disagreed with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
opposition to exchanging occupied land for recognition by Arab
states. Dukakis, he noted, said he would have signed the letter.
   Gore, in appearances before a civic group and a coalition of
Jewish organizations, said the Democratic race was far from over
and that Jackson's sudden ascendancy could be as fleeting as Gary
Hart's had been.
   ``When Gary Hart got back into the race and he rocketed to the
top of the polls, a lot of people expressed a sense of panic,''
Gore told reporters at a breakfast of the Association for a Better
New York. ``This race changes from day to day.''
   Later, answering questions after a speech to the Conference of
Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations, Gore said he
hasn't been afraid to criticize Jackson.
   ``I have sharp disagreements with Jesse Jackson,'' the Tennessee
senator said. ``I (have) talked about his complete and total lack
of experience in the national government. He hasn't served a single
day in the national government, or had a single day's experience in
foreign policy.
   ``He has said, `I'm a tree shaker, not a jelly maker.' Well,
some jelly has to be made in the White House, so to speak. If you
need brain surgery, you're going to want to know if the surgeon has
gone to medical school or has had experience practicing that
particular line of work.
   ``We need a president who is prepared to tackle some of the
toughest problems we have ever had in our foreign policy and our
domestic policy, and we need a president who has the experience to
do that job well.''
   Gore was applauded for his criticism of Jackson.
   In his speech to the Jewish group, Gore contrasted his support
of Israel with Jackson's recognition of the Palestine Liberation
Organization. He also said he was ``deeply troubled'' by a report
of Chinese weapons sales to Saudi Arabia and urged steps by the
United States to discourage such trade.
   The Tennessean said the New York primary on April 19 would be a
critical test of his candidacy, but he did not say he had to win it
_ only ``do extremely well.''
   New York will send 255 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention.
</TEXT>
