<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Congress     03-29 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Congress,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reporters Attend Legislature's Discussion Groups For First Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters were allowed into the Chinese
legislature's small group meetings for the first time Tuesday, but
saw a limited amount of the free and lively discussion that has
been ballyhooed by the official news media.
   In the Tibetan Room of the Great Hall of the People, seat of
China's government, 19 delegates from Tibet gathered for what was
supposed to be an example of democracy at work.
   Foreign and Chinese reporters crowded the room in anticipation
of observing delegates engaged in a free exchange of ideas.
   But many soon left as one delegate after another to the National
People's Congress read lengthy, prepared speeches, praising
economic reform and China's open-door policy and calling for unity
and perseverence in the ``great work of socialist construction.''
   Western reporters who attended other provincial discussion
groups said the action was a little livelier as delegates
interrupted each other to add remarks or to disagree.
   The reporters said they were surprised that their presence
seemed not to deter delegates from criticizing the implementation
of policies in their areas.
   But most speakers prefaced critical remarks by saying they
agreed with China's policies of reform and with the report
presented by acting Premier Li Peng at Friday's opening session of
the congress.
   China has given lavish publicity to what it says is the
increasingly democratic nature of its government. For the first
time this year, there were more candidates than seats in elections
for local people's congresses.
   The media portrayed the small group discussions as being the
heart of the democratic exercise. The national TV evening news for
two days has devoted nearly half its domestic news to showing
delegates in animated exchanges.
   But in the Tibetan Room, 20 minutes passed before the first
delegate spoke out of turn, and then it was to support his
colleague's statements.
   At the 2{-hour meeting, delegates were seldom interrupted and no
one expressed disagreement or a differing viewpoint.
   Most delegates seemed disinterested, smoking absently and
staring into space. Through much of the session, the Panchen Lama,
Tibetan Buddhism's second-highest leader and a vice chairman of the
National People's Congress, carried on a private conversation with
his neighbor Ngapoi Ngawang Jigme, chairman of the Tibetan People's
Congress.
   Western reporters said delegates in other groups took a more
active role in discussions. ``There was a certain amount of give
and take,'' one reporter said.
   In the Liaoning province group, a rural school teacher found
fault with government education policy and delegates frequently
interrupted one another to disagree.
   The Tibetan delegates and those representing China's other
minorities used the discussion groups to cite what they said was
the lower standard of living in many minority regions and to say
they wanted more favorable minority policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
