<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0705 03-29 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0705,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Remains Shut Down in Ethnic Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 8 grafs curfew in Sumgait lifted; picks up 7th
`Soviet officials' and edits below to conform and trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers stayed home again Tuesday in a region of
the Caucasus whose Armenian majority is trying to force the Soviet
bureaucracy to reverse a decision it made about local rule 65 years
ago.
   ``My report today will be short,'' Izvestia correspondent P.
Gutiontov wrote from Stepanakert, the largest city of the disputed
Nagorno-Karabakh region. ``City enterprises are at standstill,
people are home.''
   About 75 percent of Nagorno-Karabakh's 157,000 people are ethnic
Armenians, but the Kremlin assigned it to neighboring Azerbaijan in
1923. Most Armenians are Christians. Azeris, the indigenous people
of Azerbaijan, are predominantly Moslem.
   Izvestia, the government newspaper, also gave the first
breakdown of Armenian and Azeri casualties in Feb. 28 rioting in
the city of Sumgait in Azerbaijan, and denied reports that children
were killed.
   A curfew was imposed on Sumgait after the riots but Pravda, the
Communist Party daily, said it was lifted Tuesday because ``life in
the city ... has returned to normal.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told a news
briefing some workers in Stepanakert stayed home and ``certain
enterprises are not functioning or are partially not functioning.''
   Telephone calls to Stepanakert from Moscow did not go through or
were cut off.
   Izvestia also reported Monday that residents of Stepanakert
stayed home. Dissident sources say the strike began last week, but
their reports could not be confirmed.
   Soviet officials, who have announced a costly program to improve
social and economic conditions in Nagorno-Karabakh, will not bend
to pressure from activists to allow Armenia to annex the region,
Gerasimov said.
   ``We believe that problems have to be solved ... on the basis of
realism and without undue emotion,'' Gerasimov said. ``One cannot
solve these complex problems with demonstrations only.''
   ``We cannot solve the problem by mechanically transferring this
region as some Armenian officials want,'' he said. ``The more you
study this problem the more you will see the whole thing is not as
simple as that, as merely saying Nagorno-Karabakh must be part of
Armenia.''
   Gerasimov said the situation had improved but not enough for the
government to allow foreign journalists to travel there.
   Sporadic strikes and protests have been reported in
Nagorno-Karabakh since Feb. 13. The latest labor trouble is said to
have begun last Wednesday.
   Izvestia quoted investigators as confirming the previously
announced death toll of 32 in the Sumgait riot. It said 26 of them
were Armenians and six were from Azerbaijan. Previously, officials
had said the 32 dead were of various nationalities, and that the
rioting was not necessarily an ethnic dispute.
   Armenian activists had claimed the death toll was much higher
and that most of the dead were Armenians.
   ``It has been firmly established with evidence that during the
disorder in Sumgait not one child suffered,'' Izvestia quoted
investigators as saying. ``There were not 400 or 500 deaths, but
exactly 32 people, as said in a published statement by the Soviet
prosecutor. Included in these 32 were 26 Armenians and six
Azerbaijanis.''
   Armenian activists have claimed that small children were thrown
from the windows of maternity hospitals during the riot.
   Izvestia said the strike would not help Stepanakert residents,
and accused activists of lack of concern for the region's welfare.
   Its article Tuesday and a report it published Monday were part
of a new, more detailed look at the Nagorno-Karabakh dispute.
   Soviet media are being encouraged under Communist Party chief
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost to be more open about
social problems, but initial reports on the Nagorno-Karabakh
dispute were slow in coming and lacked detail.
   Sovietskaya Kultura said Tuesday the government's plan for
Nagorno-Karabakh would cost about $640 million.
   ``These millions, which are so necessary now for restructuring,
the country is giving to Karabakh,'' it said in a front-page
article tracing the unrest to poor social and economic conditions.
   Moscow dissident Tamara Grigoryants said police broke up a
demonstration Monday evening in Yerevan, capital of Soviet Armenia,
by more than 50 people demanding freedom for jailed Armenian
activist Paryur Arikyan.
   She said they carried saying, ``We don't believe in
perestroika,'' a reference to Gorbachev's effort to restructure
Soviet society.
</TEXT>
