<DOCNO> AP880329-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 2143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Bombs     03-29 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Bombs,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs Go Off In Three Movie Theaters, Hurt Four People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bombs exploded within
minutes of each other Tuesday in three movie houses, spreading
panic in the downtown cinema district and injuring two federal
policemen and two other people, officials said.
   The officers were trying to deactivate one bomb when it exploded
in the second row of the Normandie Theater on Lavalle Street. Bombs
also hit the nearby Atlas Lavalle and Sarmiento theaters, police
said.
   A bomb was found at a fourth theater but experts defused it.
Three other movie houses received telephoned bomb threats but
searches turned up nothing, police said.
   The explosions caused panic along the street, which is reserved
for pedestrians only, Federal Police Chief Juan Angel Pirker said.
Theaters and businesses emptied. Ticket-takers ran into the street
shouting for ambulances.
   Leaflets scattered at one bombing site read ``O.A.S.-M.R.P.,''
initials of a group that claimed responsibility for most of the 18
bombings and bomb attempts in Argentina this year. It is not known
what the initials stand for.
   Hurt the worst in Tuesday's bombings was a police inspector who
had one hand blown off, officials at Churruca Hospital said. The
other policeman also was badly hurt, they said.
   The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Two movie-goers, a man and a woman, were injured while watching
``The Last Emperor'' at the Atlas Lavalle, police said. The bomb
exploded near the front of the theater, where about 250 people were
seated.
   ``They (the bombers) placed the explosive devices in sites where
they knew there were going to be civilians injured,'' said Pirker.
   Similar O.A.S.-M.R.P. leaflets were scattered earlier this month
at the site of bombings in a downtown apartment building and a
Roman Catholic church. Some reports suggest the bombings stem from
a rightist terrorist group linked to rebel leader Aldo Rico, a
former lieutenant colonel.
   Last year, Rico led a brief Easter Week uprising at three army
camps. The mutineers demanded an end to prosecution of officers
accused of human rights abuses during the 1976-83 military regime.
   Rico and other leaders of that rebellion and a similar one in
January are held at Magdalena military prison, 60 miles south of
Buenos Aires.
   The Supreme Court meanwhile ordered freed four admirals accused
of human rights abuses under the military regime at the Naval
Mechanics School, a notorious detention center in northern Buenos
Aires.
   The court ruled the four were among about 270 officers with the
rank of brigadier general or below who could benefit from last
year's ``due obedience'' law passed by Congress. The law says only
top-ranked officers who ordered human rights crimes now face
prosecution, not those of lower rank who obeyed orders.
   At least 9,000 people vanished during the military regime's
``dirty war'' against suspected leftists, the government says.
   Raul Alfonsin was elected president in 1983, ending the
military's nearly eight-year rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
