<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SelvageExecution 1stLd-Writethru a0819 03-29 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Selvage Execution, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0819,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Stays Execution Of Man Who Killed Deputy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Supreme Court issuing stay,
editing ton conform. Picks up penultimate graf, `On Monday...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted killer scheduled five times
to die for murdering a sheriff's deputy won another last-minute
reprieve Tuesday by a 6-3 vote of the U.S. Supreme Court, which has
heard but not decided a similar case.
   Attorneys for John Henry Selvage filed an appeal with the high
court a day after an appeals court Monday vacated a stay granted by
a federal judge.
   Selvage was sentenced to die for the shooting death of Harris
County Sheriff's Deputy Albert Garza, who was killed July 30, 1979
_ his 48th birthday. Garza was trying to prevent a Houston jewelry
store robbery but had not drawn his gun.
   The appeal covered several issues, but Selvage's strongest case
for a reprieve stemmed from his use of the same argument the
Supreme Court heard March 1 in Texas inmate Donald Gene Franklin's
case, said attorney David Cunningham.
   Franklin's attorney argued that Texas' capital punishment law
keeps jurors from giving full consideration to ``mitigating
circumstances'' suggesting life in prison as more appropriate than
the death penalty.
   The Supreme Court granted a stay of execution to the 37-year-old
Selvage after he was moved from death row at the Ellis I Unit
outside Huntsville to a cell near the death chamber at the Walls
Unit in Huntsville, Texas Department of Corrections spokesman
Charles Brown said.
   By a 6-3 vote, the justices granted the stay pending action by
the court on a formal appeal by Selvage. The dissenters were Chief
Justice William H. Renquist and justices Byron R. White and Sandra
Day O'Conner.
   In February, another Texas inmate, Calvin Williams, won a stay
from the Supreme Court about 90 minutes before he was to be
executed. He used the same argument as in the Franklin case, which
the Supreme Court has not yet decided.
   The scheduling of Selvage's execution on Wednesday, shortly
after midnight, marked the fifth time Selvage faced lethal
injection. Each time he won stays.
   On Monday, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans
vacated the stay granted to Selvage on Friday by U.S. District
Judge Norman Black of Houston.
   The Texas attorney general's office argued that Black should not
have granted a reprieve because the appellate court is
reconsidering the appeal of another death row inmate from Harris
County, Leon Rutherford King, who like Selvage questioned the
selection of jurors during his trial.
</TEXT>
