<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bennett-ChicagoTeachers 1stLd-Writethru a0809 03-29
0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bennett-Chicago Teachers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0809,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Teachers Unions Blocking Efforts for Reform, Bennett Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``Bennett said
...'' and ADDS 2 grafs at end to UPDATE with Vaughn comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers' unions are ``standing in the
hallways and blocking up the doors of reform'' in places like
Chicago with troubled public schools, Secretary of Education
William J. Bennett said Tuesday.
   Bennett, who has said Chicago schools are in an ``education
meltdown,'' toured two public schools there last Wednesday at the
invitation of Jacqueline Vaughn, president of the Chicago Teachers
Union.
   Bennett said afterwards that ``two schools do not a system make.
Facts remain facts, and the evidence suggests very serious
problems.''
   Mrs. Vaughn responded that ``what stalls education reform are
not teachers or teachers' unions, but the cutbacks in funds from
his administration.
   ``Mr. Bennett appears to have a personal vendetta against our
union, because every time we challenge him to produce the so-called
facts he throws around, he insults us,'' she continued.
   In an interview with The Associated Press on Tuesday, Bennett
said teachers' unions have been an impediment to school reform in
some places.
   He said the American Federation of Teachers has been more open
to accountability and choice than its larger rival, the National
Education Association, but he said AFT affiliates like the one in
Chicago ``can be as intransigent and mindless as the NEA.''
   ``We sat there together in a press conference and I said, `Why
don't you admit what everybody knows, which is there are a lot of
teachers ... who have no business in being in classrooms?'''
Bennett said.
   He said Vaughn replied, ``We don't think there's such a thing as
an incompetent teacher. There's only a teacher in need of
assistance or help, a sabbatical or something.''
   Bennett called that ``just utter nonsense or drivel. But that's
the party line.''
   ``I was struck and kind of put off by the party line,'' he said.
``Every time I met with the Chicago Teachers Union, every time they
appeared, they appeared as a committee, and there were five or six
of them, and they would say these things which are obviously the
approved way of speaking. It was kind of scary.''
   ``They're standing in the hallways and blocking up the doors of
reform, as is the bureaucracy there. It's an urban school situation
and the children are suffering,'' he said.
   Bennett added that the ``intransigence of special interests''
such as teacher unions remains the biggest obstacle toward improved
schools.
   Mrs. Vaughn said Bennett's comments show he is ``uninterested in
fair and objective appraisals. Every system has good and bad in it,
but he seems to like to single out ours.''
   She also said the Chicago union had a history of proposing
innovative reforms.
</TEXT>
