<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Nomination     03-29 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Nomination,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Have Delegates Needed To Nominate For A Few More Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although Vice President George Bush is running
virtually alone for the Republican presidential nomination, it will
be at least a couple of weeks before he can gain enough delegates
for a majority at the GOP convention.
   Going into Tuesday's primary in Connecticut, Bush had 788 of the
1,139 delegates needed to win the Republican nomination. Another
250 delegates, most of whom are the remnants of the presidential
campaigns of Sen. Bob Dole and Rep. Jack Kemp, now are counted as
uncommitted.
   If Bush were to pick up all of those delegates, he still would
be 101 short of the number needed to win the nomination.
   The Connecticut primary could give Bush 35 delegates and he
could gain 47 more next week in Wisconsin. Minnesota holds the next
Republican event yielding national convention delegates when the
party there holds its state convention on April 15.
   That convention, where 24 delegates are at stake, would be the
earliest opporunity for Bush to go over the top.
   However, if Bush gains none of the currently uncommitted
delegates, his road to the nomination will be a bit longer.
Assuming he wins every delegate that can be won from now on, Bush
would cross the threshold on May 3, when Ohio, Indiana and the
District of Columbia hold their primaries.
   Bush's only challenger is former television evangelist Pat
Robertson, who has 17 delegates and has all but quit campaigning.
</TEXT>
