<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 2209EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Guatemala-Arias     03-29 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala-Arias,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Costa Rican President Meets with Guatemalan Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Oscar Arias met Tuesday
with three Guatemalan guerrilla leaders and said he would try to
help arrange new negotiations between Guatemala's government and
leftist rebels.
   He told reporters after the meeting that he would intercede with
President Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala to see if negotiations could
be resumed.
   ``It has been proven that peace and democracy can be reached
through dialogue,'' Arias said.
   Cerezo's government and the rebels held their only peace talks
in 27 years of fighting last October in Madrid, Spain.
   Those negotiations were in line with the peace plan signed in
Guatemala in August by the presidents of the five Central American
countries _ Costa Rica, Guatemala, El Salvador, Nicaragua and
Honduras. Arias was the author of the plan and was awarded the 1987
Nobel Peace Prize.
   Arias met for more than an hour with rebel leaders Rodrigo
Asturias, Luis Becker and Hector Nuila. Asturias is the son of
Miguel Angel Asturias, who won the Nobel Prize for Literature in
1971.
   Asturias told reporters the rebels proposed another negotiating
session to be held in Costa Rica next month with Archbishop
Prospero Penados del Barrio, the Roman Catholic prelate of
Guatemala, as mediator.
   Penados del Barrio agreed earlier this year to the guerrillas'
proposal that he serve as mediator, but Cerezo's government has
rebuffed calls for a resumption of the talks.
   ``We place no conditions on these talks, instead we offer an
open agenda to discuss the problems of Guatemala and from there
look for a political solution for our country, with the
participation of all social sectors,'' Asturias told a news
conference.
   He is a commander of the Guatemalan National Revolutionary
Union, a coalition of three guerrilla groups that claim a total of
3,500 combatants.
   The Central American peace plan calls for cease-fires in the
regional conflicts, democratic reforms, amnesties for political
prisoners and a ban on outside military assistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
