<HEAD>Mecham Dealership Sale Announced As Loan To Business Discussed At
Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5-6ths grafs pvs, bgng `Meanwhile, a...'., with 5 grafs
to UPDATE with prosecutor saying dealership sale would have no
immediate effect, defense resting on second count, and to CORRECT
that witness who was admonished was trying to read from earlier
testimony, sted from a law. Picks up 7th graf, `L'Ecuyer
continued...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the Arizona Senate heard testimony
about an allegedly improper loan to Gov. Evan Mecham's car
dealership, the governor's son announced Tuesday that the family
has been forced to sell the business to avert financial ruin.
   ``The confusion and questions this avalanche of negative
publicity has caused ... has forced my family to come to this
decision to sell Mecham Pontiac while the condition of the company
remains solvent and salable,'' Dennis Mecham told a news conference
at the dealership in suburban Glendale.
   Dennis Mecham said sales have decreased dramatically for over a
year as the result of Mecham's political battle and its effect on
consumers. The dealership was sold for about $4 million to a
neighboring auto dealer, he said.
   Dennis Mecham testified last week that the Mecham car dealership
was on sure footing last July when his father arranged an $80,000
loan to the business from a protocol fund. The prosecution has
sought to show that Mecham Pontiac was in desperate straits and
needed the money. The governor denies this.
   Prosecutors said the sale would have no effect on Mecham's
impeachment tral at this time.
   Mecham attorney Jerris Leonard said he was sure Mecham would
reap ``a substantial amount of money'' from the sale although not
as much if he had sold before the political crisis.
   Leonard rested his case late Tuesday on the $80,000 loan count,
and the prosecution said it would call at least one rebuttal
witness before closing its evidence on the charge Wednesday.
   Senators then would decide whether to vote on Mecham's guilt or
innocence of the two charges already considered or move on to
evidence on the third and last count.
   Meanwhile, a defense witness who testified that the $80,000 loan
was ``legal but stupid,'' was threatened with contempt of court.
   The warning to political consultant and lawyer Robert L'Ecuyer
from presiding officer Frank X. Gordon came at Mecham's impeachment
trial as L'Ecuyer tried to blunt a piercing cross-examination by
reading sections of another witness' earlier testimony about which
he had not been questioned.
   L'Ecuyer continued his discourse even after Gordon, the chief
justice of the Arizona Supreme Court, ruled him out of order.
   ``Mr. L'Ecuyer,'' you see this thing in my hand?'' Gordon asked,
pointing his gavel at the witness.
   ``I have been a judge for 26 years, sir. I have never had to rap
this gavel and find a lawyer in contempt but you are tempting me.''
   ``I am properly admonished,'' said L'Ecuyer.
   Earlier, L'Ecuyer was admonished for trying to read a lengthy
statement to defuse a prosecution disclosure that he had been
reprimanded by the Arizona Bar for unethical conduct in 1979 and
voluntarily stopped practicing law for three years.
   He admitted that he improperly borrowed $5,500 from a client's
trust fund which he said was in lieu of his fee.
   ``And your defense was that you were borrowing at a higher rate
of interest than it could otherwise get?'' prosecutor Paul Eckstein
asked to laughter from the gallery.
   Part of Mecham's defense on the charge that he misused the
protocol fund by loaning $80,000 to his Mecham Pontiac dealership
was that he borrowed the money at a higher rate of interest than it
was receiving at the bank.
   Asked by Mecham lawyer Jerris Leonard whether he knew of any law
that made the governor's loan illegal, L'Ecuyer replied: ``I know
of no such law.''
   L'Ecuyer testified, ``I told the governor when I found out that
it was stupid. I thought it was legal but stupid.''
   Mecham contends the protocol fund was not public money because
it was raised by his inaugural committee to pay off campaign debts.
   When state law barred that use, the money was placed in a fund
for such uses as the governor's trips and entertainment to promote
Arizona's image.
   L'Ecuyer, who was hired by Mecham to analyze laws relating to
the public funds issue, said, he concluded that the money raised by
the inaugural committee remained private and in Mecham's control.
   ``The status of the funds is they are purely private funds of a
private unincorporated organization in that association's bank
account,'' he said.
   Eckstein noted that the chairman of Mecham's inaugural
committee, William Long, has said his committee ceased to exist
after its funds were transferred into the protocol fund.
   L'Ecuyer said he felt Long was not qualified to make that
decision, which he said he considered a legal opinion.
   Mecham, who testified earlier this week on the loan charge, also
is accused of thwarting investigation of an alleged death threat on
a grand jury witness and concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   The campaign loan, for which Mecham faces felony charges and a
criminal trial April 21, is scheduled to become the focus of the
impeachment trial later this week.
   On Tuesday, Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Michael Ryan
rejected two defense motions to dismiss charges against Mecham in
the criminal case.
   The defense had claimed Mecham was being selectively prosecuted
and prosecuted under the wrong law. The judge also refused to
separate Mecham's case from that of a co-defendant, his brother
Willard, who was his 1986 campaign treasurer.
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor impeached in six decades, also
faces a recall election May 17.
</TEXT>
