<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WaryWelcome 1stLd-Writethru a0697 03-29 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wary Welcome, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0697,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Demands Restrictions On Alcoholics Meetings; Group Won't Buy
Building</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with board vote against buying building,
add new quotes. No pickup. Name VanIwaarden is cq in 9th graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOLLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that sponsors meetings for
recovering alcoholics voted against buying an abandoned schoolhouse
Tuesday after wary Park Township officials imposed nearly two dozen
restrictions.
   The rules would have prohibited members from gathering outside
on the 4-acre property, which includes soccer and softball fields
and a playground, and would have limited the number of cars on the
premises to 35.
   Those two stipulations were the ones most bothersome to the
Holland Alano Association, said spokesman Donald Hann.
   ``We cannot and we will not turn away people seeking help
because they happen to arrive in the 36th car,'' said Hann, whose
association provides meeting space for 250 to 300 people in six
groups, including Alcoholics Anonymous and Al-Anon.
   Directors of the non-profit organization had planned to buy the
former Ventura School, a vacant four-room building in a rural area
six miles north of Holland, because its lease on a decaying
warehouse expires May 1.
   ``The Holland Alano Association finds it impossible to purchase
the Ventura School because of the onerous and unfair restrictions
placed on the use of the premises by the Parkship Township Planning
Commission,'' the group said in a statement after meeting Tuesday
night.
   The rules, which included a ban on alcoholic beverages and
``mood altering substances,'' were imposed Monday night by the
Ottawa County township's planning commission on a special-use
permit sought by the association.
   Several homeowners had contended the presence of the
organization would destroy the peaceful character of their
neighborhood.
   ``I still don't feel it belongs in a quiet residential area,''
said Carol VanIwaarden. ``It's too bad. They need a place to go and
they are a necessary organization, but they should be in an area
where there's more activity.''
   Hann said the Alano Association must begin searching for a new
building immediately.
   ``We thought an abandoned schoolhouse in the country would be
ideal for us, but I guess we were wrong,'' he said.
</TEXT>
