<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Salutes Dole on Withdrawal, Says He'll Ease Schedule</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 5 grafs, Bush comment on victory in Connecticut,
picks up 6th graf pvs, ``He was xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STEVENS POINT, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, given a
lock on the Republican presidential nomination by the withdrawal of
Sen. Bob Dole and bolstered by a big win in his boyhood home state
of Connecticut, declared: ``The immediate task ahead is unity.''
   ``Now is the time for all of us to join together and unify the
party,'' Bush told a campaign rally after learning of Dole's
announcement. Later, learning of his lopsided win in Connecticut,
he said: ``Let's get together, keep together and get to work.''
   The Kansas senator dropped out of the race earlier in the day in
Washington, pledging to ``do all I can to elect Republican in
November and doing all I can for our nominee, George Bush.''
   ``It's been a hard-fought campaign and I respect the tenacity of
Bob Dole,'' Bush said.
   The vice president said he had called Dole in Washington to
thank him for the ``very generous statement.''
   ``He was a tough competitor and I wanted to congratulate him on
a hard-fought race,'' Bush said.
   Bush also said Dole's departure from the campaign ``changes some
of the dynamics. It removes some of the tension.'' He added, ``I
don't like running against other Republicans.''
   Former television evangelist Pat Robertson has indicated he has
no plans to withdraw from the GOP race, but he has only 17
delegates _ to Bush's nearly 800 _ and is no longer actively
campaigning in most states.
   Dole's withdrawal came as Bush was headed toward overwhelming
victory in Tuesday's GOP primary in Connecticut, and as he
campaigned in Wisconsin where he had been expected to easily
dominate Dole in this state's April 5 primary.
   Bush said he intended to continue cmapaigning in states with key
primaries, mentioning California, Ohio, Pennsylvania and New York.
   Overall, however, ``the schedule will be somewhat lighter and
I'll have more time to flesh out the issue positions,'' Bush said.
   He denied that there had been animosity between him and Dole.
``I don't feel that way, never have.'' he told reporters.
   Although Bush's camp was clearly elated at the development, one
top Bush supporter, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, said that Dole's
exit could hurt Bush's chances in the long run.
   ``I can't see the fact that the vice president doesn't have any
more opposition is that good for him. It's good to have a
primary,'' said Thompson, speaking to reporters on Air Force Two.
``Those individuals who come out of a hotly contested primary can
use it as a springbord to solidify the party,'' Thompson said.
   Bush faced hecklers and students chanting, ``just say no'' as he
addressed an audience at Lawrence University in Appleton, Wis.
``This is nothing. This is small bore stuff. A preview of the
Democratic convention that is about to come,'' Bush told the
college audience.
</TEXT>
