<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0805 03-29 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0805,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista President Says Reagan Should Meet Sandinistas</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New grafs 1-13 UPDATE with zones agreed on, negotiators'
quotes, other details. Picks up 4th graf pvs, Ortega spoke ... with
minor editing to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega urged the
United States on Tuesday to negotiate a return to normal relations
with his leftist Sandinista government.
   Ortega said President Reagan had promised to begin discussions
with Nicaragua if the Sandinistas met with U.S.-supported Contra
rebels. A truce agreement with the Contras was reached last week.
   ``We hope President Reagan keeps his word,'' Ortega declared.
``He has repeatedly said that the day the Sandinistas sit down for
direct negotiations with the Contras, then the United States
government would sit down and negotiate with the Sandinistas.''
   Contra and Sandinista representatives reached general agreement
Tuesday on the size and location of zones where the rebels will
gather during a temporary 60-day cease-fire to begin Friday.
   A communique at the end of two days of talks in the southern
Nicaragua border town of Sapoa said two zones would be in the
northern part of the country, two on the Caribbean coast and one in
the south.
   Aristides Sanchez, head of the rebel delegation, said exact
locations would not be disclosed yet.
   Still to be decided was how the truce will work, said Maj. Gen.
Joaquin Cuadra, chief government delegate.
   He said it would be a main topic when talks resume in Sapoa next
Tuesday.
   The agreement signed last week does not say if the rebels must
lay down their arms during the truce.
   ``What is important in these meetings is that they have
advanced,'' Cuadra said.
   He called the talks ``an important step toward the permanent
cease-fire.'' Cuadra said the cease-fire will take effect Friday as
scheduled, even though the conditions were not agreed upon.
   Sanchez said the talks ``are quite delicate. We are trying to
guarantee the physical and moral security of our combatants.''
   Ortega spoke at a ceremony honoring anti-war activist S. Brian
Willson of San Francisco as a ``hero of peace.'' Willson lost both
legs when a train ran over him during a protest at a U.S. Navy
weapons depot in Concord, Calif., last fall.
   Reagan told the Organization of American States in November that
Secretary of State George P. Shultz was prepared to meet with the
Sandinistas as part of discussions with other Central American
countries ``once serious negotiations'' on a Nicaraguan cease-fire
were under way.
   Direct talks between the United States and Nicaragua have not
been held since 1984.
   On March 23, the Sandinistas and Contras ended three days of
meetings with a signed agreement to work out a permanent cease-fire
in the civil war, which began in 1981, and restore democracy to
Nicaragua.
   Ortega's government refused for years to meet with the Contras,
insisting instead on negotiations with the United States.
   The Nicaraguan president said Tuesday: ``We hope he (Reagan) is
a man of his word and immediately fulfills his word to accept
bilateral conversations to deal with security issues that concern
the United States with respect to Nicaragua and with Nicaragua in
respect to the United States.''
   Those talks should concentrate on normalizing relations, not the
internal policies of Nicaragua, Ortega said, and added: ``We will
not directly discuss the democratic regime in Nicaragua or the
democratic regime in the United States.''
   Washington contends the Sandinistas broke promises made to the
OAS in 1979 in exchange for its support. The Reagan administration
says they promised democracy and delivered Marxism.
   The Sandinistas came to power in a revolution that ousted the
pro-American, rightist regime of the late President Anastasio
Somoza in July 1979. The United States supported the Sandinistas
initially, but in 1981 began financing the Contras.
   In his remarks Tuesday, Ortega urged the U.S. Congress not to
approve any Contra aid that would conflict with last week's
agreement, in which the Contras agreed to accept only humanitarian
assistance from neutral organizations.
   U.S. aid to the rebels expired Feb. 29 and Sandinistas sources
have cited lack of aid as the reason the Contras signed the truce
agreement.
   Rebel spokesmen say continuing the war is unnecessary if the
Sandinistas keep their promises of restoring democratic freedoms.
   For the Sandinistas, the agreement could ease internal pressures
created by dissatisfaction with the war, an unpopular military
draft, food shortages and a shattered economy.
</TEXT>
