<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 2334EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GoetzAppeal     03-29 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Goetz Appeal,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goetz Appeals Conviction and Six-Month Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernhard H. Goetz on Tuesday appealed his
conviction on weapons charges in the 1984 subway shooting of four
teen-agers, saying the instructions to the jurors did not give them
the option of being merciful toward him.
   The appeal, which contained a legal attack on his sentence as
well as his conviction, was filed at the state Supreme Court's
Appellate Division by his lawyer, Barry Slotnick.
   Goetz, 40, is free on $5,000 bail pending appeal. After a widely
publicized trial, the man dubbed the ``subway vigilante'' was
convicted last June on one count of third-degree weapons possession
but acquitted of more serious charges in the December 1984
shootings.
   Goetz said he shot the four young men, all 19, because they were
trying to rob him when they approached and asked for $5. The men
said they were merely panhandling.
   In the appeal, Slotnick argued that the trial judge, Stephen
Crane, illegally violated Goetz's right to have a jury decide his
guilt or innocence on the weapons charge by telling the jurors they
``must'' _ rather than they ``may'' _ convict, if they found Goetz
guilty beyond a reasonable doubt.
   The lawyer argued the judge voided the jury's power to find that
a defendant committed a criminal act but also deserved mercy.
   ``Jury mercy is indeed a well-recognized phenomenon indigenous
to out justice system,'' Slotnick wrote.
   Slotnick also argued against the sentence that Crane imposed
last October: six months in jail and 4{ years' probation, plus
community service, a fine and counseling.
   Paradoxically, Slotnick argued for a longer, one-year jail
sentence, because a definite one-year sentence would make Goetz
eligible for parole in two months. His sentence as it now stands
means he must serve the six months with the possibility of being
jailed again if he violates probation.
   The one-year sentence is required because there is a state law
requiring a mandatory year in jail for a weapons possession
conviction, and the law does not mention splitting the sentence
into part jail time, part probation, the lawyer said.
   The appeals brief also argued that a jail sentence would be
``unduly harsh'' in Goetz's case because of his state of mind.
Slotnick said Goetz continues to suffer ``psychic pain'' because of
the intense publicity the case received.
   Goetz had no comment on the appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
