<DOCNO> AP880329-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 2335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Religion-Politics     03-29 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion-Politics,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clergy And Politicians Tackling Critical Issues Together</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A meeting including Mother Teresa, the Dalai
Lama, Carl Sagan, and officials from the United States, Soviet
Union and United Nations will be a unique collaboration on problems
that threaten human survival, planners said Tuesday.
   Most of the world's forums, national and international, approach
problems only politically, which is just one side of the world's
``two vast structures,'' said the Very Rev. James Parks Morton,
dean of New York's Episcopal Cathedral of St. John the Divine.
   Religious forces ``have been excluded from the debate,'' he
said, adding, ``It seems that the adjudication has got to be both
sides working together.'' Morton is co-chairman of the Global
Conference of Spiritual and Parliamentary Leaders on Human Survival
April 11-15 at Oxford University in England.
   About 100 elected leaders from around the world and about 100
religious leaders of five major faiths are scheduled to
participate. Morton's co-chairman is Sen. Sat Paul Mittal of India.
   Angier Biddle Duke, chairman of the international advisory
committee for the conference, described it as ``first time in
modern history'' for religious-political collaboration on such a
range of critical issues. Duke is a former U.S. ambassador to Spain
and El Salvador.
   In dealing with dangers to life on earth, ``politicians haven't
been able to do it on their own,'' said Rep. James H. Scheuer,
D-N.Y., who plans to attend the conference.
   ``We must merge the ethical and the practicial, the politician
and the priest, the sacred and the secular.''
   He and Sagan, a Cornell University astronomer, ticked off a long
list of threats to the planet, includingtoxic waste, acid rain,
depletion the protective ozone layer allowing in more destructive
ultraviolet rays, the temperature-raising ``greenhouse effect'' of
fossil fuels, AIDS, and nuclear arms.
   Some of the effects ``are so serious as they can be described
only in words of Catholic theology as crimes against creation,''
Sagan said.
   Political leaders have looked at the problems without doing
much, he said, and religions, ``repositories of classical wisdom,''
must become involved to raise consciousness.
   Other participants include Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie, Cardinal Franz Koenig of Austria, Soviet Academy of
Sciences vice president Evguenij Velikhov, U.N. Secretary General
Javier Perez de Cuellar and MacArthur Foundation Chairman Thornton
Bradshaw.
   Financing for the conference, expected to be about $1 million,
has come from individual religious donors, said the conference
executive coordinator, Akio Matsumura of New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 2335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Panama-Journalists     03-29 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Journalists,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Injured Journalists Return To United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two network journalists beaten at their hotel in
Panama by plainclothes police flew here Tuesday, and one said he
wouldn't believe his experience if he had seen it in a movie.
   ``I've never seen anything like it in any other country,
grabbing people like that,'' said Ignacio Medrano, a CBS cameraman
who limped in a stoop as he was helped off a chartered private jet
at Miami International Airport. ``If we'd seen it in a movie, I
would've said they were lying.''
   Medrano was admitted to Mount Sinai Medical Center in
satisfactory condition Tuesday night with broken ribs, a hospital
spokeswoman said. Before being taken there by ambulance, he said
X-rays in Panama had indicated no broken bones, but his ribs had
turned purple and his legs ached from a beating with a nightstick.
   At least 10 foreign journalists and 20 opposition leaders were
arrested Monday when troops raided the Marriott Hotel in Panama
City. Most were released by Tuesday.
   Medrano said he came to the aid of NBC cameraman Domingo Rex of
Mexico City, who said he suffered a broken nose when punched by a
plainclothes security agent. The officer broke his wrist throwing
the punch, Rex said.
   ``He tried to grab my camera and we started fighting. He got
real mad,'' said Rex, whose nose was covered with gauze and tape.
``At this point, Ignacio Medrano tried to save me and they beat him
too.''
   ``It is really scary because they are up. They are looking for
the press. They were after them,'' Rex said, adding he paid a $365
fine to be released from jail, returned to his hotel and left the
country.
   ``At one point, I was really scared a lot, scared about leaving
this place alive,'' said Rex, who had been in Panama for 17 days.
``I decided it was time to go.''
   People in the hotel, which serves as the headquarters of
Panama's opposition and the foreign press, were attacked by agents
with guns pointing in the air, Medrano said.
   ``They just threw me in the van with the rest of the people,''
he said. ``They kicked me all the way to the van.''
   Alfredo Gudino, an NBC sound technician, also returned on the
chartered plane. He was detained but not injured.
   The Overseas Press Club, a New York-based organization of
jounalists, sent a letter of protest Tuesday to Panama's ruler,
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
