<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-ANC     03-29 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-ANC,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ANC Accuses South Africa of Poison-Sugar Plot</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-ANC Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver Tambo, head of the African
National Congress, accused South Africa Tuesday of a plot to kill
ANC representatives in Mozambique with poison sugar.
   Tambo told a news conference in Harare that South Africa had
arranged for a third country to deliver the poisoned sugar,
apparently as a gift, to ANC officials in Maputo, the capital of
neighboring Mozambique.
   He did not name the third country allegedly involved but said
the sugar ``was brought into Mozambique by a country in which the
Pretoria regime operates freely.''
   Tambo did not say if any ANC officials had been poisoned.
   The ANC is the main guerrilla group fighting South Africa's
policy of apartheid, or legalized racial discrimination by the
white minority.
   Tambo is in Harare for a 3-day conference of West European
parliamentarians on apartheid. The conference, attended by
delegates from 14 countries, ends Wednesday.
   ``As long as it (apartheid) remains there will be no peace in
the region,'' Tambo said. ``This message was clear yesterday when
for no reason at all South Africa attacked Botswana.''
   He referred to the South African military attack Monday on a
house on the outskirts of Gaborone, the capital of Botswana, in
which four people were killed.
   South African confirmed the raid and said the four people killed
were terrorists. Botswana said one man and three woman were killed.
It said the man was a ``South African refugee,'' two of the women
were Botswanans and the third woman had not been identified.
   In an attack Tuesday in Paris, Dulcie September, the ANC
representative for France, was shot to death in her office. French
news reports said Mrs. September, 45, was shot in the face while
entering the office at about 9 .m.
   ANC officials claimed South Africa was behind the killing, but
South Africa denied it and suggested the attack was related to
strife within the outlawed organization.
   Tambo, based in the Zambian capital of Lusaka, told the news
conference: ``We must step up our attacks on the police, the army
and other personnel associated with the institution'' of apartheid.
   ``We will strike against its economic infrastructure and do much
more intensively what we have been doing all the time.''
   By South African law and custom, apartheid establishes a
segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
