<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 2350EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tibet-PanchenLama     03-29 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet-Panchen Lama,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panchen Lama Says Four Killed in Last Tibetan Riot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panchen Lama, highest Tibetan religious
leader in the Chinese government, said Tuesday four people were
killed in a pro-independence protest earlier this month in Lhasa,
capital of the remote Himalayan region.
   Official Chinese reports have said the only fatality was a
Chinese policeman.
   The Panchen Lama told Western reporters a monk and two civilians
also were killed. He spoke after meeting with a small group of
Tibetan delegates to the National People's Congress in Beijing.
   Western travelers in Lhasa have said Tibetans were reporting 21
civilians and 3 policemen killed, and many arrests. The Panchen
Lama would not comment on the reports of arrests.
   Buddhist monks and lay people in Lhasa held a violent
anti-Chinese protest March 5 at the close of the annual Moinlam
Qenmo, or great prayer festival, that lasted more than 12 hours.
   Reports from witnesses said they attacked police with stones,
knives and steel bars, seriously injuring 30 officers, and set
bonfires throughout the city.
   Buddhist priests seeking independence for Tibet led a protest
last October in which at least 14 people were killed and a police
station was destroyed.
   The Panchen Lama, Tibetan Buddhism's second-highest leader after
the Dalai Lama, continued his campaign Tuesday for a lenient policy
toward Tibet.
   The Dalai Lama, a god-king to Tibetan Buddhists, went into exile
in India after an unsuccessful rebellion in 1959. China took over
Tibet in 1950.
   Under the Panchen Lama's proposals, efforts would continue to
heal wounds caused by China's radical Cultural Revolution of
1966-76. Religious belief was outlawed and many Buddhist temples
and monasteries were destroyed during that period.
   ``How we implement our religious policies will have a great
affect on the thinking of the masses in Tibet, where nearly
everyone is religious,'' said the Panchen Lama, a loyal supporter
of China's communist government.
   He also addressed militants advocating Tibetan independence:
``Some separatists outside China want to split Tibet from the
motherland,'' he said. ``They'd better stop their dirty tricks.
Tibetan affairs are Chinese domestic affairs, and they are family
affairs.''
</TEXT>
