musk oxen given to China by the United States in 1972, a Georgia
widow began a one-person campaign to replace them.
   Next month, Helen Miller travels to Beijing for a ceremony
marking the success of her efforts and the arrival of two new
animals.
   Mrs. Miller said she learned that just as pandas Ling-Ling and
Hsing-Hsing _gifts from China _ had become popular at the National
Zoo in Washington, millions of Chinese children visited the Beijing
Zoo to see the oxen.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How to shop in a city with horrendous traffic,
boutiques that close for two hours at lunch and sales clerks who
are imperious, or just plain rude? Maribeth Clemente knows, and
helps fellow Americans for a fee.
   With an investment of less than $9,000, she started a business
called Chic Promenade last June to counsel visitors and shepherd
them through the array of stores and shops in the ``city of light.''
   Ms. Clemente, a 26-year-old native of Troy, N.Y., takes up to
four people on a tour of six to 12 boutiques in an average day,
with a midafternoon break in a cozy tea room.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of American experts on the supernatural
found that the only thing special about Chinese reputed to have
magic powers was their ability to disappear when asked to prove
their claims.
   ``They failed all the tests,'' said Dr. Paul Kurtz, chairman of
the Committee for the Scientific Investigation of Claims of the
Paranormal and professor of philosophy at State University of New
York at Buffalo.
   Kurtz said in particular his six-member delegation had seen no
scientific evidence to back up claims from masters of the Chinese
martial art of ``qigong'' that they can cure tumors and help
cripples walk through energy emanating from their fingers.
</TEXT>
