<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1159EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV FortunatePilgrim Adv30 03-29 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV, Fortunate Pilgrim, Adv 30,0812</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, March 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NBC's Unfortunate `Fortunate Pilgrim'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Fortunate Pilgrim,'' based on novelist
Mario Puzo's sweeping saga of an Italian immigrant family in search
of the American dream, is, unfortunately, a tedious, wooden
melodrama in its adaptation for TV.
   NBC will air the two-part, five-hour miniseries on Sunday and
Monday, April 3-4.
   Sophia Loren, whose husband, Carlo Ponti, produced ``The
Fortunate Pilgrim,'' stars as plucky matriarch Lucia Corbo, whose
first husband is killed in a factory explosion, and whose second
husband, played by Edward James Olmos of ``Miami Vice,'' succumbs
to insanity. Her children, meanwhile, get tuberculosis, arrested
and the neighbor's wife pregnant.
   Hal Holbrook arrives in Part 2 as a Scotch-French doctor who
romances Lucia. John Turturro, who made his mark playing malevolent
types in such films as ``To Live and Die in L.A.'' and ``Five
Corners,'' is eldest son Larry.
   The movie, a period piece set in the 1920s and '30s, was shot
against an almost sepia-toned backdrop by director Stuart Cooper,
who did the miniseries ``The Long Hot Summer.'' This one was filmed
on location in Yugoslavia, but the sets look more like a studio
backlot. Also, inexplicably, the dialogue sounds dubbed much of the
time.
   Cooper's rudimentary direction is matched only by the pedestrian
script. Drama needs conflict. The fluffy ``I'll Take Manhattan,''
even with broadly drawn characters and plotlines, worked because it
at least had structure.
   ``The Fortunate Pilgrim'' is a muddle. The central conflict
seems to be Lucia's dream for a home in the country and success for
her children running up against her offspring's constant moral
lapses, illnesses and scrapes with neighbors and the law. An early
symbol of evil is a laughably Snidely Whiplash-like landlord.
   The result is a meandering plotline composed of a series of
unconnected events, most of which have no buildup or ramifications.
   In John McGreevey's script, as well, character development
consists of simplistic dialogue, although it doesn't help us
connect with them to switch actors every hour or two as the
children age.
   A sample scene: Early in Part 2, son Vinnie goes to comfort
sister-in-law Luisa who is weeping after being insulted by her
husband, Larry. We have seen these two only in passing, so this is
supposed to establish their characters.
   ``Too bad you didn't get to finish high school. I probably won't
either,'' Vinnie says at one point.
   ``You should. Vinnie, you're so smart,'' says Luisa.
   ``Mom depends on me. That's the way it is,'' he replies.
   ``You're too kind,'' she says. ``You're always doing things for
other people.''
   The miniseries does have the dubious honor of stifling a fine
cast.
   Loren is becoming something of a TV movie regular _ she was in
``Courage'' last season and before that ``Aurora'' and ``Sophia
Loren: Her Own Story'' _ and she is still a charismatic screen
presence.
   Olmos, who plays enigmatic Martin Castillo on ``Vice,'' does a
good job with smoldering Frank Corbo, convincing us by strength of
performance that Lucia could indeed fall in love with this troubled
man.
   Annabella Sciorra makes an impressive television debut as
Octavia, Lucia's headstrong eldest daughter. Also notable is
Yugoslavian actress Mirjana Karanovic who plays Clara, a married
woman who becomes pregnant by Larry.
   All these immigrants are yearning to breathe free.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CHRISTIE IN FIRST MINI _ Noted film actress Julie Christie is
set to make her television debut in a miniseries to air next season
on CBS with the working title ``Dadah is Death'' (``dadah'' being
the Malaysian word for drugs). Christie plays an Australian woman
who launches an international campaign to save her son (Hugo
Weaving) and a friend (John Polson) from the death penalty after
they are caught smuggling drugs in Malaysia. The director is Jerry
London, whose credits include ``Shogun'' and ``Ellis Island.'' .. .
   OPRAH TOP BROADCASTER _ The International Radio & Television
Society has named talk-show host Oprah Winfrey as its Broadcaster
of the Year. Winfrey, whose ``Oprah Winfrey Show'' is the
third-highest-rated syndicated show, will receive the award at the
IRTS annual meeting in New York on June 1. ...
   `WISEGUY' GUY GETS AWARD _ Jonathan Banks, who plays agent Frank
McPike on CBS' ``Wiseguy,'' is getting an award from real-life
police officers back home. Officers from Baltimore and Washington,
D.C., (Banks grew up in Silver Spring, Md.) will honor the actor at
a May 6 banquet for his realistic portrayal of a law enforcement
officer. CBS quotes Banks as saying two childhood friends who grew
up to be police officers served as models for his role as the
acerbic Organized Crime Bureau agent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, March 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
