<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APArts:Organ-Pipedreams Adv03   03-29 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Organ-Pipedreams, Adv 03,0421</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Pipedreams' on American Public Radio _ The Organ's Showcase</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Organs-Orphans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A staggering amount of organ music is
heard in the United States, most of it live on Sunday mornings
though perhaps little of it worth hearing again.
   It's that smaller segment that Michael Barone pursues for
``Pipedreams,'' a 90-minute weekly showcase for organs and
organists on American Public Radio.
   The inspiration came in 1980 when Barone found himself running
the only tape recorder at an American Guild of Organists convention
in the Twin Cities.
   ``Gosh, this was incredible music, some good commissioned works,
some young artists who were just outstanding,'' said Barone, who
had a local organ program at the time.
   He put together 14 programs to offer nationally in 1982.
   ``I did it only because there seemed like a lot of good stuff
available, not only here that year but around the country, and
there didn't seem to be anyone else doing anything with it,'' he
said.
   That's still true.
   ``I'm getting the sense that though 128 stations do carry
`Pipedreams,' they may carry no other pipe organ music during the
week,'' Barone said.
   There is one other nationally distributed organ program _
half-hour performances by John Obetz from the headquarters of the
Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints in
Independence, Mo., which is carried by about 100 stations.
   ``Pipedreams'' ranges far more widely.
   Recently, for example, programs have featured the flamboyant
French organist Jean Guillou, the dedication of new organ at Iowa
State University, an anthology of American music and a variety of
Bach organ works played at several universities.
   One of Barone's favorite shows included what was apparently a
premiere performance _ 139 years after the composer's death _ of a
work by Felix Mendelssohn.
   In addition to the AGO conventions, Barone's digital tape
equipment has captured gatherings of the Organ Historical Society,
recital competitions of young organists and even the occasional
theater organ or choir. He also uses records, compact discs and
tapes submitted ``on spec.''
   There is so much, he said, that he is just now scheduling some
of the material from the AGO's 1986 convention.
   ``I'm really here to beat the drum for the pipe organ,'' which,
Barone feels, ``is almost an invisible creature in the world of
music.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 3</NOTE>
