<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0586</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says Americans won't
accept trade restrictions and retaliation against foreign
manufacturers and threatened to veto legislation aimed at curbing
U.S. trade deficits.
   Reagan, promoting his free-trade stance even in the face of
mounting U.S. trade imbalances, warned Monday that a trade bill
under consideration in Congress could weaken international trading
systems and ``require the president to start trade wars.''
   ``I'll veto if I must,'' Reagan told Reynolds Metals Co. workers
on the eve of a crucial House-Senate conference committee meeting
on the bill.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal fund that insures deposits in
commercial banks could suffer a loss in 1988 for the first time in
its 54-year history, Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman L.
William Seidman says.
   Seidman said Monday a loss to the insurance fund, if any, would
depend on how much the FDIC spends to resolve the problems of First
RepublicBank of Dallas, which earlier this month received a $1
billion infusion of government aid. He said it is too soon to say
with certainty what the cost of restoring First RepublicBank to
health will be.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A merger between photofinishing giants
Eastman Kodak Co. and Colorcraft Corp. is aimed at making the firms
more competitive rather than forcing other companies out of the
industry, a federal appeals court says.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Monday reversed a
preliminary injunction granted to Phototron Corp. that blocked the
Kodak-Colorcraft merger.
   A lower court ruled Feb. 22 that Phototron had standing to
challenge the merger, and that the merger between Kodak and
Colorcraft could substantially reduce competition in the wholesale
photofinishing market.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. said it was prepared
to up its bid for Lucky Stores Inc. to more than $1.9 billion in an
effort to create the nation's largest grocery store chain.
   In a letter to the board of the Dublin, Calif.-based company,
American Stores chairman L.S. Skaggs said his company was ready to
offer $50 per share if a ``mutually acceptable agreement'' could be
worked out with Lucky Stores.
   Earlier Monday, American launched a cash tender offer for Lucky
at $45 per share, or a total of $1.74 billion. That offer expires
at midnight April 22.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. says its
board will move Wednesday to end the bidding war for the retailer
by acting on the final competing purchase offers of R.H. Macy & Co.
Inc. and Campeau Corp.
   A committee of Federated's outside directors met Monday to
determine bidding procedures and would inform Macy and Campeau of
those guidelines, Federated said in a statement.
   Macy and Campeau have each offered more than $6 billion to buy
Federated, the nation's fifth-largest retailer. Macy's bid has the
approval of Federated management.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corning Glass Works and SmithKline Beckman
Corp. have each raised their bids for International Clinical
Laboratories, a chain of clinical-testing laboratories that is
based in Tennessee.
   Corning moved first, increasing its tender offer Monday to about
$360 million, or $35 a share for ICL's 10 million-plus outstanding
shares and common stock equivalents.
   But SmithKline, based in Philadelphia, soon followed by raising
its offer to $37 a share, which it said would amount to about $400
million. It had previously offered $32 a share.
</TEXT>
