<DOCNO> AP880329-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 0103EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers Bjt   03-29 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers, Bjt,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Takeover Legislation Promised In Koppers Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. John Heinz promised to push for a
law that would make a hostile takeover of Koppers Co. unpalatable
for British investor Brian Beazer, and Sen. Arlen Specter asked the
attorney general to enter the case personally.
   Heinz, a Pittsburgh Republican, charged at a news conference
Monday that if a $1.7 billion tender offer from BNS Inc. succeeds,
Beazer will gain a monopoly in various markets for aggregates, road
building materials that include sand and pebbles added to concrete
to make cement.
   ``A strangle hold on the existing aggregates business'' is
financially attractive because ``environmental laws are such at the
state and local level that you cannot easily open ... a new source
of aggregate,'' he said.
   Specter, a Philadelphia Republican, said he is concerned whether
an initial Jusice Department review satisfied the Hart-Scott-Rodino
Act, which sets guidelines for corporate takeovers. He asked
Attorney General Edwin Meese to personally review the Koppers case
and to respond to the request by Thursday.
   Heinz withheld details of his proposed legislation.
   ``To reveal our strategy might very well be to jeopardize its
success,'' he said.
   The proposal will be offered this week or after the Easter break
as an amendment to pending legislation, Heinz said.
   ``I'm not in the business of making hollow promises, and I do
not make idle threats,'' Heinz said. ``I have drafted and am
prepared to introduce and press legislation to make the takeover of
Koppers extremely unpalatable.
   ``The corporate raiders will be and should be as surprised by
this legislation as Koppers was by this raid,'' he said.
   ``We are not corporate raiders,'' Beazer declared in a full-page
advertisement Monday in Pittsburgh's newspapers. ``Our goal is not
to make a quick buck. Rather, we are in the process of creating a
vital, dynamic worldwide organization.''
   Beazer said that after he acquired the Atlanta homebuilder Cohn
Communities and the Dallas construction materials company
Gifford-Hill in 1985 and 1986 respectively, ``each of those
companies has grown and prospered under our ownership.''
   BNS Inc., a takeover company formed by Beazer and Shearon Lehman
Hutton Inc., bid $60 cash per share for Koppers stock under a
tender offer open until April 7. A federal court in California
temporarily has blocked the acquisition over antitrust concerns.
   Koppers management says it may sell all or part of the company
or pay cash to shareholders to keep the company out of Beazer's
hands.
   Heinz said taxpayers will spend more for public roads if the
takeover succeeds.
   ``The two of them combined in what are essentially local market
areas would, if the sale went through, amount to a de facto local
monopoly on very costly road-building materials,'' he said.
   The senator, Allegheny County Commission Chairman Thomas
Foerster and others at the news conference said the takeover
jeopardizes the approximately 1,100 Pittsburgh-area jobs in
Koppers' chemicals businesses. Beazer has said he would sell
chemicals and related businesses, although it is not clear that all
those jobs would be eliminated.
   Opponents also worry about the $232 million that Koppers
contributes to the area economy.
   Heinz joined city, county and state officials who have lambasted
Shearson for going a step beyond traditional takeover financing and
becoming an equity partner in the takeover company, BNS.
   ``I am appalled by the involvement of Shearson,'' he said.
``Shearson stands to gain tens of millions of dollars in fees
simply for shuffling some paper around.''
   Shearson officials have said their ownership in BNS is merely a
temporary method of helping finance the takeover.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
