<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CourtingConsumers Bjt   03-29 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Courting Consumers, Bjt,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Corporations Pay More Attention To Consumers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies faced with increased competition and
more demanding consumers are learning to stress customer
satisfaction over bottom-line profit strategy, the president of a
Boston-based corporate research and training firm says.
   ``Right now, there are a lot of people playing around in each
others' back yard,'' said Richard C. Whiteley, president of The
Forum Corporation. ``With more options, the consumer is in a better
position to be selective.''
   A Forum Corporation survey of nearly 5,700 employees and
consumers released Monday said top-level management should rely on
``front-line'' employees and the public to gauge service quality
and corporate image.
   ``Companies are learning that they need the consumer and that
service has got to improve or they can lose their business
overnight if they're not careful,'' said Whiteley, who estimates
consumer complaints have doubled since 1980.
   The survey, which included more than 3,200 employees at 14 large
companies in the United States and Canada, revealed a trend toward
stressing consumer satisfaction.
   ``There's a certain arrogance in companies on a downward
spiral,'' Whiteley said. ``They think they know what their
customers need more than their customers do.''
   The survey indicated that empathy and responsiveness among
so-called front-line workers who deal directly with the public
leads to customer loyalty and new business.
   But the report noted that managers constantly must seek comments
and advice from front-line employees and customers, who have the
best sense of how the company is perceived in the marketplace.
   The report also notes that the attitudes of front-line workers
is heavily influenced by upper management.
   ``Consumer focus ... has come to be regarded as a complex notion
that involves the entire organization, and not just something that
is the responsibility of people who are sometimes the lowest-paid,
least-trained and least-motivated employees in the company,'' the
report said.
   Whiteley cited toll-free information numbers, consumer
questionnaires and maintaining executives' connection with the
public as methods successfully used by companies seeking to enhance
image and customer satisfaction.
   ``You now hear, `Thank you for calling AT&T' when you call,'' he
said. ``That wasn't the case years ago.''
   Whiteley predicted more U.S. companies will foster better
consumer policies as foreign and domestic competition grows.
   Forty percent of the 2,374 consumers interviewed late last year
in the two-month survey said poor service prompted them to pull
away their business. An additional 30 percent cited ``other
reasons'' for switching, including some service-related problems,
according to the report.
   But between 60 percent and 73 percent of consumer respondents
rated service quality with the companies ``excellent,'' according
to the report.
   ``We found their standards are just lower,'' said Thomas
Atkinson, who supervised the survey. ``There's the impression that
service just is not very good in America anymore.''
   The number of employees who said that ``satisfying customers''
was among their companies' top three priorities ranged from 8.7
percent to 63 percent.
   In addition, ``attracting new customers'' was considered a
priority almost twice as often as ``keeping customers'' among the
corporate sponsors of the survey, which included manufacterers,
high-techonology firms and service-oriented companies.
   The names of the companies were not released.
   ``In general, priorities having to do with customers or better
financial performance were seen as key by the employees ... while
objectives such as emphasizing quality, finding new products and
finding new markets ranked lower,'' the report said
   A final version of the findings is scheduled to be released in
September, Atkinson said.
</TEXT>
