<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down Slightly Against Yen; Stocks Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar recovered from an early plunge in Tokyo
trading today following moderate intervention by Japan's central
bank, while stock prices posted substantial gains for the second
consecutive day.
   Traders said the U.S. currency's recovery during the day's
trading was due mostly to technical factors, including dollar
purchases by participants with dollar-short positions.
   ``Sentiments toward the dollar are still bearish,'' said a
trader who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``The Bank of Japan's
intervention wasn't large, and much of the dollar buying was by
people who recently sold dollars and were beginning to feel
nervous.''
   The U.S. currency now has fallen 2.78 yen in Tokyo over the past
four trading days.
   The Bank of Japan began buying dollars shortly after the U.S.
currency opened at 123.88 yen, down 0.55 yen from Monday's close of
124.43 yen. Traders estimated the central bank's purchases at about
$100 million. As usual, the bank did not comment officially on its
market activity.
   The dollar then reversed direction, and ended the day's trading
at 124.37 yen, down 0.06 yen from its close on Monday. It ranged
between 123.87 yen and 124.85 yen.
   Traders said the dollar also was boosted by fiscal year-end
buying by some corporations. The Japanese fiscal year ends Thursday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-stock Nikkei Average gained
330.38 points, or 1.29 percent, closing at 25,953.09. On Monday,
the index rose 301.99 points.
   Nobuo Ishikawa of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage,
said market participants were relieved to see the dollar
stabilizing during today's trading.
</TEXT>
