<1ST_LINE>u f PM-FloridaTourism Bjt   03-29 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida Tourism, Bjt,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Visitors Boost South Florida Tourism, While Spring Break
A
Bust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign visitors are boosting attendance at South
Florida tourist attractions from the Everglades to Ocean World,
while the number of vacationing collegians has plummeted to an
all-time low this decade.
   ``You have a truly unique place,'' said Klaus Mueller, who was
bird watching on the Anhinga Trail in the Everglades, the greatest
expanse of sawgrass in the world. ``Everybody in the world knows
about the Everglades.''
   Attendance at Everglades National Park is up 43 percent over
last season with 306,202 visitors in January and February compared
to 213,384 during the same time last year, spokesman Pat Tolle said
Monday.
   ``It's like a language school outside my office,'' said park
superintendent Michael Finley. ``I'm hearing French, German,
Japanese everywhere.''
   Jerome Scherr, president of Miami's Parrot Jungle, where
attendance was up 16 percent, said the attraction is ``something
different than they've got back home in Europe and Japan ... We're
subtropical _ palm trees and glamour.''
   The weak dollar against foreign currencies and the slick image
created by the television series ``Miami Vice'' are attracting many
of the foreign visitors to South Florida.
   Nigel and Rosy Collins visited Miami's Seaquarium during their
week-long trip to South Florida and Orlando from London. The couple
expected their vacation to cost half of what they would have paid
two years ago because of the weak dollar.
   ``Everything is so warm, so clean, so new, so cheap,'' Collins
said, as his wife chimed in, ``And you've got Don Johnson.''
   But the traditional spring break market in Fort Lauderdale is
going bust instead of boom this year, according to Broward County
tourism officials.
   A turnout of 200,000 college students had been expected,
matching last year's dismal turnout. However, the numbers now being
forecast range from 110,000 to 180,000, and the hotels and bars
that report solid business say it's due to the influx of European
tourists.
   Although South Florida tourist officials are uncertain of the
number of foreign tourists, international traffic at Miami
International Airport was up 9 percent to 786,951 passengers in
January compared to the same month last year.
   Finley expects Europeans to generate 80 percent of the business
at Flamingo Lodge at the southern tip of the Everglades in the
mosquito-swarming months of July and August.
   At Lion Country Safari, the Palm Beach County big-game preserve
and amusement park, a 25 percent boost in attendance over last year
was reported, said Lion Country marketing director Brian Osborne.
   Ocean World, where Fort Lauderdale visitors can pet dolphins and
watch sharks feed, reports 18 percent more visitors so far this
season. The attraction does not release specific admission figures,
said general manager George Boucher.
   Businesses that thrive on tourism expect the boom to continue as
long as the dollar is low.
   ``The English should be here big in April,'' Parrot Jungle's
Scherr said. South Americans will then travel north to avoid
winter, and Europeans will keep coming.
</TEXT>
