<1ST_LINE>u f PM-KodakMerger Bjt   03-29 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak Merger, Bjt,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Proceeds With Colorcraft Merger Following Court Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. will seek to complete
its merger with fellow photofinishing giant Colorcraft Corp. now
that an appeals court has ruled the two were not trying to force
other companies out of the industry, a Kodak spokesman said.
   ``We're absolutely gratified,'' spokesman Henry Kaska said
Monday evening after hearing of the federal court ruling. ``It does
mean that we will be proceeding with that merger.''
   However, Kaska said it was still too early to tell when the
merger would actually take place.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Monday reversed a
preliminary injunction granted to Phototron Corp. that blocked the
Kodak-Colorcraft merger. The court ruled the merger was aimed at
making the firms more competitive and was not an attempt to put
others out of business.
   A lower court ruled Feb. 22 that Phototron had standing to
challenge the merger, and that the combination of Kodak and
Colorcraft could substantially reduce competition in the wholesale
photofinishing market.
   Kaska said the merger would not result in a monopoly of the
wholesale photofinishing business and retail operations known as
mini labs, but he could not immediately provide figures on how much
of the market the companies would control.
   Kodak operates 50 photofinishing labs throughout the United
States, while Colorcraft operates 41 labs. Phototron operates nine
labs in the southern and western United States.
   Kodak and Colorcraft decided to merge to make their
photofinishing operations more competitive. Phototron sued, asking
a district court in Texas to block the merger.
   The lower court issued a preliminary injunction, saying it was
appropriate given the threat of loss and damages Phototron could
suffer.
   However, the three-judge panel of the 5th Circuit said the
district court had ``erred in handing down a preliminary injunction
without first finding Phototron had demonstrated a substantial
likelihood of having suffered an antitrust injury.''
   The appeals court went on to say that under a previous ruling by
the U.S Supreme Court, a competitor can obtain a permanent
injunction against a merger only if it can prove the transaction
would violate antitrust laws.
   ``Under Cargill, a competitor ... has standing to challenge the
merger if an allegation and proof of predatory pricing is made,''
the appeals court said.
   The panel said Phototron has not offered substantial proof that
the merger would fall under the predatory pricing guidelines, and
therefore has not demonstrated the ``substantial likelihood'' it
would prevail in a trial.
   Phototron argued to the district court that Kodak and Colorcraft
had undercut the price Phototron offers retailers, and therefore
claimed that its two competitors could be operating unprofitably
and violating the predatory pricing prohibition.
   The appeals court said Phototron must prove Kodak and Colorcraft
are offering services below their own cost in order to satisfy the
``substantial likelihood'' requirement for a preliminary injunction.
   Kaska said the legal obstacles have only delayed the merger
several weeks. ``Obviously any delay would mean a loss of revenue,
but the delay was not that long,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
