<HEAD>Share Prices Hold Most Gains Through Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the London stock exchange moved higher
Tuesday, aided by modest technical strength, bargain-hunting and
pre-holiday apathy.
   At midday, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100
selected stocks was up 11.6 points, or about 0.6 percent, at
1,758.1.
   Gains in Tokyo overnight, where the Nikkei stock average rose
330.58 points, and in New York, where the Dow Jones Industrial
Average was up 0.82 point on Monday, were less a support for the
market than a sign that markets were likely to take a temporary
breather until after the Easter weekend.
   Traders depicted the London advance as a technical bounce
following six consecutive days of declines.
   But they said the rally lacks momentum and predicted shares
would not advance much further barring an unexpected move by Wall
Street.
   One broker reckoned that after the four-day Easter holiday,
institutions could make a big showing in the market.
   ``They've got plenty of liquidity,'' he said. ``We could see
quite a good rise out of that after the holiday.''
