<1ST_LINE>r f BC-CBOT-BondIndex     03-29 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-CBOT-Bond Index,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBOT Suspends Trading in Corporate Bond Index</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade has suspended trading
in its 5-month-old CBOT Corporate Bond Index futures contract
because of a lack of sustained volume.
   The contract, based on an index of bonds issued by 100 U.S.
corporations, was launched Oct. 28, nine days after the stock
market collapse.
   The launch date, sandwiched between the market's plunge and the
traditionally low-volume winter holiday season, may have been one
reason for the contract's disappointing performance, William
Murschel, an exchange spokesman, said Monday.
   The Commodities Futures Trading Commission approved the
exchange's request to place the contract in ``dormant status,''
meaning the exchange could relaunch it at some future date,
Murschel said.
   The Commodity Exchange in New York also trades a corporate bond
index futures contract. That contract, based on Moody's
Investment-Grade Corporate Bond Index, was launched one day after
the CBOT contract and also has failed to attract much interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
