<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ResortsInternational     03-29 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Resorts International,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Griffin Amends Suit Against Trump in Resorts Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investment firm of entertainment
entrepreneur Merv Griffin amended a lawsuit against developer
Donald Trump to allege the controlling shareholder in Resorts
International Inc. schemed to depress the value of the casino
operator's shares.
   Griffin and Trump are making rival bids to take over the
hotel-casino concern, which has operations in New Jersey and the
Bahamas.
   The amended suit, filed by the Griffin Co. in federal district
court in Manhattan, ``adds to our claims concerning Mr. Trump's
scheme to depress the value of Resorts shares and lock up his
control in order to acquire Resorts on the cheap.''
   Trump has denied the charges.
   The suit added no new allegations. Rather it sought to buttress
its existing claims with new evidence.
   The suit, which seeks $500 million in damages, contends Trump
misled other shareholders, the public and government agencies by
withholding material information regarding the value of Resorts.
   Trump controls nearly all of Resorts' 572,000 Class B shares,
which has 100 votes per share, giving him 88 percent of the
company's voting power.
   He is offering $22 per share for the remainder of the Class B
stock and the company's 5.7 million shares of Class A common stock,
which has one vote per share.
   Griffin initially offered $35 per share, or $225 million, for
all of the company's stock. He has since boosted that offer to $295
million, allowing Resorts' directors to decide how to apportion it
between Class A and Class B stockholders.
</TEXT>
