<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed to lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean prices were pressured by profit-taking after Monday's
sharp gains. But the outlook for soybeans remains bullish, said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``I think today may be the pause that refreshes,'' Lespinasse
said. ``Hopefully we'll resume the uptrend tomorrow.''
   Contracts for May and July delivery of corn advanced slightly in
reaction to news that the government had granted one-year
extensions on certain corn loans from 1984, 1985 and 1986.
   The extensions mean farmers can delay decisions about marketing
hundreds of millions of bushels of corn that could have gone onto
the market this year, Lespinasse said.
   Other corn contracts posted early losses; wheat was fractionally
lower.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $2.99\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
lower to { cent higher with May at $2.11 a bushel; oats were \ cent
to 1 cent lower with May at $1.65} a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents
to 4} cents lower with May at $6.52 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent lower with April at 75.22
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .28 cent lower with
March at 82.85 cents a pound; hogs were .23 cent lower to .22 cent
higher with April at 45.82 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.30 cent lower to .03 cent higher with May at 56.15 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Monday while pork futures
retreated.
