<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Lawson     03-29 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Lawson,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Denies Policy Split with Lawson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told Parliament
that there isn't any policy split between herself and Chancellor of
the Exchequer Nigel Lawson, the Treasury's top official.
   ``Both Mr. Lawson and I put downward pressure on inflation as
topmost priority. Both of us think interest rate stability can be
very useful to industry,'' Mrs. Thatcher said Tuesday in response
to a question in the House of Commons.
   It was the first time that the Conservative prime minister had
publicly denied a split with Lawson, according to observers.
   After the government's recent decision to allow the British
pound to rise above 3.00 West German marks, there were press
reports that Lawson had been against allowing the pound to rise but
had been overruled by Mrs. Thatcher. The prime minister was more
concerned about the inflationary impact of any effort to stem the
pound's rise on world currency markets, the reports said.
   A stronger pound could hurt British exports and company profits.
   Earlier Tuesday, Lawson told a gathering of the Association of
American Correspondents in London that ``the whole (government)
policy is to ensure to continue to have downward pressure on
inflation.''
   ``There is no sign whatsoever of resurgence of inflation,''
Lawson said. Britain's annual inflation rate is currently 3.3
percent.
   He said Britain's intervention in the foreign-exchange markets
wasn't inflationary.
   Lawson also said he is ``perfectly satisfied'' with the current
trading level of the pound against the mark.
   The British currency was quoted at around 3.1050 marks on
Tuesday afternoon in London.
   But Lawson added that ``you shouldn't draw the conclusion from
that that there is a target'' for the pound against the mark.
   Lawson's lack of concern about the current inflation rate might
mean there is room for British interest rates to fall further. The
banks' base lending rate currently stands at 8.5 percent.
   The reported policy split between Mrs. Thatcher and Lawson
fueled speculation in recent weeks that he would resign his post,
which he has held since 1983.
   ``I haven't formed myself a view of how long I will remain
chancellor,'' Lawson said. ``I am not worn out and you can see my
hair hasn't turned gray.'' But he also said that no one holds a job
forever, and added, ``I have been chancellor longer than most.''
   Lawson also said he wasn't particularly concerned about
Britain's widening trade deficit, ``provided there is no resurgence
of inflation.''
   The Treasury is forecasting a doubling this year of the
current-account deficit to 4 billion pounds, or about $7 billion.
But the government on Friday reported a worse-than-expected
February deficit of 1.56 billion pounds, or around $2.9 billion,
which made the financial markets nervous.
</TEXT>
