<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AmericanStores 1stLd-Writethru   03-29 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-American Stores, 1st Ld-Writethru,0876</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Stores Launches Tender Offer For Lucky Stores</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds new 7th graf to update lack of comment today from
American, Lucky; picks up 7th graf pvs: The combination ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Stores Co. says it is prepared to
increase its offer for Lucky Stores Inc. to more than $1.9 billion
if a friendly merger of the two grocery store chains can be worked
out.
   American also filed a lawsuit in Delaware state court to enjoin
Lucky officers from defending against American's unsolicited tender
offer, indicating American may be bracing for a takeover battle.
   In a letter to the board of the Dublin, Calif.-based Lucky late
Monday, American chairman L.S. Skaggs said his company was ready to
offer $50 per share if a ``mutually acceptable agreement'' could be
worked out with Lucky.
   Earlier in the day, American launched a cash tender offer for
Lucky at $45 per share, or a total of $1.74 billion. That offer
expires at midnight April 22.
   ``We made clear our willingness to negotiate concerning all
aspects of our offer, including the price,'' said Skaggs in his
letter to Lucky.
   So far Lucky's representatives have declined to negotiate.
   American Stores Vice President Michael Holt today said the
company would have no comment on either the lawsuit or increased
stock cash offer. Lucky officials were not available to discuss the
matter this morning.
   The combination of American, the nation's third-largest grocery
retailer with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $15 billion, and
Lucky, the sixth-largest with 480 stores and sales of $7 billion,
could produce the biggest grocery retailer in the country, analysts
say.
   Lucky officials were not immediately available for comment on
the latest developments, which were announced in a press release
after the close of stock trading.
   Lucky shares advanced 87{ cents to close at $48.62{, while
American shares lost $1.75 to finish at $54.87{ on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   Before American revealed the contents of its letter, Lucky
spokeswoman Lissa Perlman said company officials had been reviewing
the offer with financial and legal advisers since last week.
   Ms. Perlman said Lucky was advising stockholders not to take any
action on the American offer until Lucky's board of directors has a
chance to study the bid and make its recommendation.
   American's lawsuit, filed Friday in Wilmington, Del., alleges
Lucky and its executives have breached their fiduciary duties by
``following a course of conduct directed towards entrenching
themselves in control of Lucky Stores.''
   In the lawsuit, American said its representatives met with
Lucky's March 21 to announce the tender offer. American claimed the
$45 offered for each Lucky common share is about 40 percent over
the market price of the company's stock immediately before the
offer.
   American said its representatives advised Lucky Chairman John M.
Lillie that their company preferred to negotiate a friendly
acquisition and requested a prompt meeting to do so.
   But ``within hours of this meeting, Lucky ... set out on a
course of conduct which would deny the Lucky stockholders a premium
price for their shares and would preserve the position of the
company's management and the board,'' the suit alleged.
   The lawsuit further claimed that Lucky initially threatened to
take injunctive action against American and urged the Utah company
to delay its tender share filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, not to publicize the offer and to consider certain
arrangements between the two companies leading to abandonment of
the offer.
   Based on those attempts, the lawsuit said, American believes
Lucky's management ``will continue to refuse to negotiate seriously
... and will employ an array of defensive measures to prevent the
acquisition of the company in violation of the defendant's
fiduciary obligation and duties to its stockholders.''
   In a March 26 letter telling Lillie of the takeover plans,
Skaggs praised Lucky's management and marketing strategies and
invited Lucky executives to stay on if the deal is completed.
   Lucky's headquarters would remain in Dublin, Skaggs said.
   The bid for Lucky came 16 months after takeover specialist Asher
Edelman dropped his hostile effort to acquire the company. In
return, Lucky agreed to pay his $2.8 million in legal bills.
   Lucky kept Edelman at bay partially by selling off its
non-grocery divisions and adopting anti-takeover measures.
   After the text of the letter was released last week, Lucky
officials had no comment on the American's tender offer except to
say company bylaws contain a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
provision limiting the voting power of any shareholder who acquires
more than 10 percent of Lucky's stock.
   In 1984, American spent $1.1 billion to take over Jewel
Companies Inc., a Chicago-based grocery, drug and convenience store
chain.
   That acquisition expanded American's operations from just over
1,000 retail outlets to its present 1,700. The company has three
divisions _ Skaggs, which operates supermarkets in the western
United States; American Superstores, which runs outlets in the
Midwest and East, and Osco Drug Stores, which has stores nationwide.
   The company operates stores under the names Acme, Jewel, Star,
Buttrey, Skaggs, Skaggs Alpha Beta, and Osco Drug.
</TEXT>
