<1ST_LINE>r f BC-IBPPlant     03-29 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-IBP Plant,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBP Announces Plans To Build In Waterloo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SPEER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATERLOO, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of IBP inc. said they will build
a $40 million state-of-the-art hog processing plant at Waterloo.
   ``We truly believe that Waterloo will be good for IBP and IBP
will be good for Waterloo,'' IBP Chairman Robert L. Peterson told a
Tuesday news conference.
   The pork and beef processing giant said in November 1986 it was
considering building a plant in northeastern Iowa. The company
focused attention on a Delaware County site south of Manchester
before opposition arose to IBP plans to dump treated sewage into
tributaries of the Maquoketa River.
   IBP will begin construction on the 365,000-square-foot plant
this spring at a 130-acre site in northeastern Waterloo. Completion
of the plant is expected to take a year and a half.
   When at full capacity, the plant will employ 1,200 to 1,500
people with an annual plyroll of more than $20 million and will
process 4 million hogs a year. IBP currently has four pork plants _
at Storm Lake, Louisa County and Council Bluffs in Iowa and
Madison, Neb. _ and employs 20,000 people at 15 plants in eight
states.
</TEXT>
