<DOCNO> AP880329-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1253EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco     03-29 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kinnear Says Icahn Won't Take Over Texaco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate raider Carl C. Icahn will
not take over Texaco Inc., which is coming out of bankruptcy,
company President James Kinnear predicted today.
   Icahn, who owns 14.8 percent of Texaco and is the oil giant's
largest single shareholder, has threatened to run a panel of five
candidates for the Texaco's 14-member board at the next annual
meeting unless Texaco offers to put itself up for sale.
   But Kinnear, whose seat on the board of directors also is
threatened for takeover, said Texaco management will do its best to
keep Icahn out. Texaco officials have repeatedly said the company
is not for sale.
   ``He recently said in public that he has no intention of being
on Texaco's board or wanting to take control of the company, but
the next day he said he might run a proxy slate,'' Kinnear told a
news conference. ``I just don't know what his intentions are. My
prediction is that he will not take over this company.''
   Kinnear did not elaborate on the strategy for keeping Icahn from
making a run at the company.
   Icahn is not the only takeover artist known to be interested in
Texaco. Oilman T. Boone Pickens has said he is seeking federal
regulatory permission to acquire 15 percent or more of Texaco's
stock, as has Getty Petroleum Co., a large independent distributor
that was born of Texaco's takeover of Getty Oil.
   Kinnear talked to reporters after a speech to the National
Petroleum Refiners Association.
   He said the company would become leaner and stronger by selling
some assets to clear up its huge debt.
   Last week, a U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge approved a
reorganization plan that will enable Texaco to emerge from Chapter
11 protection early next month.
   Texaco filed for that protection last April to avoid having to
post an $11 billion security bond while appealing a $10.3 billion
judgment against the company held by Houston-based Pennzoil Co.
   The judgment stemmed from a November 1985 ruling by a Houston
jury that Texaco had improperly interfered with a Pennzoil bid to
acquire part of Getty Oil Co., then bought Getty itself.
   Texaco's reorganization plan calls for payment of $5.6 billion,
with $3 billion going to Pennzoil to drop the judgment and the rest
going to creditors.
   Texaco expects to sell $3 billion in assets to finance the
program, Kinnear said.
   In his speech, Kinnear said that the petrochemical industry
could profit if it remains lean.
   ``U.S. chemical manufacturers must adjust their thinking to a
slower-growth economy and to competition from new players,'' he
said. ``Revamping facilities, stretching existing units, or making
strategic acquisitions will generally yield far greater returns
than investing in new, grassroots plants with the expectation of
growing to full capacity in two or three years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0256 </DOCNO>
