<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed to Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mixed Tuesday on
the Chicago Board of Trade. Soybeans posted losses, most wheat
contracts made slight gains and corn finished nearly unchanged.
   The decline in soybean prices was mostly due to profit-taking
after Monday's sharp advances, analysts said.
   Wheat prices also did an about-face as traders bought contracts
after a fairly steep drop on Monday, said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Contracts for May and July delivery of corn advanced marginally
in reaction to news that the government had granted one-year
extensions on certain corn loans taken out in 1984, 1985 and 1986.
   The extensions mean farmers can delay decisions about marketing
hundreds of millions of bushels of corn that might otherwise have
gone onto the market this year, Lespinasse said.
   Trading volume is expected to drop on Wednesday and Thursday
ahead of two eagerly awaited Agriculture Department reports _ the
annual spring planting intentions report and the quarterly grain
stocks report _ due out after Thursday's close.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $3.01 a bushel; corn was 1 cent
lower to } cent higher with May at $2.11\ a bushel; oats were 1\
cents lower to 3 cents higher with May at $1.63} a bushel; soybeans
were 3 cents to 6 cents lower with May at $6.51 a bushel.
