<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Stevens Bjt   03-29 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stevens, Bjt,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Odyssey Ups Bid for Stevens; West Point-Pepperell Expected To
Counter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be updated with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Odyssey Partners sweetened its tender offer for
J.P. Stevens & Co. to $1.14 billion Tuesday, but analysts predicted
further bidding in the battle for the textile giant.
   West Point-Pepperell Inc., which has made a $1.1 billion bid for
Stevens, is expected to compete fiercely for the crown jewels _
three state-of-the-art factories and licenses for hot designer
labels that lure consumers around the world to Stevens' quality
sheets and towels.
   Odyssey, a New York investment firm, said it would pay $64 for
each of Stevens' 17.8 million outstanding shares, up from the
$61.50-a-share tender offer Stevens' management accepted earlier
this month.
   In ``consideration'' for the sweetened offer, Stevens' board
agreed to pay Odyssey up to $8 million if it is acquired by a third
party for more than $64 a share.
   Pepperell made its $62.50-a-share bid after Stevens forged its
agreement with Odyssey. Pepperell had said it might be willing to
increase its offer to $64 a share if Stevens agreed to a friendly
deal.
   A spokesman at Pepperell's headquarters in West Point, Ga., had
no comment after Odyssey announced its increased offer.
   But asked in an interview last week whether Pepperell would
consider raising its offer above the conditional $64 a share,
Chairman Joseph L. Lanier said, ``I wouldn't preclude it.''
   In afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Stevens
rose 37{ cents to $64.87{a share.
   Odyssey partner Brian D. Young noted in a statement that while
Odyssey's bid matched what Pepperell said it was prepared to pay
under friendly terms, Odyssey's tender offer expires on April 11 _
10 days ahead of Pepperell's offer.
   Investors are likely to find the earlier expiration attractive
unless Pepperell raises its bid.
   ``West Point-Pepperell wants Stevens very badly,'' said George
Zimmerman, director of research at Gruntal & Co.
   The acquisition would quickly further Pepperell in its goal of
becoming a major international marketer of branded products.
   ``Not only does Stevens have some of the best brand names in the
business, but they have bigger international operations,
particularly in Canada and Japan,'' said Josephine Esquivel, a
textile analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Pepperell's brands include Arrow, Martex, Lady Pepperell and
Burberrys. Among Stevens' arsenal of top designer names are Ralph
Lauren, Laura Ashley, Pierre Cardin, Vanderbilt, Perry Ellis and
Givenchy.
   In addition to the attraction of the licenses to use those
names, Pepperell is keen on acquiring Stevens' sheet plant in
Clemson, S.C., and two top towel plants in Wagram, N.C., analysts
agreed.
   How much higher Pepperell can go is another matter. Esquivel
noted that the company's debt-to-equity ratio, currently at 28
percent, would jump to 63 percent based on a $64-a-share tender
offer.
   Odyssey's Young has charged that a Pepperell merger with Stevens
would violate antitrust laws.
   Pepperell has sought to soothe potential antitrust concerns with
a plan that includes the sale of half of Stevens' bath lines and 20
percent of its sheet lines for about $170 million. Pepperell signed
a definitive agreement for the sale with NTC Group, parent of Bibb
Co., a textile manufacturer.
   But Young said the proposed sale to Bibb ``does not cure the
antitrust problems.'' He said Odyssey will ``strongly present our
views to the appropriate governmental authorities and will continue
to oppose any amended proposal if we believe that the antitrust
problems have not been solved.''
   Bidding for Stevens began after it received a leveraged buyout
offer several weeks ago from a group led by its own senior
management, including Chairman Whitney Stevens _ a fifth-generation
member of the family that founded the company in 1813.
   The management group initially offered $43 a share and later
sweetened its bid to $55 a share in cash and securities. In a
leveraged buyout, a company is acquired largely with borrowed money
repaid with a target company's profits or the sale of assets.
</TEXT>
