<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HomeSales Bjt   03-29 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales, Bjt,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales Of New Homes Soar 20.3 Percent In February</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY40</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New home sales, which had fallen for three
months following the October collapse of the stock market, soared
20.3 percent in February, the fastest increase in almost two years,
the government said Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department said that new single-family homes were
sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 628,000 units. It was
the first monthly increase since a 1.4 percent rise in October, but
it still left sales 14.9 percent below where they were a year ago.
   Sales had fallen 10.3 percent in January, 6.8 percent in
December and 4.2 percent in November, declines which analysts had
blamed on high mortgage rates and consumer jitters following the
record plunge in stock prices that occurred on Oct. 19.
   Because housing is often the first sector to weaken at the start
of a new recession, the string of declines had raised concerns
about whether another downturn was imminent.
   But analysts said the strong February rebound erased those
worries and indicated housing should strengthen further in coming
months.
   ``The February numbers spell relief and optimism,'' said David
Seiders, chief economist for the National Association of Home
Builders. ``We feel we are back on track where we should be.''
   James Christian, chief economist of the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions, said the February housing performance ``is another
piece of evidence that we are shrugging off the aftershocks from
the stock market crash.''
   Christian predicted that new home sales would rise further
during the spring sales season and help boost sales for the entire
year to around 650,000. While that would be down from the 671,000
new homes sold in 1987, it would still be considered a strong sales
year for the industry.
   Analysts said it is unlikely that mortgage rates will fall much
further. Fixed-rate mortgages currently stand at 9.99 percent, down
from a high last year of 11.58 percent just before the stock market
decline.
   Economists predicted rates would begin rising later this spring
and would probably top 11 percent by the end of the year.
   ``The economy is too strong and the dollar is too weak to
believe that interest rates will go down from here,'' said Martin
Regalia, chief economist of the National Council of Savings
Institutions.
   The big February sales rebound was the largest monthly increase
since a 21 percent gain in March 1986. It was accompanied by a
sharp decline in prices, reflecting in part the re-entry into the
market of first-time buyers, who normally buy less expensive homes.
   The median, or mid-point, price of new homes was $110,800 in
February, down 6.1 percent from the record January price of
$118,000.
   The average price of a new home fell 4.6 percent to $139,000
last month, down from $145,700 in January.
   The big jump in sales was propelled by a 42.9 percent surge in
sales in the South. This region of the country, which accounts for
40 percent of all new homes sold, is still 9.6 percent below the
year-earlier sales pace.
   Sales were up 29.3 percent in the Northeast and 18.2 percent in
the Midwest. The West was the only region of the country to suffer
a sales decline in February, a drop of 7.1 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880329-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1940EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Sundstrand     03-29 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sundstrand,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sundstrand Anticipates Filing of Criminal Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sundstrand Corp. has agreed in principle
to plead guilty to filing false statements with the government and
to pay $12.5 million in connection with alleged overcharges on
defense contracts, according to published reports Tuesday.
   Sundstrand Corp., an aerospace contractor, previously revealed
in a financial filing with the government that it would face
criminal charges resulting from two federal grand jury
investigations into alleged overcharges.
   The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday that Sundstrand had
agreed to the guilty plea and payment in one of those
investigations and that Justice Department officials hoped to gain
an agreement in the second, larger investigation.
   Sundstrand reported a year ago that the government was seeking
repayment of $13.5 million plus interest and $102.9 million plus
interest in two separate disputes over contract pricing.
   The Journal said the two cases, taken together, could result in
the largest total payment ever for alleged military contracting
fraud.
   Claude Bernam, a spokesman for Sundstrand, referred inquiries
about the investigations to the company's lawyers, who were not
available for comment.
   In a report filed recently with the federal Securities and
Exchange Commission, Sundstrand acknowledged the ``government has
advised that it intends to charge the company with criminal
violations'' in both Rockford and Seattle.
   Sundstrand is based in Rockford and operates a subsidiary in
Redmond, Wash., near Seattle, that is part of its Advanced
Technology Group.
   Sundstrand, which makes flight data equipment, engine start-up
systems and other electronic equipment for commercial and military
aircraft, said in its SEC filing that it was ``in the process of
entering a settlement in one or possibly both actions.''
   Such settlements, the company also noted in the filing, ``could
result in the imposition of materially adverse fines and
penalties.''
   In the Seattle case, the newspaper said Sundstrand failed to
disclose improper accounting procedures during negotiations with
the Defense Department. In the Rockford case, Sundstrand allegedly
charged private commercial costs to Air Force and Navy contracts
and subcontracts.
   Sundstrand's military sales last year amounted to $574 million
and accounted for more than half of all sales in the aerospace
segment.
   In 1986, Sundstrand put aside $61.5 million to cover settlement
and legal expenses relating to the government disputes. As a
result, 1986 profits were down 39 percent.
   One analyst said Sundstrand has the market presence to weather a
temporary halt in government business.
   ``The question is, is this jeopardizing on a long-term basis,''
said Steven Colbert, at Prudential-Bache Securities. ``The answer
right now is, `I don't think so.' Right now they have very strong
market share.''

</TEXT>
