<HEAD>Stock Prices Surge Ahead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market pulled out of its slump today,
bolstered by a more stable dollar, lower interest rates and some
positive news about the economy.
   Analysts, however, were uncertain whether today's broad-based
rally represented a bullish trend or just a much-needed respite
following three sessions of losses.
   ``In light of what we've seen in the equity market today ...
much of this action is almost like an oversold bounce,'' said
Dennis E. Jarrett, a technical analyst for Kidder, Peabody & Co.
``It's too early to say whether it's sustainable.''
   The dollar's improvement in foreign exchange trading helped
stock prices by easing inflation fears and pushing interest rates
lower, analysts said. A sharp decline in the U.S. currency had been
largely responsible for driving down the stock market on Monday.
   ``The fact that the dollar has stabilized and is no longer going
into a free-fall, that's a psychological prop,'' said Larry
Wachtel, market strategist and first vice president at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The dollar was aided today by central bank intervention and
remarks from Japan's foreign minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, who called
for major industrialized nations to follow last year's currency
stabilization accord.
   Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.,
said a report showing the Index of Leading Indicators _ the
government's chief economic forecsting gauge _ gained 0.9 percent
in February also lent support to stock prices. The index had fallen
in three of the past four months.
   ``Maybe those fears that the economy is going to run out of
steam either this year or next year are unfounded,'' Johnson said.
</TEXT>
