<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WorkerNotice     03-29 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Worker Notice,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Rejects Union-Sought Bill To Warn Workers Of Job Hazards</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Tuesday effectively rejected
legislation to warn up to 300,000 workers a year they risk cancer
and other diseases from occupational exposure to toxic chemicals.
   On a 52-42 vote, Senate sponsors of the House-passed measured
failed by 18 of the 60 votes necessary on a fourth attempt to break
off a conservative Republican filibuster over the past eight days
against the union-sought bill.
   The bill's author, Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, conceded
defeat but said the issue will not go away.
   ``In this one I've lost,'' he said. ``But as long as workers are
kept in the dark about occupational hazards, we will continue to
try to bring them light.'
   The defeat was the first for the AFL-CIO on the Senate floor
since helping return the 100-member body to Democratic control. But
15 of the Senate's 54 Democrats, most of them from the South, ended
up siding with the leader of the filibuster, Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah.
   ``We've had 50 years of these type of give-away programs that
don't work,'' said Hatch, who claimed the measure could cost
businesses up to $7 billion if exposed workers began filing and
winning liability suits against their current and former employers.
   The bill was aimed at addressing what the National Institute of
Occupational Safety and Health estimates is one in every four
Americans who has been exposed to carcinogens at work, most of them
unaware of it.
   Metzenbaum, the measure's chief sponsor, repeatedly cited
American Cancer Society estimates that warnings to at-risk workers
could have saved 250,000 lives over the next 10 years.
   ``Tens of thousands of American workers are dying each year from
occupational diseases and could prevent many of these deaths ... by
telling them the truth that they are at risk,'' he said.
   Metzenbaum accused the National Association of Manufacturers and
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce of waging an ``orchestrated campaign
of misrepresentation, innuendo and hype'' in citing the potential
costs to employers.
   Alexander Trowbridge, the NAM's president, called Metzenbaum's
charge ``irresponsible,'' saying worker health is a prime concern
of every responsible manager in the country.
   ``We care a great deal about preventing disease from happening
rather than discovering it after the fact, which is what his
proposal would bring about,'' Trowbridge said.
   The bill would have established a panel of seven scientific
experts to identify the most hazardous substances in workplaces and
the groups of employees most susceptible to disabling diseases
because of exposure to them.
   NIOSH would have been required to individually notify between
100,000 and 300,000 of those at-risk workers every year at an
annual cost of $25 million. Employers then would be required to
finance medical monitoring program for them at a cost of up to $250
each annually.
   If a physician recommended transferring a monitored employee to
less hazardous work, he or she would have had to be paid the same
level of wages and benefits to them in the new job. If no other job
is available, the employee would have been entitled to full wages
for up to a year after leaving work.
   In addition to unions, the bill was supported by public health
and environmental groups, the chemical and electronic industries
and several giant companies, most of which have instituted such
notification programs on their own.
</TEXT>
