<DOCNO> AP880329-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 1721EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FCC-Murdoch 2ndLd-Writethru a0735 03-29 0980</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Murdoch, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0735,1008</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Says Congress Can't Legislate Against Murdoch on
Cross-Ownership</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf of Hollings comment after 22nd graf, He said
... today's decision.; and SUBS 26th graf pvs, The issue ...
further action., to CLARIFY that FCC barred from acting during
current fiscal year. Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress unconstitutionally singled out
publisher Rupert Murdoch by prohibiting his continued ownership of
newspapers and television stations in the same city, an appeals
court ruled Tuesday.
   A recently enacted provision barring the Federal Communications
Commission from extending temporary waivers from its
cross-ownership rule is unconstitutional because it ``strikes at
Murdoch with the precision of a laser beam'' without a legitimate
purpose, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington ruled in a
2-1 opinion.
   The law violates the the Constitution's equal protection clause
as well as the First Amendment's guarantee of freedom of the press,
the court said.
   The decision means Murdoch may petition the FCC to extend past
June 30 the waiver that allows his News American Publishing Inc. to
own both the Boston Herald and that city's WFXT-TV.
   Murdoch also had sought an extension of a waiver that allowed
him to own both the New York Post and WNYW-TV until March 6, but
the newspaper was sold earlier this month for $37 million to real
estate developer Peter Kalikow. The decision, therefore, won't
affect the Post's sale.
   Lawrence Kessler, general counsel for News America, said Murdoch
has no plans to repurchase the newspaper in light of the court's
ruling.
   The provision that banned the cross-ownership waiver extension
had been tucked quietly into a massive spending bill last December
by Sens. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., and Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
   In its ruling Tuesday, the court said the ban was so narrowly
drawn that it applied only to Murdoch _ who held the only two
waivers from the cross-ownership rule.
   The court is saying Congress ``should not enact legislation that
is aimed in a punitive way at a single individual,'' said Howard
Squadron, a New York attorney who argued the case for News America.
   ``I would think it's a benefit to all people who enjoy the First
Amendment freedom,'' Squadron said.
   Howard Rubinstein, a spokesman for both News America and
Kalikow, said News America was ``gratified'' with the court's
ruling and that Kalikow has instructed his attorneys to seek to
purchase a radio station or television station in New York City. He
would not name stations.
   Rubinstein said Kalikow will challenge the cross-ownership rule
itself because he believes the reasons for the rule no longer exist
since there are an ample number of radio and televison stations.
   The FCC, which defended the law's constitutionality but not the
policy it enacted, appeared as pleased with the decision as
Murdoch's lawyers.
   ``The court by this decision has demonstrated that the Congress
does not have a free hand in the regulation of the broadcast
press,'' FCC Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said in a statement. ``I am
pleased the court will hold the Congress to a higher standard when
First Amendment freedoms are implicated.''
   The court did not specify how the commission should rule on
Murdoch's request for an extension except to say political pressure
from Congress should ``play no role in agency adjudications
involving important constitutional rights.''
   The court found that the law had no other purpose than to
prohibit extensions of the waivers and therefore unconstitutionally
targeted a specific individual for no legitimate purpose, the court
said.
   ``Congress's exclusive focus on a single party clearly
implicates values similar to those behind the constitutional
prosription of Bills of Attainders,'' Judge Stephen Williams wrote
in an opinion joined by Judge Laurence Silberman. Bills of
attainder are aimed at specific people.
   Murdoch and some politicians had criticized the ban as an
attempt to muzzle the conservative editorial policies of the
newspapers, particularly the Herald, which repeatedly has been
critical of Kennedy.
   Kennedy and Hollings, however, said they merely were trying to
force Murdoch to comply with rules that other publishers must
observe.
   In a statement Tuesday, Kennedy said the court's decision does
not mean Murdoch should retain ownership of his Boston newspaper
and television station.
   ``Nothing in the Constitution or even the court's decision says
that Rupert Murdoch is entitled to be the only newspaper owner in
American who can buy a broadcasting station and keep his newspaper
in the same community,'' Kennedy said.
   He said he believed Congress ``will be vindicated by the Supreme
Court if the parties appeal today's decision.''
   Hollings, meanwhile, said the court ``has arrested the policeman
on the beat, while the culprit has gone free.'' He called the
decision a ``legal contortion'' that ``set up Murdoch for special
treatment.''
   While the court did not speculate on the senators' motives, it
noted the provision did not bar new temporary waivers that are
normally extended to give a company time to divest itself of a TV
station or newspaper acquired during a merger or acquisition.
   Nor did Congress mention waivers from the cross-ownership rules,
the court said.
   In dissent, Circuit Judge Spotswood Robinson said ``Congress
pursued a wholly legitimate purpose when it acted to protect the
cross-ownership rule from circumvention or erosion.''
   Even though a statute so narrowly drawn ``naturally arouses
suspicions about its legal propriety,'' Robinson concluded that
Congress ``selected a method that was more than adequately related
to the purpose it sought to achieve.''
   The issue arose last fall when the FCC was asked in a petition
to consider abolishing the cross-ownership rule. The FCC said it
would solicit comments on the idea but the law's enactment barred
the agency from taking further action during the current fiscal
year.
   Murdoch, meanwhile, has indicated he would keep the Herald and
sell his Boston TV outlet if the FCC forces him to divest one of
the properties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
