<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold Bjt   03-29 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold, Bjt,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises on Central Bank Purchases; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar surged upward Tuesday from its lowest
point since early January, responding favorably to reports of
modest efforts by central banks to support it.
   Gold prices edged higher. Republic National Bank of New York
said gold was bid at $455.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from
$455.10 late Monday.
   There were conflicting reports on the extent of intervention by
central banks, although traders agreed the Bank of Japan bought
some dollars with yen in the Tokyo market.
   The Federal Reserve Bank of New York also bought dollars
Tuesday, said David H. Arbesman, president of Kemper Currency Inc.
   The rally generated by reports of the central banks' action
squeezed out investors who had bet on further declines in the
dollar, forcing them to buy dollars to cover borrowed positions,
Arbesman said.
   Traders who bought dollars were pushing aside the concerns that
have sent the dollar lower the past several weeks. The dollar
closed Monday at its lowest levels since the first week in January
against major currencies.
   The bearish factors include ``disenchantment with anything being
really done about the budget, the fear of renewed inflation, and
the fear of another stock market collapse,'' Arbesman said.
   ``Those are all really still in the backs of people's minds, but
they're taking a back seat,'' he said.
   The dollar showed little reaction to reports Tuesday that the
government's chief economic forecasting gauge rose 0.9 percent in
February and sales of new homes shot up 20.3 percent, said David
Godwin, chief foreign exchange dealer for the Union Bank of
Switzerland in New York.
   The British pound was bolstered by rumors, later firmly denied,
that British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson had resigned
and by a statement by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher that keeping
inflation down was the government's top priority.
   Lawson, whose job is equivalent to the U.S. secretary of the
treasury, reportedly has been arguing against allowing the pound to
continue its recent rise against other currencies.
   In London, the pound rose to $1.8705 from $1.8590 Monday. Later,
in New York, the pound fell to $1.8642 from $1.8705.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar fell 0.06 yen to a closing 124.37 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 124.50 yen. At the end of the trading day in New
York, the dollar jumped to 125.26 from 123.84 late Monday.
   Other dollar rates late Tuesday in New York, compared with late
Monday, included: 1.6693 West German marks, up from 1.6562; 1.3768
Swiss francs, up from 1.3652; 1.2360 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2372; 5.6505 French francs, up from 5.6130; and 1,236 Italian
lire, up from 1,226.
   Other dollar rates late Tuesday in Europe, compared with late
Monday, included: 1.6610 West German marks, up from 1.6605; 1.3735
Swiss francs, up from 1.3705; 5.6280 French francs, up from 5.6275;
1.8690 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8685; 1,232.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,231.00; and 1.2363 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2377.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery was bid at $455.40 a troy ounce, down 40 cents from late
Monday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $454.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $454.00. In Zurich, gold was higher,
closing at a bid $455 compared with $453.50 late Monday. Earlier,
in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.21 to close at a bid $456.88.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market, where silver
traded at a late bid price of $6.69 a troy ounce, compared with
Monday's $6.63. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery was bid at $6.705 a troy ounce, up 4 cents from Monday.
</TEXT>
