<FILEID>AP-NR-03-29-88 2321EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DefunctAirline 1stLd-Writethru   03-29 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defunct Airline, 1st Ld-Writethru,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passengers Stranded By Charter Airline Closing; `Chaos' at Airport</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10 grafs for grafs 5-10 pvs, Another 6,000 ... Caro
said. UPDATING with most passengers flown out of Palma, other
arrangements and detail. Picks up 11th graf pvs, On Tuesday ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PALMA DE MAJORCA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A charter airline shut down
operations unexpectedly for lack of funds, stranding about 7,000
angry Easter vacationers in airports around Europe on Tuesday, an
official of the carrier said.
   The Spanish-based airline Spantax, which is about $88 million in
debt, closed operations after it ran out of money and couldn't find
new investors, said Pedro Caro, the carrier's director of sales.
   About 100 employees protested the shutdown by blocking entry
roads as 1,000 passengers waited anxiously for flights at Son Sant
Joan Airport in Palma, the capital of this Mediterranean island
where the company is based.
   Caro said there was ``absolute chaos'' at the airport.
   Late Tuesday, airport official Fernando Echegarray said most of
the passengers stranded on this island were able to leave on
substitute flights.
   About 6,000 passengers were expected to be stranded at other
airports in Spain, Finland, Denmark and Italy, Caro had said
earlier.
   ``There aren't enough airplanes in all of Europe to resolve
this,'' Caro said.
   He said the situation was expected to get worse this weekend at
the height of the Easter vacation boom.
   ``By Sunday I'll be hiding under the bed,'' he said.
   Echegarray said tour operators made arrangements for Palma
passengers originally scheduled to fly on seven incoming and seven
outgoing Spantax flights, all canceled Tuesday. Spantax had 30
routes.
   He said charter airlines Air Europa, Canafrica and TAE arranged
to carry Spantax passengers. Some passengers booked on a flight
from Palma to Barcelona on the Spanish mainland were to travel by
boat, Echegarray said.
   He said passengers reserved on a 6 a.m. plane Tuesday to
Helsinki were expected to reach the Finnish capital early Wednesday.
   In Madrid, a spokesman for a tour operator said 350 people
scheduled to fly Spantax to New York Tuesday were to leave
Wednesday morning on another airline.
   Earlier, Antenna 3 radio reported in Madrid that the passengers
there staged a protest after being told their flight was canceled.
   On Tuesday, Spantax chairman Wolfgang Krauss told the company's
800 employees they would not be paid at the end of the month.
   ``There's no money to keep operating and no investors,'' the
Spanish national news agency EFE quoted Krauss as saying. The
employees rejected Krauss' appeal that they work unpaid for a
48-hour period.
   According to Caro, the company's revenues totaled $150 million
in 1987.
   In 1982, 51 people died and 121 were injured when a Spantax
DC-10 crashed while taking off from the Mediterranean coastal city
of Malaga.
</TEXT>
